1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:01,040
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:01,760 --> 00:00:05,760
August 1940: The Doctor and his Daughter

3
00:00:07,920 --> 00:00:14,240
Dr Iannis had enjoyed a satisfactory day in which 
none of his patients had died or got any worse.  

4
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:19,200
He had removed a tooth, attended the 
surprisingly easy birth of a lamb,  

5
00:00:19,760 --> 00:00:23,120
and had performed a successful, 
though minor, operation.

6
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:29,920
He had been called to the house of old man 
Stamatis, who was suffering from earache.  

7
00:00:29,920 --> 00:00:35,520
After gazing into the dark, hairy hole of the 
old man's ear, the doctor had cleaned up the  

8
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:43,280
inside of the ear using a matchstick, cotton wool 
and alcohol. He was aware that old man Stamatis  

9
00:00:43,280 --> 00:00:49,200
had been deaf in that ear since childhood, but 
was nevertheless surprised when the tip of the  

10
00:00:49,200 --> 00:00:54,720
matchstick touched something hard, something 
that had no excuse for its presence there.  

11
00:00:55,840 --> 00:01:01,680
He took the old man to the window, where the light 
was better, and stared down into the ear again;  

12
00:01:02,720 --> 00:01:07,520
then with his long matchstick he 
pushed the grey hairs to one side.  

13
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:14,240
There was something round inside. He 
scratched its surface and saw a pea.  

14
00:01:15,120 --> 00:01:22,080
It was undoubtedly a pea; it was light green 
and slightly lined. Dr Iannis considered the  

15
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:27,600
problem for some moments, then requested 
a small fishhook and a light hammer.

16
00:01:28,960 --> 00:01:33,840
The old man and his wife looked at each other 
with the single thought that the doctor must  

17
00:01:33,840 --> 00:01:40,880
have lost his mind. 'What does this have to do 
with my earache?' asked Stamatis suspiciously.  

18
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:47,840
But the hook and hammer were fetched, and the 
doctor carefully placed the straightened hook  

19
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:53,840
into the hairy hole and raised the 
hammer. There was a terrible scream.

20
00:01:54,560 --> 00:02:01,200
'Oh, oh, the fishhook will enter his brain. 
May God protect us!' cried the old wife,  

21
00:02:01,200 --> 00:02:02,800
hiding her head in her hands.

22
00:02:03,760 --> 00:02:08,480
This speech caused the doctor to pause and 
consider the possibility that the hammer  

23
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:14,640
might only drive the pea further into the 
ear. 'Change of plan,' he announced, and gave  

24
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:22,320
instructions that Stamatis should lie on his side 
till evening with his ear filled with warm water.  

25
00:02:22,320 --> 00:02:27,840
He returned at six o'clock, hooked the softened 
pea successfully without the aid of a hammer,  

26
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:34,720
small or otherwise, and pulled it out. Stamatis 
clapped his hand to his ear and exclaimed,  

27
00:02:35,360 --> 00:02:41,360
'It's cold in there. My God, it's 
loud. I mean everything is loud!'

28
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:47,840
'Your deafness is cured,' announced Dr Iannis. 
'A very satisfactory operation, I think.'  

29
00:02:49,280 --> 00:02:52,640
Shortly afterwards he walked home 
with a fat chicken under each arm,  

30
00:02:53,200 --> 00:02:56,000
and an ancient pea wrapped up in his handkerchief.

31
00:02:57,360 --> 00:03:01,360
The doctor was now left with an 
entire evening in which to write his  

32
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:08,800
'New History of Cephallonia', a project which he 
had begun at least a dozen times. He seemed unable  

33
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:15,360
to achieve objectivity and so had never been 
satisfied with the result. He sat down and wrote:

34
00:03:16,640 --> 00:03:21,840
'The ancient, half-forgotten island of 
Cephallonia rises from the Ionian Sea,  

35
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:28,720
its rocks and red earth heavy with the heat 
of the sun and the weight of memory. In the  

36
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:35,360
stories of ancient Greece, the island played 
its part and had its gods - among them Poseidon,  

37
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:43,760
the god of the Sea and Apollo, the god of the Sun. 
Yes, once this island, with its brilliant light,  

38
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:50,960
its transparent waters, was an island 
filled with gods. But today Cephallonia  

39
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:57,040
has become a factory that breeds babies for 
export. There are more Cephallonians abroad  

40
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:02,400
or at sea than there are at home. There is no 
industry here that keeps families together,  

41
00:04:03,200 --> 00:04:09,600
there is not enough agricultural land, there are 
not enough fish in the ocean. Our men go abroad  

42
00:04:10,240 --> 00:04:17,680
and return here to die. The only good thing about 
it is that only the beautiful women find husbands  

43
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:23,840
among the men who are left, and consequently we 
have the most beautiful women in all of Greece...'

44
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:30,960
The doctor refilled his pipe and read this 
through. He listened to Pelagia moving about  

45
00:04:30,960 --> 00:04:36,480
in the kitchen, preparing the evening meal. He 
read what he had written about beautiful women  

46
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:42,480
and remembered his wife, who had died from 
lung disease despite all his efforts and  

47
00:04:42,480 --> 00:04:49,440
who had been as lovely as his daughter was now. 
'This island betrays its own people,' he wrote,  

48
00:04:50,080 --> 00:04:54,480
then seized the sheet of paper and threw 
it forcefully into the corner of the room.  

49
00:04:55,280 --> 00:05:01,440
This was not good enough. Why could he not 
write like a writer of histories? Why could  

50
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:06,560
he not write without passion, without anger 
at the many betrayals and oppressions that the  

51
00:05:06,560 --> 00:05:13,440
island had suffered in the past? He went outside 
for a breath of fresh air, returning indoors  

52
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:19,440
just in time to catch Pelagia's little goat eating 
his writings with a look of satisfaction on its  

53
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:26,000
face. He tore the paper from the animal's mouth, 
chased it outside, then marched into the kitchen.  

54
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:31,200
'That unpleasant animal of yours has 
eaten everything I've written tonight,'  

55
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:38,160
he exclaimed crossly. 'Any more incidents 
like this, and it'll end up on our plates.'

56
00:05:38,160 --> 00:05:43,120
Pelagia looked up at her father and smiled. 
'We'll be eating at about ten o'clock.'

57
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:50,880
'Did you hear what I said? No more goats inside 
the house.' Pelagia paused in her slicing of a  

58
00:05:50,880 --> 00:05:56,320
tomato, brushed her hair from her face and 
replied, 'You're as fond of him as I am.'

59
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:04,400
Dr Iannis turned away, defeated. It was an 
annoying thing when a daughter spoke cheekily  

60
00:06:04,400 --> 00:06:11,200
to him and reminded him of her mother at the 
same time. He returned to his table, took the  

61
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:18,240
title page, 'A New History of Cephallonia', and 
crossed out the first two words, writing instead,  

62
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:25,280
'A Personal'. Now he could express his opinions 
as freely and unpleasantly as he wished.

63
00:06:28,320 --> 00:06:32,640
When Pelagia heard from a neighbour that a 
strongman was giving a performance in the  

64
00:06:32,640 --> 00:06:38,320
village square, she put away her broom and hurried 
to join the group of curious islanders that had  

65
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:45,760
gathered there. Megalo Velisarios, famous all over 
the islands of Ionia as one of the strongest men  

66
00:06:45,760 --> 00:06:51,600
who had ever lived, was jumping up and down in 
time to the clapping of hands. On each of his  

67
00:06:51,600 --> 00:06:59,040
outstretched arms sat a full-grown man. One of 
them held on tightly to his body while the other  

68
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:06,400
calmly smoked a cigarette. On Vehsarios's head 
sat an anxious little girl of about six years,  

69
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:11,440
who was making matters more complicated by 
holding her hands firmly across his eyes.

70
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:20,320
'Lemoni!' he roared. 'Take your hands from my eyes 
and hold on to my hair, or I'll have to stop.'

71
00:07:21,600 --> 00:07:28,960
Lemoni was too frightened to move her hands and 
Megalo Velisarios stopped. With one graceful  

72
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:35,520
movement he threw both men to their feet, lifted 
Lemoni from his head, threw her high into the air  

73
00:07:35,520 --> 00:07:42,960
and caught her, kissed her dramatically upon the 
tip of her nose and set her down. Raising himself  

74
00:07:42,960 --> 00:07:49,440
to his full height, he cried, 'I will lift 
anything that it takes three men to lift.'

75
00:07:50,880 --> 00:07:56,080
The village priest, Father Arsenios, 
chose just this moment to walk with a  

76
00:07:56,080 --> 00:08:02,160
self-important expression across the square 
on his way to the church. He lacked respect,  

77
00:08:02,800 --> 00:08:08,640
not because he was completely round but 
because he was greedy for both money and food  

78
00:08:08,640 --> 00:08:11,840
and was much too interested in women.

79
00:08:13,280 --> 00:08:15,760
'Lift Father Arsenios,' someone called.

80
00:08:16,320 --> 00:08:18,560
'Impossible,' called another.

81
00:08:19,760 --> 00:08:25,680
Father Arsenios quite suddenly found himself 
grasped around his chest and lifted up on to  

82
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:32,560
the wall. He sat there speechless with surprise, 
his mouth opening and closing like a fish, and a  

83
00:08:32,560 --> 00:08:39,920
guilty silence descended. Pelagia felt her heart 
overflow with pity for the poor man. She stepped  

84
00:08:39,920 --> 00:08:47,520
forward and extended a hand to help him down, 
and the priest walked off without a word. Pelagia  

85
00:08:47,520 --> 00:08:55,120
now spoke sharply to Velisarios. She was only 
seventeen but she was proud and knew her own mind,  

86
00:08:55,680 --> 00:09:02,000
and her position as the doctor's daughter meant 
that even the men were forced to respect her. 'You  

87
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:08,720
shouldn't have done that, Velisarios,' she said. 
'It was cruel and horrible. You must apologize.'

88
00:09:09,840 --> 00:09:16,400
He looked down at her from his great height. 
This was without doubt a difficult situation.  

89
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:19,440
He thought of lifting her above his head.

90
00:09:20,800 --> 00:09:26,800
'We want to see the cannon,' called an old 
lady, and others in the crowd echoed her.

91
00:09:27,840 --> 00:09:32,640
Velisarios was immensely proud of his 
ability to raise the old Turkish cannon,  

92
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:39,280
which had the date 1739 on it and was 
much too heavy for anyone else to lift.  

93
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:46,800
He looked down at Pelagia and said, 'I'll 
apologize later, pretty one,' then announced,  

94
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:54,480
'Good people of the village, to see the cannon, 
you must bring me your old nails, your broken  

95
00:09:54,480 --> 00:10:01,120
pots, and the stones of the streets. Find me 
these things while I pack the gun with powder.'

96
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:06,240
People ran off eagerly in all 
directions to seek out these objects,  

97
00:10:06,800 --> 00:10:12,400
and the cannon was soon prepared for the 
great explosion. 'I will fire the gun  

98
00:10:12,400 --> 00:10:19,040
down the road,' said Velisarios when all was 
made ready. 'Everybody out of the way now.'

99
00:10:20,800 --> 00:10:27,040
With a theatrical expression, the enormous man put 
a match to the cannon and lifted it to his waist.  

100
00:10:28,080 --> 00:10:34,880
Silence fell. Breaths were held. There was 
a great roar as the old pots and nails burst  

101
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:43,520
from the gun... and then a long, low cry of pain. 
There was a moment of confusion and hesitation.  

102
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:47,440
People looked around at each 
other to see who had been hit,  

103
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:52,880
and Velisarios dropped his cannon and ran 
forward to a young man lying in the dust.

104
00:10:54,320 --> 00:11:00,400
Mandras later thanked Velisarios for firing at him 
as he came round the bend at the entrance to the  

105
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:06,000
village. But at the time he greatly disliked 
being carried in the arms of the strongman  

106
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:11,760
to the doctor's house and he did not enjoy 
having a bent nail removed from his shoulder.  

107
00:11:13,200 --> 00:11:20,240
What he thanked Megalo Velisarios for was that in 
the doctor's house he first set eyes on Pelagia.  

108
00:11:21,520 --> 00:11:26,480
There was a moment when he became aware that he 
was being bandaged, that a young woman's long  

109
00:11:26,480 --> 00:11:33,120
hair was brushing against his face. He opened 
his eyes and found himself gazing into a pair  

110
00:11:33,120 --> 00:11:41,840
of anxious eyes. 'At that moment,' he liked 
to say later, 'I recognized my future wife.'

111
00:11:43,280 --> 00:11:47,600
Dr Iannis put on a fresh shirt in readiness 
for his daily visit to the kapheneion,  

112
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:53,840
and stepped out into the yard. He was 
entirely unsurprised to see Mandras there,  

113
00:11:53,840 --> 00:11:59,040
talking to Pelagia. The young fisherman's 
face went red when he saw him.  

114
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:04,080
'Oh, good evening, doctor. I've 
brought you some fish,' he said.

115
00:12:05,200 --> 00:12:11,760
The doctor twisted his mouth and pretended to 
sigh. 'Mandras,' he said, 'you know perfectly  

116
00:12:11,760 --> 00:12:16,880
well that I know perfectly well that you 
have only come here to flirt with Pelagia.'

117
00:12:17,920 --> 00:12:22,240
'Flirt?' repeated the young man, attempting 
to appear both innocent and shocked.

118
00:12:23,120 --> 00:12:29,280
'Yes. Flirt. Yesterday you brought us another 
fish and then flirted with Pelagia for an hour.  

119
00:12:30,640 --> 00:12:32,800
Well, you'd better get on with it.'

120
00:12:33,760 --> 00:12:36,160
'Then I have your permission 
to talk to your daughter?'

121
00:12:36,720 --> 00:12:42,560
'Talk, talk, talk,' said Dr Iannis, waving 
his hands, and he set off for the kapheneion.

122
00:12:43,760 --> 00:12:46,640
'Your dad's a funny fellow,' 
Mandras said to Pelagia.

123
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:51,600
'There's nothing wrong with my father,' she 
exclaimed, 'and anyone who says there is gets  

124
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:57,360
a broom in the face.' She pushed the broom at him 
and he caught it and twisted it out of her grasp.  

125
00:12:58,240 --> 00:13:00,240
'Give it back,' she said laughing.

126
00:13:01,280 --> 00:13:04,240
'I'll give it back... in return for a kiss.'

127
00:13:05,600 --> 00:13:08,320
Pelagia gave the young man a flirtatious smile.

128
00:13:10,320 --> 00:13:16,080
At the kapheneion, the doctor collected his 
tiny cup of coffee and sat next to Kokolios,  

129
00:13:16,080 --> 00:13:22,240
as he always did. The coffee shop was full of 
the usual characters: the Communist Kokolios,  

130
00:13:22,240 --> 00:13:28,400
with his splendid moustache; old man 
Stamatis; Father Arsenios, round and sweating.  

131
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:32,240
'What's the news of the war?' Kokolios asked.

132
00:13:33,120 --> 00:13:35,600
The doctor twisted the ends 
of his moustache and said,  

133
00:13:36,720 --> 00:13:42,720
'Germany is taking everything, the Italians are 
behaving like fools, the French have run away,  

134
00:13:43,440 --> 00:13:49,440
the Americans have been playing ball games, the 
British have been drinking tea, the Russians  

135
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:56,080
have been sitting on their hands. Thank God we 
are out of it. Why don't we turn on the radio?'

136
00:13:57,360 --> 00:14:02,400
The large British radio in the corner of the 
room was switched on, its whistles reduced to  

137
00:14:02,400 --> 00:14:08,320
a minimum by moving it around. Just then, 
Pelagia appeared at the door, gesturing  

138
00:14:08,320 --> 00:14:14,720
urgently, greatly embarrassed by her presence 
in the men-only kapheneion. The doctor raised  

139
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:20,240
his eyes to the ceiling, put his pipe in his 
pocket and went to the door. 'What is it, girl?'

140
00:14:21,040 --> 00:14:24,320
'It's Mandras, he's fallen 
out of a tree on to a pot.'

141
00:14:25,520 --> 00:14:29,840
The doctor shook his head in disbelief and 
allowed his daughter to hurry him home.  

142
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:35,520
There, he made Mandras lie on the kitchen 
table while he removed tiny pieces of the  

143
00:14:35,520 --> 00:14:41,200
broken pot from the young man's muscular 
back. 'You're a fool,' he told his patient.

144
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:46,240
'I know, doctor,' said Mandras, biting 
his lip as another piece came out.

145
00:14:47,360 --> 00:14:50,640
'Stop being so polite. I 
know what you're planning.  

146
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:53,440
Are you going to ask her to marry you or not?'

147
00:14:55,120 --> 00:14:58,960
'Not yet, doctor. Everyone 
says there's going to be a war,  

148
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:03,040
and I don't want to leave a widow. 
You know how people treat a widow.'

149
00:15:03,760 --> 00:15:07,280
'Quite right,' said the doctor and wondered,  

150
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:13,280
as he wiped away a spot of blood, whether his body 
had ever been as beautiful as this young fool's.

151
00:15:14,800 --> 00:15:20,800
It was several hours before he returned to the 
kapheneion. When he entered, he knew immediately  

152
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:28,080
that something was wrong. Warlike music came 
from the radio and Dr Iannis was astonished to  

153
00:15:28,080 --> 00:15:34,560
see that the faces of several of the men were 
shiny with tears. 'What's going on?' he asked.

154
00:15:35,920 --> 00:15:41,680
'Those Italian pigs have sunk one of our ships 
at Tinos. And they fired on the harbour there.  

155
00:15:41,680 --> 00:15:44,720
It was full of people. On a holy day too.'

156
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:51,440
The doctor put his hands to his face and 
felt his own tears fighting to appear.  

157
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:58,400
He was possessed by a feeling of helpless 
anger. He did not stop to question whether  

158
00:15:58,400 --> 00:16:04,320
war with Italy was inevitable. Although he did 
not believe in God he found himself saying,  

159
00:16:05,520 --> 00:16:12,480
'Come on boys, we're all going to the church.' The 
men of the kapheneion rose and followed him.
 
 
 

160
00:16:16,960 --> 00:16:17,680
CHAPTER TWO

161
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:22,320
Pelagia and Mandras

162
00:16:22,320 --> 00:16:29,920
Pelagia (resting in the afternoon): Papas says 
that Mandras is going to have tiny pieces of that  

163
00:16:29,920 --> 00:16:37,600
pot in his back for the rest of his life. I like 
his body, what I've seen of it. God forgive me,  

164
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:44,160
I have such wicked thoughts. Thank God no 
one can read my mind, or I'd be locked up  

165
00:16:44,160 --> 00:16:51,920
and all the old women would throw stones at me. 
I wonder what Mandras is doing. He's so beautiful  

166
00:16:51,920 --> 00:16:57,360
and so tunny too. He made my stomach ache 
with laughing before he fell out of the tree.  

167
00:16:58,320 --> 00:17:03,840
That's when I knew I loved him; it was 
the fear I felt when he fell on the pot.

168
00:17:04,800 --> 00:17:11,280
When will he ask me to marry him? But he's 
not a serious fellow, and it gives me doubts.  

169
00:17:12,320 --> 00:17:17,840
He's so funny, but I can't talk to him about 
anything and you have to be able to discuss  

170
00:17:17,840 --> 00:17:24,560
things with a husband, don't you? I say, 'Is there 
going to be a war?' and he just grins and says,  

171
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:32,000
'Who cares? Is there going to be a kiss?' 
I don't want there to be a war. Let there  

172
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:38,480
be Mandras standing in the yard with a fish in his 
hands. Let there be Mandras every day with a fish.

173
00:17:40,720 --> 00:17:47,760
Mandras (leaving the harbour in his boat): It's 
going to be too hot again today, I know it,  

174
00:17:48,320 --> 00:17:55,040
and all the fish will hide in the rocks and 
go to the bottom. Let the clouds hide the sun,  

175
00:17:55,040 --> 00:18:01,200
let me catch some fine fish and I'll take one 
to Pelagia and she'll ask me to eat with them,  

176
00:18:01,200 --> 00:18:06,160
and I can rub her leg with my foot under the 
table while the doctor discusses ancient poetry.  

177
00:18:07,120 --> 00:18:14,240
I know he likes me, but he doesn't think I'm good 
enough for her - he's always calling me a fool.

178
00:18:14,240 --> 00:18:21,840
The trouble is that I can't be myself when I'm 
with her. I mean, I am a serious man. I follow  

179
00:18:21,840 --> 00:18:28,640
politics, I want to improve the world. But 
when I'm with Pelagia it's as if I'm twelve  

180
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:35,680
again. I want to amuse her and what else am I 
supposed to do? I can't imagine myself saying,  

181
00:18:36,240 --> 00:18:41,840
'Come on, Pelagia, let's talk about politics.' 
Women aren't interested in that sort of thing,  

182
00:18:42,560 --> 00:18:47,280
they want you to entertain them. 
Perhaps she thinks I'm a fool as well.  

183
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:54,080
I'm not in her class, I know that. The doctor 
taught her Italian and a bit of English,  

184
00:18:54,080 --> 00:18:59,440
and they're not a typical island family. I 
mean, the doctor's sailed all over the world,  

185
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:05,040
he's even been to America. And 
where have I been? What do I know?  

186
00:19:06,160 --> 00:19:11,680
I love Pelagia, but I know that I will never 
be a man until I've done something important,  

187
00:19:12,320 --> 00:19:19,120
something people can respect me for. I feel so 
useless and insignificant here on the island.

188
00:19:21,120 --> 00:19:29,120
Pelagia (taking roast lamb from the village 
oven): Where is Mandras? He's usually here by now.  

189
00:19:29,840 --> 00:19:35,920
I want him to come, I can hardly breathe, I 
want him so much. My hands are shaking again.

190
00:19:36,720 --> 00:19:40,880
I'd better take this silly smile off 
my face or everyone will think I'm mad.  

191
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:47,520
Come, Mandras, please come, stay for dinner 
and stroke my ankles with your feet, Mandras.

192
00:19:48,880 --> 00:19:54,560
Mandras (mending his nets): We're going 
to go to war with Italy very soon.  

193
00:19:55,360 --> 00:19:59,360
I've got a letter saying that I'll be ordered 
to join the army in the next few weeks.  

194
00:20:00,560 --> 00:20:04,560
I know one thing, I'm going to ask 
Pelagia to marry me before I leave.  

195
00:20:05,360 --> 00:20:12,080
With no jokes. I'm going to make her understand 
that in defending Greece I'm defending her  

196
00:20:12,080 --> 00:20:18,560
and every woman like her, and if I die, I'll die 
with the name of Pelagia and the name of Greece  

197
00:20:18,560 --> 00:20:25,040
equally on my lips. And if I live, I'll walk 
with my head held high for the rest of my life,  

198
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:34,320
and everyone will say, 'That's Mandras, who fought 
in the war. We owe everything to people like him.'

199
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:40,800
The island's saint, St Geronimos, dead for 
five centuries, had lived a genuinely holy  

200
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:45,920
life and had left his ancient blackened body 
in an island church as evidence of this.  

201
00:20:47,200 --> 00:20:54,160
He was so loved by the islanders that he had two 
feast days, one in August and another in October,  

202
00:20:54,800 --> 00:21:01,440
and on these days he tolerantly looked elsewhere 
as the population of the island became excessively  

203
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:06,800
drunk. It was eight days before Greece 
and Italy declared war on each other,  

204
00:21:07,440 --> 00:21:11,040
but it might have been any October 
feast day in the last hundred years.  

205
00:21:12,160 --> 00:21:16,000
The cruelty had gone out of the 
sun, and the delightfully warm day  

206
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:21,600
was made even more pleasant by a light wind from 
the sea that wandered in and out of the trees.  

207
00:21:22,960 --> 00:21:27,120
From all over the island, people made their 
way to the church where the saint's body lay,  

208
00:21:27,760 --> 00:21:31,440
packing the church tightly and 
squeezing together in the yard outside.  

209
00:21:32,400 --> 00:21:38,720
At different points in the crowd, 
Velisarios, Pelagia, Dr Iannis, Kokolios  

210
00:21:39,280 --> 00:21:44,640
and Stamatis all turned their heads sideways 
to hear the distant prayers of the priest.  

211
00:21:46,160 --> 00:21:53,520
The sun climbed higher and the people, packed 
together, began to sweat. The heat was just  

212
00:21:53,520 --> 00:21:59,680
becoming unbearable when the service ended, 
the bells rang out and the celebrations began.

213
00:22:01,040 --> 00:22:06,560
A small band began playing while a line of pretty 
girls stepped from side to side at the back,  

214
00:22:06,560 --> 00:22:09,920
and a row of young men danced with 
their heads twisted backwards.  

215
00:22:10,960 --> 00:22:17,120
Those who were drunk began to insult each other, 
and in some places fighting had already begun.  

216
00:22:18,640 --> 00:22:21,440
Pelagia moved nearer the 
church and sat on a bench.  

217
00:22:22,560 --> 00:22:29,520
Someone tapped on her shoulder and she looked up 
and saw Mandras. He fell drunkenly to his knees  

218
00:22:29,520 --> 00:22:36,880
and declared dramatically, 'Pelagia, 
will you marry me? Marry me or I die!'

219
00:22:38,400 --> 00:22:43,920
She regarded him silently for a moment, then 
said quietly, 'Of course I'll marry you,'  

220
00:22:45,040 --> 00:22:50,240
When he heard this, Mandras leapt 
joyfully but unsteadily into the air,  

221
00:22:50,240 --> 00:22:56,720
then suddenly became extremely serious and 
said, 'My darling, I love you with all my heart,  

222
00:22:57,600 --> 00:23:00,480
but we can't get married until 
I get back from the Army.'

223
00:23:01,520 --> 00:23:07,680
'Go and speak to my father,' said Pelagia. Then, 
worried by the strange way in which she did not  

224
00:23:07,680 --> 00:23:13,440
feel as happy as she ought, she made her way back 
to the church in order to be alone with the saint.  

225
00:23:14,800 --> 00:23:19,680
Time passed, and Mandras failed to find 
the doctor before drink overcame him.  

226
00:23:20,560 --> 00:23:27,440
He slept sweetly in a pool of something 
disgusting but unidentifiable, while, nearby,  

227
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:31,920
Lemoni attempted to set fire to the 
beard of the sleeping Father Arsenios,  

228
00:23:32,480 --> 00:23:37,200
and Kokolios and Stamatis became lost in 
the bushes while searching for their wives.

229
00:23:38,720 --> 00:23:42,320
Pelagia walked back from the feast 
with her father, bursting with a  

230
00:23:42,320 --> 00:23:47,680
painful mixture of anxiety and happiness, 
desperate to mention Mandras's proposal.  

231
00:23:48,720 --> 00:23:54,240
But the doctor was in a much too drunken state 
to be sensitive to his daughter's feelings, and  

232
00:23:54,240 --> 00:23:59,600
when they reached the house, he danced about the 
yard before falling onto his bed fully clothed.

233
00:24:00,960 --> 00:24:08,160
Pelagia went to bed and could not sleep. 'I love 
you, Mandras,' she declared, at the same time  

234
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:14,800
as doubts rose in her like an invasion of tiny 
devils. How much did she really know Mandras?  

235
00:24:15,600 --> 00:24:22,640
What evidence did she have that he was patient 
and kind? Can you trust someone who replies  

236
00:24:22,640 --> 00:24:28,880
immediately, without thought? She was frightened 
by the suspicion that there was something hard  

237
00:24:28,880 --> 00:24:35,440
about his heart. If it were not love that she 
felt for Mandras, then why this breathlessness,  

238
00:24:35,440 --> 00:24:42,800
this endless desire that made her heart beat 
fast? She imagined that Mandras had died, and  

239
00:24:42,800 --> 00:24:48,400
as the tears came she was shocked to 
discover that she also felt relief.

240
00:24:50,080 --> 00:24:54,240
In the morning she took herself to 
the yard and created tasks that would  

241
00:24:54,240 --> 00:24:57,520
cause her to see him as soon as he 
came around the curve of the road.  

242
00:24:58,400 --> 00:25:03,120
But he did not come, and Pelagia passed 
the day with feelings of impatience  

243
00:25:03,680 --> 00:25:10,640
that soon turned into real concern. That evening, 
when he had still not appeared, her father said,  

244
00:25:10,640 --> 00:25:16,080
quite unexpectedly, 'I expect he hasn't come 
because he's feeling as sick as everyone else.'

245
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:19,440
Pelagia took his hand and kissed it gratefully.  

246
00:25:20,320 --> 00:25:24,720
'He's asked me to marry him. I told 
him I'd have to ask you,' she said.

247
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:29,200
'I don't want to marry Mandras,' said Dr Iannis.  

248
00:25:29,200 --> 00:25:32,240
'It would be a much better idea 
if he married you, I think.'

249
00:25:33,600 --> 00:25:35,360
'Don't you approve of him, Papakis?'

250
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:41,000
He turned and looked at her 
gently. 'He's too young. Also,  

251
00:25:41,760 --> 00:25:48,000
I have not done you a favour. You read poetry, 
you speak Italian. He isn't your equal,  

252
00:25:48,640 --> 00:25:55,120
and he would expect to be better than his wife. 
He is a man, after all. I have often thought that  

253
00:25:55,120 --> 00:26:00,960
you would only ever be able to marry happily with 
a foreigner, a dentist from Norway or something.'

254
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:06,080
Pelagia laughed at the ridiculous 
thought, then closed her eyes.  

255
00:26:07,200 --> 00:26:12,000
The doctor went inside and came out with 
something that he handed very formally to her.  

256
00:26:12,560 --> 00:26:18,000
She took it, saw what it was, and dropped 
it into her skirts with a cry of horror.

257
00:26:19,200 --> 00:26:25,680
The doctor remained standing. 'There's going to 
be a war, and terrible things happen in wars,  

258
00:26:26,240 --> 00:26:32,320
especially to women. Use the gun to defend 
yourself. It might happen that your marriage  

259
00:26:32,320 --> 00:26:37,840
will have to wait. We must make sure first that 
Mussolini does not invite himself to the wedding.'  

260
00:26:39,200 --> 00:26:45,520
He turned and went into the house, leaving Pelagia 
to her fears, and after a few minutes she went to  

261
00:26:45,520 --> 00:26:51,840
her room and placed the gun under her pillow, 
imagining once again that Mandras was dead.

262
00:26:52,800 --> 00:26:57,840
It was not until the third day after 
the feast that there was a quiet knock  

263
00:26:57,840 --> 00:27:03,200
at the door. Mandras stood, speaking 
fast, a bucket of fish in his hand.  

264
00:27:04,080 --> 00:27:08,400
'I'm sorry I didn't come sooner, but 
I was ill the day after the feast,  

265
00:27:08,400 --> 00:27:14,160
and yesterday I had to collect my Army papers, 
and I'm leaving for Athens the day after tomorrow,  

266
00:27:14,160 --> 00:27:20,320
and I've spoken to your father, and he's agreed 
to the marriage, and I've brought you some fish.'

267
00:27:20,320 --> 00:27:27,680
Pelagia sat on her bed and went cold inside; 
it was too much happiness, too much pain.  

268
00:27:28,640 --> 00:27:32,560
She was engaged to a man who mixed 
marriage together with fish and war,  

269
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:40,240
a man who was too beautiful to go away and die in 
the snows of Tsamoria. Suddenly Mandras seemed to  

270
00:27:40,240 --> 00:27:48,160
her to be an extraordinarily delicate creature, 
so delicate and beautiful that he was sure to die.  

271
00:27:48,160 --> 00:27:53,680
Her hands began to shake and she 
whispered, 'Don't go, don't go.'
 
 
 

272
00:27:58,240 --> 00:27:59,040
CHAPTER THREE

273
00:28:00,080 --> 00:28:01,840
The Homosexual

274
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:08,480
I, Carlo Piero Guercio, write these 
words with the intention that they  

275
00:28:08,480 --> 00:28:13,280
should be found after my death, when 
what is written here will not harm me.

276
00:28:14,560 --> 00:28:21,840
I know only silence. I have not told the priest, 
since I know in advance what I will be told;  

277
00:28:22,720 --> 00:28:30,160
it is a wicked sin and I must marry and lead the 
life of a normal man. Nor have I told a doctor,  

278
00:28:30,160 --> 00:28:34,560
as I know that I will be informed that I 
am sick and can be cured of my disease.

279
00:28:35,520 --> 00:28:40,480
What could I say to such priests and 
doctors? I would say to the priest that  

280
00:28:40,480 --> 00:28:46,320
God made me like this for a purpose, that 
I had no choice. I would say to the doctor,  

281
00:28:46,960 --> 00:28:52,320
'I have been like this from the start, it is 
nature that has created me.' But they would  

282
00:28:52,320 --> 00:29:00,000
not understand. I am like someone who is the only 
person in the world that knows the truth, but is  

283
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:06,640
forbidden to speak. And this truth weighs more 
than the universe, this burden cracks my bones.

284
00:29:08,720 --> 00:29:14,160
In my search to understand myself, I have 
read everything, from the most modern to  

285
00:29:14,160 --> 00:29:19,360
the most ancient, and it was in the work 
of the ancient Greek philosopher, Plato,  

286
00:29:19,360 --> 00:29:26,480
that I finally found myself. In his writings, 
he explained that there were three sexes,  

287
00:29:27,040 --> 00:29:35,120
the third sex being men who loved men, and 
this idea made sense to me. Plato also wrote  

288
00:29:35,120 --> 00:29:40,480
that if an army was made up of men who loved 
one another, they would be the bravest army  

289
00:29:40,480 --> 00:29:45,840
in the world, because men would become 
heroes, ready to die for their lovers.

290
00:29:46,960 --> 00:29:53,040
I admit that I joined the Army because the men are 
young and beautiful, and because I knew that in  

291
00:29:53,040 --> 00:30:00,640
the Army I would find someone I could love though 
never touch. I would not abandon him in battle,  

292
00:30:01,280 --> 00:30:09,360
I would win his admiration, I would die for him if 
necessary and in this way give purpose to my life.

293
00:30:10,960 --> 00:30:19,200
In the Army I found my family. It was a world 
without women, and for the first time in my life  

294
00:30:19,200 --> 00:30:26,640
I did not have to pretend. I was very fortunate 
at first; our unit was sent to Albania,  

295
00:30:26,640 --> 00:30:32,160
where there was no real fighting, and we did not 
realize that we might be ordered to invade Greece.  

296
00:30:33,440 --> 00:30:40,080
No one outside the Army can understand the joy 
of being a soldier, of being part of a group  

297
00:30:40,080 --> 00:30:44,800
where you are all young and strong and 
quickly learn everything about each other.  

298
00:30:45,520 --> 00:30:51,440
We believed we could not die, we could march 
eighty kilometres a day, singing battle songs.  

299
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:56,480
We were new and beautiful, we loved 
each other more than brothers.

300
00:30:58,400 --> 00:31:05,280
I fell in love with Francesco, a young married 
soldier from Genoa, who accepted me as his best  

301
00:31:05,280 --> 00:31:12,160
friend without ever suspecting my passion 
for him. He was an entirely beautiful boy,  

302
00:31:12,800 --> 00:31:19,440
reminding me of one of those elegant cats that 
give the impression of immense but easy strength.  

303
00:31:20,880 --> 00:31:27,440
I was attracted most of all to his face, 
with its strong, high cheekbones, wide mouth  

304
00:31:27,440 --> 00:31:32,880
and one-sided smile. He was always 
amusing and respected no one,  

305
00:31:32,880 --> 00:31:38,160
constantly entertaining us with his wickedly 
accurate imitations of Mussolini and Hitler.  

306
00:31:38,880 --> 00:31:43,520
Everyone loved him, he never got 
a promotion and he did not care.

307
00:31:45,040 --> 00:31:52,240
We soldiers loved the army life but had no love 
of the Fascist leaders of our country, nor did we  

308
00:31:52,240 --> 00:32:00,240
have any idea of why we were in Albania. However, 
looking back, it seems clear that an invasion of  

309
00:32:00,240 --> 00:32:07,360
Greece must have been the final intention; there 
were clues everywhere, if only we had seen them.  

310
00:32:08,560 --> 00:32:14,880
In the first place, there was the fact that all 
the roads that we built (which, we were informed,  

311
00:32:14,880 --> 00:32:21,600
were for the benefit of the Albanians) led 
towards the Greek border. In the second place,  

312
00:32:21,600 --> 00:32:27,600
we heard stories from reliable sources about 
how our frontier posts were attacked a number  

313
00:32:27,600 --> 00:32:33,520
of times by our own people dressed as Greeks, so 
that we could blame the latter for the attacks.  

314
00:32:34,800 --> 00:32:40,080
When some Albanians shot at our soldiers, 
we announced that our attackers were Greeks.  

315
00:32:41,200 --> 00:32:44,960
We also learned that one of our 
leaders arranged to have his own  

316
00:32:44,960 --> 00:32:49,760
offices blown up so that Mussolini could 
finally declare war against the Greeks.

317
00:32:50,960 --> 00:32:57,200
I have related these things as if they were 
amusing, but really they were acts of madness.  

318
00:32:58,240 --> 00:33:03,200
When war against Greece was finally declared, 
we were told that the Greeks would be defeated  

319
00:33:03,200 --> 00:33:12,480
within days. We were sent off to die, with no 
transport, no equipment and too few men. At first,  

320
00:33:12,480 --> 00:33:18,960
having no idea of what the future held for us, 
we whistled and sang, and from time to time  

321
00:33:18,960 --> 00:33:25,280
Francesco, marching beside me, looked at me 
and smiled. 'Athens in two weeks,' he said.

322
00:33:26,640 --> 00:33:33,440
Then the weather turned against us and rain 
poured from the skies, turning the ground to mud  

323
00:33:33,440 --> 00:33:39,360
so that we struggled through it, ten thousand 
men whose uniforms were weighted down with water,  

324
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:46,720
our aeroplanes unable to fly because of the bad 
weather. Our twenty heavy guns sank into the mud,  

325
00:33:47,360 --> 00:33:53,120
and our animals were unable to pull them out. We 
struggled on in these conditions for several days,  

326
00:33:53,760 --> 00:33:58,960
at a height of three hundred metres, 
our legs turned to ice so that we  

327
00:33:58,960 --> 00:34:05,840
could no longer feel our feet. 'Athens in two 
months,' said Francesco with a twisted smile.  

328
00:34:06,720 --> 00:34:11,120
But we saw no sign of the Greeks and believed 
that we were winning without fighting.

329
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:19,520
On 1 November, a bomb fell among us and there was 
a scream as a poor fellow from Piedmont lost his  

330
00:34:19,520 --> 00:34:26,160
legs, followed by the short, sharp sound of 
gunshot from the trees. We realized that the  

331
00:34:26,160 --> 00:34:31,680
Greeks had cleverly got us into a position where 
we could be surrounded and cut off from all help.  

332
00:34:32,640 --> 00:34:38,560
We were trapped in the valley floor and the 
Greeks, whom we very rarely saw, moved like  

333
00:34:38,560 --> 00:34:44,080
ghosts among the upper slopes, so that we never 
knew when we would be attacked or from where.  

334
00:34:45,200 --> 00:34:51,040
Their bombs seemed at one moment to come from 
behind, at another moment to come from the side or  

335
00:34:51,040 --> 00:34:58,960
from the front. We fired at ghosts and at mountain 
goats. The heroic Greeks seemed to rise out of the  

336
00:34:58,960 --> 00:35:06,000
ground and fall on us as if we had raped their 
mothers. It shocked us. We had no air support.  

337
00:35:07,200 --> 00:35:12,800
'Athens in two years,' said 
Francesco. We were completely alone.

338
00:35:13,840 --> 00:35:19,360
We ate only dry biscuits, but 
when our horses died, we ate them.  

339
00:35:20,320 --> 00:35:25,360
We were ordered to turn back and had to fight 
our way through the soldiers that surrounded us.  

340
00:35:26,240 --> 00:35:30,880
We grew immense beards, we 
were half buried in snowstorms,  

341
00:35:30,880 --> 00:35:37,440
our red, swollen eyes sank deep into our 
heads, our hands were torn as if by cats.  

342
00:35:38,800 --> 00:35:43,840
We became desperately thin, digging for 
food in the frozen ground like pigs.  

343
00:35:44,800 --> 00:35:50,640
It was a hell of machine guns, bombs and ice, 
a hell in which battles were fought without  

344
00:35:50,640 --> 00:35:57,040
rest for eight hours at a time, while on the 
mountains our dead lay in forgotten piles, body  

345
00:35:57,040 --> 00:36:03,920
upon body. We fought on but we lost our hearts 
as a great darkness settled across the land.  

346
00:36:04,720 --> 00:36:10,640
The snow fell endlessly. My boots, 
crawling with insects, fell apart.  

347
00:36:11,600 --> 00:36:17,760
I think it must have been December when we 
understood that we were as broken as our boots.

348
00:36:19,120 --> 00:36:26,800
Waking up in the morning, ten degrees below zero. 
The first question: who has frozen to death now?  

349
00:36:27,680 --> 00:36:34,240
Who has slipped from sleep to death? 
These were the days of the white death,  

350
00:36:34,240 --> 00:36:39,840
in which the legs became swollen and turned 
bright purple, deep blue, coal black.  

351
00:36:41,280 --> 00:36:47,760
I was exhausted, shaken by the screams of men in 
unimaginable pain as their legs were cut off by  

352
00:36:47,760 --> 00:36:53,840
our army doctors. I lived in fear of the white 
death and inspected my feet every few hours.  

353
00:36:55,200 --> 00:37:02,720
Francesco was undoubtedly mad. His mouth moved 
continually, his beard became a column of ice,  

354
00:37:02,720 --> 00:37:09,680
his eyes rolled in his head and he did not 
recognize me. We had lost four thousand men.  

355
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:14,560
There was nothing in our 
lives except the white death,  

356
00:37:15,200 --> 00:37:22,320
the bitter absence of our friends, 
the joylessness of the icy mountains.

357
00:37:22,320 --> 00:37:27,200
One morning Francesco turned to me with a wild 
expression in his eyes, speaking to me for the  

358
00:37:27,200 --> 00:37:34,400
first time in weeks. 'Look,' he said and rolled 
up his trousers, revealing the purple stripes  

359
00:37:34,400 --> 00:37:39,520
on the white flesh. He touched the dead 
flesh with a look of horror in his eyes,  

360
00:37:40,480 --> 00:37:46,560
rolled his trousers back down again and said 
to me, 'It's enough, Carlo. It's too much.'  

361
00:37:47,840 --> 00:37:55,920
He began to weep, trembling all over. Then he 
took up his gun and, before I could prevent him,  

362
00:37:56,560 --> 00:38:04,400
advanced towards the enemy, stopping to fire 
every five steps. In recognition of his heroism,  

363
00:38:04,960 --> 00:38:11,920
the Greeks did not return his fire, but a bomb 
fell next to him and he disappeared beneath a  

364
00:38:11,920 --> 00:38:20,000
shower of mud. There was a long silence. I 
saw something move where Francesco had been.

365
00:38:21,360 --> 00:38:25,600
I put my gun down and ran 
towards the place where he lay.  

366
00:38:26,640 --> 00:38:32,720
The Greeks did not shoot at me and I saw that 
although the side of his head had been blown away,  

367
00:38:33,680 --> 00:38:40,880
he was still alive. I knelt and 
gathered him into my arms, then stood up  

368
00:38:40,880 --> 00:38:47,760
and faced the Greeks, offering myself to 
their guns. There was a silence, and then  

369
00:38:48,480 --> 00:38:54,000
a cheer came from them. I turned and carried 
the bleeding bundle back to our side.

370
00:38:55,600 --> 00:39:04,000
Francesco took two hours to die. His blood ran 
down my uniform, his mouth formed silent words,  

371
00:39:05,040 --> 00:39:12,000
the light in his eyes faded and he began the 
long, slow journey towards death, suffering  

372
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:20,880
what must have been indescribable pain. I buried 
him in a deep hole, the home of enormous rats.

373
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:28,880
We lost the war and were saved only when the 
Germans invaded from Bulgaria, forcing the  

374
00:39:28,880 --> 00:39:36,480
Greeks to fight two different armies at the same 
time. We fought and froze and died for no purpose.  

375
00:39:37,760 --> 00:39:42,960
I took no part in the shameful conquest of 
Greece because the day after I buried Francesco,  

376
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:46,480
I shot myself in the flesh of my thigh.
 
 
 

377
00:39:50,960 --> 00:39:51,680
CHAPTER FOUR

378
00:39:52,400 --> 00:39:53,360
The Wild Man

379
00:39:54,800 --> 00:39:59,600
On 28 October, Greece and Italy 
formally declared war on each other.  

380
00:40:00,400 --> 00:40:05,920
All the young men of Cephallonia disappeared to 
join the army, and Dr Iannis attempted to join too  

381
00:40:06,480 --> 00:40:11,440
but was turned down when it was discovered that 
he had learned all his medical knowledge on ships  

382
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:18,160
and had no proper qualifications. Several 
Italian families on the island were attacked  

383
00:40:18,160 --> 00:40:23,520
and their houses were burnt down, and the 
islanders developed a silent, sorrowful  

384
00:40:23,520 --> 00:40:27,920
expression as they learnt to live with the 
thought that their sons and brothers might die.  

385
00:40:29,280 --> 00:40:34,960
As the weeks passed, however, they were comforted 
by the news that their country was winning the war  

386
00:40:34,960 --> 00:40:41,040
and that the Greeks were winning back territory 
that was theirs by right in Albania. The villagers  

387
00:40:41,040 --> 00:40:48,080
went often to church and Father Arsenios surprised 
them by making fine, emotional speeches and by  

388
00:40:48,080 --> 00:40:55,360
not getting drunk. Almost immediately, shortages 
of certain foods and other household essentials  

389
00:40:55,360 --> 00:41:00,240
developed, and beans became the greater 
part of the doctor's and Pelagia's diet.

390
00:41:01,520 --> 00:41:06,160
The war had the effect of increasing the 
importance of Dr Iannis, as the village  

391
00:41:06,160 --> 00:41:12,080
community turned to him for advice and leadership. 
The doctor watched his daughter progress through  

392
00:41:12,080 --> 00:41:20,080
a series of emotions, all of which seemed to him 
to be unhealthy and worrying. At first Pelagia had  

393
00:41:20,080 --> 00:41:27,600
been in a state of painful anxiety, and then in 
storms of tears. She would sit by the wall outside  

394
00:41:27,600 --> 00:41:31,920
as if she expected her fiance to arrive at 
the bend of the road where he had been shot  

395
00:41:31,920 --> 00:41:37,840
by Velisarios. Later, she developed the habit of 
remaining silently in the room with her father,  

396
00:41:38,640 --> 00:41:43,600
her hands motionless in her lap as tears 
followed each other silently down her cheeks.  

397
00:41:45,040 --> 00:41:50,400
Pelagia calmed her fears by writing letter 
after letter to Mandras, relating island  

398
00:41:50,400 --> 00:41:56,720
news and gossip, telling him about her terrible 
dreams and her fears for him, and begging him to  

399
00:41:56,720 --> 00:42:02,880
write back to her. She began the task of making 
a cover for their marriage bed, but lacked the  

400
00:42:02,880 --> 00:42:09,600
benefit of a mothers instruction in such matters. 
Each time it reached a certain stage, it began to  

401
00:42:09,600 --> 00:42:15,840
look suspiciously like a dead animal, and she 
felt forced to undo her work and begin again.

402
00:42:17,360 --> 00:42:24,400
As day followed day it became clear that not only 
had Mandras not written, but that he never would.  

403
00:42:25,680 --> 00:42:31,440
After careful observation of his daughter, her 
father realized that she was becoming bitter  

404
00:42:31,440 --> 00:42:37,680
and increasingly certain that her fiance 
could not love her. When he realized that  

405
00:42:37,680 --> 00:42:42,800
Pelagia was seriously depressed, the doctor 
made her accompany him on his medical visits,  

406
00:42:43,520 --> 00:42:46,640
sent her to bed early and let 
her sleep in the mornings.  

407
00:42:48,240 --> 00:42:53,440
He made a habit of making her laugh against her 
will, and deliberately made her angry by such  

408
00:42:53,440 --> 00:42:59,680
tricks as moving all the knives from one drawer 
to another. The doctor considered the return of  

409
00:42:59,680 --> 00:43:04,720
her normal cheerful manner to be a sign that 
she had given up her passion for Mandras.  

410
00:43:05,760 --> 00:43:11,680
On the one hand, he was glad of this, since 
he did not truly believe that Mandras would  

411
00:43:11,680 --> 00:43:16,880
make a good husband, but on the other 
hand, Pelagia was already engaged,  

412
00:43:17,440 --> 00:43:24,800
and the breaking of an engagement would cause 
great shame. The awful possibility occurred to him  

413
00:43:24,800 --> 00:43:29,920
that Pelagia might marry a man she no 
longer loved out of a sense of duty.

414
00:43:31,920 --> 00:43:37,280
Pelagia returned from the village with a jar of 
water upon her shoulder, set it down in the yard  

415
00:43:37,280 --> 00:43:44,560
and came through the door, singing. The news had 
been bad for some weeks - not only had Kokolios  

416
00:43:44,560 --> 00:43:51,040
lost two of his sons, but the Germans had attacked 
the Greek army so that the courageous Greek troops  

417
00:43:51,040 --> 00:43:58,160
were at last facing defeat. Strangely, the bad 
news made Pelagia even more appreciative of  

418
00:43:58,160 --> 00:44:04,720
the first signs of spring on the island. She was 
feeling strong and whole and was enjoying having  

419
00:44:04,720 --> 00:44:09,920
the house to herself while her father was away 
visiting a friend on the other side of the island.

420
00:44:11,360 --> 00:44:15,200
Pelagia's singing was brought to a 
sudden stop when she entered the kitchen.  

421
00:44:16,080 --> 00:44:22,320
There was a stranger seated at the kitchen 
table, a most wild and horrible stranger,  

422
00:44:22,320 --> 00:44:28,480
whose hands trembled ceaselessly and whose 
head was utterly hidden beneath a mass of dirt,  

423
00:44:28,480 --> 00:44:36,160
mud and hair. An enormous beard hid the lower 
half of the stranger's face, in which Pelagia  

424
00:44:36,160 --> 00:44:42,800
could see only two tiny bright eyes that would 
not look at her. Rags covered the stranger's  

425
00:44:42,800 --> 00:44:49,840
body and in the place of shoes there were 
bandages, stained with blood both old and new.

426
00:44:51,440 --> 00:44:56,080
Overcome with fear and pity, not 
knowing what to do, Pelagia said,  

427
00:44:57,200 --> 00:45:00,160
'My father's out. He should be back tomorrow.'

428
00:45:01,760 --> 00:45:09,680
'You're happy, anyway. Singing,' said the man 
in a cracked voice, and his whole body shook.

429
00:45:10,960 --> 00:45:14,480
'You can't stay, I'm on my own,' said Pelagia.

430
00:45:15,680 --> 00:45:20,240
'I can't walk,' replied the 
man. 'I walked from Epirus.  

431
00:45:21,120 --> 00:45:26,800
No boots.' Just then, the goat 
wandered through the open kitchen door,  

432
00:45:27,440 --> 00:45:33,560
approached the stranger and made a gentle 
attempt at tasting the stranger's rags. 'Ah,  

433
00:45:35,840 --> 00:45:41,440
at least your goat remembers me,' 
the man whispered, and began to weep.

434
00:45:42,880 --> 00:45:47,200
Pelagia was astonished by these 
words and said, 'Mandras?'

435
00:45:48,480 --> 00:45:50,720
The man turned his face towards her and said,  

436
00:45:51,760 --> 00:45:57,680
'Don't touch me, Pelagia. There are insects 
crawling all over me and I smell terrible.'

437
00:45:59,120 --> 00:46:02,960
Pelagia felt guilt, pity, disgust.  

438
00:46:04,080 --> 00:46:12,240
It seemed unimaginable that this pitiful ghost hid 
the mind and body of the man she loved. 'You never  

439
00:46:12,240 --> 00:46:18,240
wrote to me,' she said, making the accusation that 
had destroyed her love for him and left her empty.

440
00:46:19,360 --> 00:46:25,520
Mandras replied, 'I can't write.' 
For a reason she did not understand,  

441
00:46:25,520 --> 00:46:32,080
Pelagia was more disgusted by this confession 
than by Mandras's physical condition. 'Couldn't  

442
00:46:32,080 --> 00:46:38,640
someone else have written for you? I thought you 
were dead. I thought you... couldn't love me.'

443
00:46:40,080 --> 00:46:45,680
'How could I let everyone know? How could 
I have my feelings discussed by the boys?'  

444
00:46:46,720 --> 00:46:51,200
He glanced up again so that at last 
she recognized his eyes, and said,  

445
00:46:52,160 --> 00:47:00,160
'Pelagia, I got all your letters. I couldn't read 
them but I got them.' From inside his clothing  

446
00:47:00,160 --> 00:47:07,120
he drew out a huge, dirty packet. 'I carried 
you in here,' he said, beating his chest.  

447
00:47:08,080 --> 00:47:15,840
'Every day, all the time, I was thinking of you, 
talking to you. I was not a coward because of you,  

448
00:47:15,840 --> 00:47:21,760
I even prayed to you. And when the Germans 
attacked us I got through their lines, and  

449
00:47:21,760 --> 00:47:28,400
all I could think of was that I had to get home 
to you, and now...' His body shook as he wept.  

450
00:47:29,440 --> 00:47:32,720
'Now only the animals know me.'

451
00:47:34,560 --> 00:47:40,800
'I'll fetch your mother,' Pelagia whispered and 
ran out of the house, down to the small, fishy  

452
00:47:40,800 --> 00:47:46,720
but extremely clean house by the harbour where 
Kyria Drosoula, Mandras's widowed mother, lived.  

453
00:47:47,840 --> 00:47:53,680
Kyria Drosoula was a woman so large and ugly 
that at their first meeting people wondered  

454
00:47:53,680 --> 00:47:59,040
how she had ever found a husband. 
She was in fact a brave, kind woman,  

455
00:47:59,600 --> 00:48:04,160
and during Mandras's absence she and 
Pelagia had comforted one another.

456
00:48:05,120 --> 00:48:08,880
Now the two women returned, 
breathless, to the doctor's house,  

457
00:48:08,880 --> 00:48:12,880
and found Mandras in exactly the same 
position that Pelagia had left him in.

458
00:48:13,680 --> 00:48:17,840
Drosoula ran into the kitchen with 
a cry of joy and then stepped back  

459
00:48:17,840 --> 00:48:21,200
with an astonished look that in 
other circumstances would have  

460
00:48:21,200 --> 00:48:27,440
been amusing. 'It is him,' said Pelagia. 
'I told you he was in an awful state.'

461
00:48:28,880 --> 00:48:34,960
'My God,' Drosoula exclaimed, then began to 
inspect Mandras as if he were an animal she  

462
00:48:34,960 --> 00:48:42,000
was considering purchasing. 'Go and put a big pot 
to boil,' she said finally, 'because I'm going to  

463
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:47,840
wash him from head to foot, but first I'm going to 
get rid of this hair, so bring me some scissors.'

464
00:48:49,120 --> 00:48:54,160
Mandras sat motionless as his mother, 
making terrible faces as she did so,  

465
00:48:54,160 --> 00:48:59,520
cut away the ropes and lumps of his hair and 
beard, revealing the horribly infected state of  

466
00:48:59,520 --> 00:49:06,800
the skin below and the insects creeping all over 
it. Pelagia felt sickened where she knew that she  

467
00:49:06,800 --> 00:49:13,040
should feel pity, and went indoors to look in her 
father's medicine cupboard. She realized with a  

468
00:49:13,040 --> 00:49:18,560
small shock that she had learned enough from her 
father over the years to become a doctor herself.  

469
00:49:19,600 --> 00:49:25,600
Hurrying outside, she told Drosoula which 
treatments to use on Mandras's face and head and  

470
00:49:25,600 --> 00:49:31,920
where to use them. After a brief discussion about 
whether it was correct for a woman to see her  

471
00:49:31,920 --> 00:49:39,040
fiance with nothing on, the two women decided that 
in these circumstances it was entirely acceptable.

472
00:49:40,320 --> 00:49:46,000
They removed Mandras's rags, and after gazing 
sorrowfully at the parcel of skin and bones  

473
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:52,240
that sat before them, again under Pelagia's 
expert guidance, Drosoula began washing her son  

474
00:49:52,240 --> 00:49:58,320
and rubbing healing oils and creams on him. 
Pelagia forced herself to remove the bandages from  

475
00:49:58,320 --> 00:50:04,720
Mandras's feet, and despite the fact that at first 
sight they did not look as if they could be saved,  

476
00:50:04,720 --> 00:50:11,840
on closer examination she realized that the flesh 
was quite dry. She fetched a bowl of clean water,  

477
00:50:12,560 --> 00:50:18,160
salted it heavily, and as gently as she could, 
she washed and treated the terrible mess.

478
00:50:19,600 --> 00:50:25,200
When Dr Iannis returned the following morning, 
he found not only a half-dead man asleep in his  

479
00:50:25,200 --> 00:50:30,720
daughter's bed, but his daughter and an 
amazingly ugly woman asleep in his own.  

480
00:50:31,840 --> 00:50:37,200
He listened to Pelagia's account of everything 
she had done, then examined the patient carefully,  

481
00:50:37,200 --> 00:50:42,880
paying particular attention to the feet. 
Pelagia nervously waited for his anger.  

482
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:51,920
'Well done, I have never been so proud,' he 
declared. Drosoula smiled at Pelagia, who was so  

483
00:50:51,920 --> 00:50:57,440
relieved that her hands were shaking, and the two 
women made more plans for Mandras's recovery.
 
 
 

484
00:51:01,680 --> 00:51:03,680
CHAPTER FIVE

485
00:51:03,680 --> 00:51:07,840
30 April 1941: Invasion

486
00:51:09,520 --> 00:51:14,960
Though he said little, being almost incapable 
of speech due to his physical condition,  

487
00:51:15,600 --> 00:51:21,680
Mandras was fully aware of the change in Pelagia's 
attitude towards him and he hated the way in which  

488
00:51:21,680 --> 00:51:27,600
his mother and fiancee had undressed him, washed 
him and discussed him as if he were not present.  

489
00:51:28,560 --> 00:51:33,360
But the horrors of war and starvation 
had taken away from him the will to live,  

490
00:51:33,920 --> 00:51:39,680
so that he lay for weeks in bed in his mother's 
house, incapable of moving or even speaking,  

491
00:51:40,240 --> 00:51:45,120
constantly revisiting in his mind the 
terrible experiences that had been his.

492
00:51:46,400 --> 00:51:51,440
The brilliance of his Greek leaders had enabled 
him and many of his companions to survive the  

493
00:51:51,440 --> 00:51:57,040
war against the Italians, but the freezing 
conditions in the mountains and lack of food  

494
00:51:57,040 --> 00:52:02,240
meant that his body aged more in a few months 
than it would normally do in sixty years.  

495
00:52:03,200 --> 00:52:08,320
Then, when the Germans had attacked from 
the south, Mandras's unit had marched back  

496
00:52:08,320 --> 00:52:14,640
down into Greece and had fought bravely but 
uselessly against their enemy, leaving Mandras  

497
00:52:14,640 --> 00:52:21,280
the only survivor in his unit. With a vision of 
a loving, smiling Pelagia constantly before him,  

498
00:52:21,840 --> 00:52:26,960
Mandras had found the strength to struggle 
home, wearing bandages instead of boots,  

499
00:52:26,960 --> 00:52:31,840
through the wild hills, mountains and forests 
that made up the greater part of Greece.

500
00:52:33,200 --> 00:52:39,520
For much of his journey he had met very few people 
and had consequently almost died from starvation.  

501
00:52:40,880 --> 00:52:44,560
If he had been met on his return to 
Cephallonia by the loving Pelagia of  

502
00:52:44,560 --> 00:52:52,800
his dreams, Mandras's recovery might have been 
faster. But as week followed week, Pelagia,  

503
00:52:52,800 --> 00:52:59,600
though she tried hard to love Mandras, felt only 
coldness towards him, coldness and the growing  

504
00:52:59,600 --> 00:53:05,760
conviction that Mandras was remaining ill in order 
to punish her for her lack of warmth towards him.

505
00:53:07,440 --> 00:53:10,480
'He thinks that nobody wants him,' said Dr Iannis,  

506
00:53:11,040 --> 00:53:14,480
'and he's doing this in order to 
force us to show him that we do.'

507
00:53:15,920 --> 00:53:19,520
'But I don't want him,' thought 
Pelagia, again and again,  

508
00:53:19,520 --> 00:53:23,680
as she sat making the bedcover that had 
never grown beyond the size of a towel.  

509
00:53:24,800 --> 00:53:29,680
But although she spent a lot of time either 
with or thinking about Mandras, there were  

510
00:53:29,680 --> 00:53:38,160
other matters that occupied her mind just as much. 
By April 1941, the German army had reached Athens,  

511
00:53:38,160 --> 00:53:44,960
and the royal palace there was occupied not by 
King George of Greece but by German soldiers. On  

512
00:53:44,960 --> 00:53:51,200
the 28th of the month, the Italian army, claiming 
that the Ionian islands belonged to them by right,  

513
00:53:51,200 --> 00:53:56,880
invaded the island of Corfu, making it inevitable 
that Cephallonia would be next on the list.

514
00:53:58,320 --> 00:54:05,040
For the islanders, the waiting was painful. Every 
last moment of freedom and security was rolled  

515
00:54:05,040 --> 00:54:11,600
about on the tongue, tasted and remembered. 
Fathers who expected to be beaten to death  

516
00:54:11,600 --> 00:54:14,960
stroked the hair of pretty 
daughters who expected to be raped.  

517
00:54:15,920 --> 00:54:19,920
Sons sat with their mothers on doorsteps 
and talked gently of their memories.  

518
00:54:20,880 --> 00:54:25,680
Father Arsenios knelt in his church, 
attempting to find words to a prayer,  

519
00:54:25,680 --> 00:54:31,440
puzzled by an odd sensation of having been 
abandoned by God instead of the other way round.

520
00:54:33,120 --> 00:54:35,520
In these last weeks before the invasion,  

521
00:54:35,520 --> 00:54:40,240
Dr Iannis wrote what he believed to be the 
final part of his 'History of Cephallonia':

522
00:54:41,840 --> 00:54:48,880
'Among those who invaded and occupied our island 
- the Romans, the Turks, the Russians, the French,  

523
00:54:48,880 --> 00:54:55,440
the British' - he began, 'the Italians made the 
greatest impression upon us, because we spent the  

524
00:54:55,440 --> 00:55:04,320
period from 1194 to 1797 under Italian rule. This 
explains a great many things that may puzzle the  

525
00:55:04,320 --> 00:55:11,040
foreigner, for example, the numerous Italian words 
that exist in our vocabulary, and the architecture  

526
00:55:11,040 --> 00:55:17,040
of the island, which is almost entirely 
Italian.' He continued on this subject for  

527
00:55:17,040 --> 00:55:22,800
a number of pages, then, when it seemed that the 
Italian invasion was due at any moment, he wrote:

528
00:55:23,920 --> 00:55:28,800
'I wait in the knowledge that this 
may be the last thing I ever write.  

529
00:55:29,600 --> 00:55:34,640
I beg that whoever finds these papers 
should preserve and not destroy them.'

530
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:42,080
Placing the papers in a black tin box, the doctor 
lifted the old carpet beneath the table and opened  

531
00:55:42,080 --> 00:55:49,040
a trapdoor, revealing the large hole that had been 
made in 1849 in order to hide island rebels sought  

532
00:55:49,040 --> 00:55:54,720
by the British, who then governed the island. 
He placed his work safely inside the hole,  

533
00:55:55,280 --> 00:55:58,960
then went outside to listen for the 
sound of approaching aeroplanes.

534
00:56:00,400 --> 00:56:05,280
On 30 April foreign aircraft and ships 
were seen approaching from the horizon.  

535
00:56:05,920 --> 00:56:11,520
Drosoula ran inside to Pelagia shouting, 
'Italians, Italians. It's the invasion,'

536
00:56:12,560 --> 00:56:17,600
Pelagia's immediate reaction was to run up 
the hill to be with her father, whom she found  

537
00:56:17,600 --> 00:56:23,120
standing in his doorway, as everyone else stood 
in theirs, protecting his eyes against the sun  

538
00:56:23,120 --> 00:56:29,200
as he watched the planes. Out of breath, 
she flew into his arms and felt him tremble,  

539
00:56:29,840 --> 00:56:36,400
then realized with a small shock that he 
shook, not from fear, but from excitement.

540
00:56:37,600 --> 00:56:43,760
'History,' he cried, 'all this time 
I have been writing history, and now  

541
00:56:43,760 --> 00:56:46,720
history is happening before my eyes.'

542
00:56:48,640 --> 00:56:52,560
The Italian soldiers stepped apologetically 
out of their aircraft and ships  

543
00:56:53,120 --> 00:57:00,480
and waved cheerfully but hesitantly to the people 
in their doorways. In the village, Pelagia and her  

544
00:57:00,480 --> 00:57:05,920
father watched the Italian units go by, their 
leaders consulting maps with puzzled faces.  

545
00:57:07,200 --> 00:57:12,640
A line of men marched by, led by Captain 
Antonio Corelli, with the mandolin that he had  

546
00:57:12,640 --> 00:57:20,720
named Antonia hanging on his back. When he saw 
Pelagia he shouted, 'Bella bambina eyes left!'

547
00:57:22,080 --> 00:57:25,040
The heads of the soldiers turned in her direction,  

548
00:57:25,040 --> 00:57:31,920
and for one unbelievable minute Pelagia was forced 
to watch the most ridiculous behaviour. There was  

549
00:57:31,920 --> 00:57:38,160
a soldier who crossed his eyes and folded down 
his lower lip, another who pushed his lips out  

550
00:57:38,160 --> 00:57:46,080
and blew her a kiss, another who pretended at 
each step to stumble over his own feet. Pelagia  

551
00:57:46,080 --> 00:57:51,680
put her hand to her mouth. 'Don't laugh,' 
ordered the doctor. 'It's our duty to hate them.'

552
00:57:53,200 --> 00:57:59,520
All over Cephallonia the islanders painted rude 
remarks about the invaders in huge letters on all  

553
00:57:59,520 --> 00:58:07,200
available walls. The men related Italian jokes. 
What is the shortest book in the world? The  

554
00:58:07,200 --> 00:58:16,000
Italian Book of War Heroes. Why do Italians wear 
moustaches? To be reminded of their mothers. A  

555
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:22,160
decision was made that the local population should 
provide Italian officers with accommodation.  

556
00:58:22,160 --> 00:58:27,840
So one day the doctor came home and found a 
round Italian officer standing in the kitchen.

557
00:58:28,560 --> 00:58:30,480
'Buon giorno,' said the officer.

558
00:58:31,200 --> 00:58:36,560
'Buon giorno,' the doctor replied. 'Perhaps 
you could tell me why you are here.'

559
00:58:37,200 --> 00:58:39,840
'Ah,' said the man uncomfortably,  

560
00:58:40,560 --> 00:58:46,000
'I am sorry to say, you are going to have 
to provide accommodation for an officer.'

561
00:58:47,120 --> 00:58:52,720
'Impossible,' said the doctor angrily. 
Then an interesting thought occurred to him  

562
00:58:52,720 --> 00:58:56,560
and he asked, 'Do you have a supply of medicines?'

563
00:58:57,520 --> 00:58:59,360
'Naturally,' replied the officer.  

564
00:59:00,160 --> 00:59:05,680
The two men exchanged glances, understanding 
perfectly what the other was thinking.

565
00:59:06,880 --> 00:59:09,520
'There are many things I need,' said the doctor.

566
00:59:10,400 --> 00:59:12,960
'And I need accommodation. So?'

567
00:59:14,320 --> 00:59:16,160
'So it's a deal,' said the doctor.

568
00:59:16,960 --> 00:59:20,640
'A deal,' repeated the 
officer. 'Anything you want,  

569
00:59:20,640 --> 00:59:24,480
send me a message through Captain 
Corelli. You will find him charming.'

570
00:59:26,640 --> 00:59:31,120
In the early evening Captain Corelli 
arrived, driven by another soldier,  

571
00:59:31,120 --> 00:59:38,560
Carlo Piero Guercio. The captain looked around, 
appreciating the signs of a quiet domestic life.  

572
00:59:39,520 --> 00:59:45,120
There was a goat tied to a tree, and a 
young woman with dark eyes at a table,  

573
00:59:45,120 --> 00:59:51,440
with a scarf tied round her head and a large 
cooking knife in her hand. The captain fell to  

574
00:59:51,440 --> 00:59:57,760
his knees before her and exclaimed dramatically, 
'Please don't kill me, I am innocent.'

575
00:59:59,520 --> 01:00:05,120
Pelagia smiled, against her will, and glanced 
at Carlo, amazed to see that he was as big as  

576
01:00:05,120 --> 01:00:13,440
Velisarios. The captain leapt up. 'I am Captain 
Antonio Corelli and this...' he took Carlo by  

577
01:00:13,440 --> 01:00:18,640
the arm, '... is one of our heroes. He 
rescued a fallen friend under fire.'

578
01:00:20,160 --> 01:00:26,880
'It's nothing,' said Carlo with a shy smile, and 
Pelagia knew immediately that, despite his size,  

579
01:00:26,880 --> 01:00:34,480
he was a soft and saddened man. 'This...' Corelli 
continued, tapping a case in his hand, '... is  

580
01:00:34,480 --> 01:00:41,760
Antonia. By what name do men know you, may I 
ask?' Pelagia looked at Corelli properly for  

581
01:00:41,760 --> 01:00:47,360
the first time and realized that this was the 
same officer who had commanded his men to march  

582
01:00:47,360 --> 01:00:55,600
past at 'eyes left'. At the same moment Corelli 
recognized her. 'Ah,' he exclaimed and smacked  

583
01:00:55,600 --> 01:01:02,000
himself on the wrist, then fell to his knees once 
more and said softly, 'Forgive me, I have sinned.'

584
01:01:03,520 --> 01:01:07,040
Dr Iannis came out, saw the 
captain on his knees and said,  

585
01:01:08,080 --> 01:01:11,200
'Captain Corelli? I want a word with you. Now.'

586
01:01:12,720 --> 01:01:17,840
Surprised by the authority in the older man's 
voice, Corelli stood up and held out his hand,  

587
01:01:18,640 --> 01:01:24,800
but the doctor did not put out his own, instead 
saying sharply, 'I want an explanation please.  

588
01:01:25,600 --> 01:01:28,640
Why has the teaching of Greek 
history been forbidden in schools?  

589
01:01:29,360 --> 01:01:31,840
And why is everyone being 
forced to learn Italian?'

590
01:01:33,040 --> 01:01:36,080
The captain felt himself wanting 
to run away like a little boy.  

591
01:01:37,200 --> 01:01:39,760
'I am not responsible for it,' he said.

592
01:01:40,800 --> 01:01:43,840
The doctor frowned fiercely and 
shook his finger at the captain.  

593
01:01:44,800 --> 01:01:49,520
'There would be no wars, captain, if 
men like you took more responsibility.'

594
01:01:50,640 --> 01:01:53,760
'I must protest,' the captain replied weakly.

595
01:01:54,640 --> 01:02:01,760
'Fool,' said the doctor forcefully and returned 
inside, very satisfied with himself. Pelagia could  

596
01:02:01,760 --> 01:02:08,480
not help feeling sorry for the captain. 'Your 
father is...' he said, and the words failed him.

597
01:02:09,520 --> 01:02:12,040
'Yes, he is,' confirmed Pelagia.

598
01:02:12,800 --> 01:02:16,560
'Where shall I sleep?' asked 
Corelli, eager to change the subject.

599
01:02:17,680 --> 01:02:19,920
'You will have my bed,' said Pelagia.

600
01:02:21,120 --> 01:02:25,280
Under normal circumstances Antonio 
Corelli would have asked brightly,  

601
01:02:25,920 --> 01:02:32,400
'Are we going to share it then? How kind,' but 
now, after the doctor's words, he received this  

602
01:02:32,400 --> 01:02:38,640
information with horror. 'Impossible,' he 
said. 'Tonight I shall sleep in the yard  

603
01:02:38,640 --> 01:02:41,440
and tomorrow I shall request 
alternative accommodation.'

604
01:02:42,640 --> 01:02:46,160
Pelagia was shocked by the feelings 
of anxiety that rose in her.  

605
01:02:46,800 --> 01:02:50,080
Could there be something inside her 
that wanted this foreigner, this  

606
01:02:50,720 --> 01:02:56,160
invader, to stay? She went inside and told 
her father about the captain's decision.  

607
01:02:56,960 --> 01:03:01,840
'He can't go,' he said. 'How am I supposed 
to be nasty to him if he isn't here?  

608
01:03:02,560 --> 01:03:08,800
And anyway, he seems like a pleasant boy.' He took 
his daughter's arm and went back out with her.  

609
01:03:09,440 --> 01:03:14,160
'Young man,' he said to the captain, 'you 
are staying here whether you like it or not.  

610
01:03:14,800 --> 01:03:18,480
It is quite possible that we 
will be sent someone even worse.'

611
01:03:19,680 --> 01:03:23,200
'Yes,' said the captain, 
overcome with embarrassment.

612
01:03:24,720 --> 01:03:31,600
'Kyria Pelagia will bring water, some coffee and 
food. You will find we look after our guests,  

613
01:03:31,600 --> 01:03:36,640
even those who do not deserve it. Your 
vast friend is welcome to join us.'

614
01:03:38,240 --> 01:03:43,840
The captain went to call Carlo to the meal in a 
state of miserable obedience and utter defeat.

615
01:03:46,160 --> 01:03:51,200
When the captain woke after his first night in 
the doctor's house, he went into the kitchen,  

616
01:03:51,200 --> 01:03:58,480
saw Pelagia fast asleep and did not know what 
to do. He looked down upon her and realized  

617
01:03:58,480 --> 01:04:04,640
he wanted to crawl in beside her - nothing 
could have seemed more natural - but instead  

618
01:04:04,640 --> 01:04:09,280
he returned to his room and took his 
mandolin, Antonia, out of its case.  

619
01:04:10,560 --> 01:04:16,560
After practising for five minutes or so, he 
began playing a very fast, complicated piece,  

620
01:04:17,520 --> 01:04:23,440
forgetful of the sleeping girl next door, so that 
Pelagia woke to indescribably beautiful music  

621
01:04:23,440 --> 01:04:29,040
coming from somewhere in the house. She lay 
listening, then went to dress in her father's  

622
01:04:29,040 --> 01:04:34,320
room, and Corelli, realizing that she had 
risen at last, came out into the kitchen.

623
01:04:35,680 --> 01:04:37,920
'That was lovely,' commented Pelagia.

624
01:04:38,720 --> 01:04:42,240
He looked unhappy. 'I'm sorry, I woke you up.'

625
01:04:43,120 --> 01:04:46,960
'That's very beautiful,' she said, 
gesturing towards the instrument.  

626
01:04:47,920 --> 01:04:49,280
'Why do you play the mandolin?'

627
01:04:50,240 --> 01:04:55,760
'Why does one do anything? My uncle gave me 
Antonia and I discovered I could be a good  

628
01:04:55,760 --> 01:05:01,840
musician. When the war's over, I'm going to become 
a professional concert player and composer.'

629
01:05:02,720 --> 01:05:06,400
'You're going to be rich and famous, 
then,' Pelagia said jokingly.  

630
01:05:07,040 --> 01:05:08,400
'Why don't you play me something?'

631
01:05:09,680 --> 01:05:15,760
The captain picked up the mandolin, and a stream 
of notes poured from it that made Pelagia's mouth  

632
01:05:15,760 --> 01:05:22,880
fall open. She had never before heard such 
complex, lovely music. She realized for the  

633
01:05:22,880 --> 01:05:28,720
first time that music was not just a sweet 
sound, but was, to those who understood it,  

634
01:05:28,720 --> 01:05:33,600
an emotional and intellectual journey, 
a journey that she wanted to share.  

635
01:05:34,800 --> 01:05:38,960
She leaned forward and put her hands 
together as if she were at prayer.

636
01:05:40,960 --> 01:05:43,440
'There you are,' said the 
captain when he had finished.

637
01:05:44,240 --> 01:05:51,040
In her excitement at the music, she wanted to 
dance and spin round, but she only said, 'I  

638
01:05:51,040 --> 01:05:57,280
just don't understand why an artist like you would 
descend to being a soldier. It's a waste of time.'

639
01:05:58,320 --> 01:06:04,320
'Of course it's a waste of time.' He rose and 
glanced at his watch. 'Carlo should have been  

640
01:06:04,320 --> 01:06:10,720
here by now. I'll have to go and find him.' He 
looked at her with one eyebrow raised and said,  

641
01:06:11,520 --> 01:06:17,840
'By the way, Signorina, I couldn't help noticing 
that you have a gun in the pocket of your skirt.'

642
01:06:18,800 --> 01:06:21,760
Pelagia began to tremble 
but the captain continued,  

643
01:06:22,480 --> 01:06:28,080
'I understand why you might want to have 
it, and in fact I haven't seen it at all,  

644
01:06:28,080 --> 01:06:33,920
but you must realize what would happen 
if someone else saw it. Be more careful.'

645
01:06:35,120 --> 01:06:39,360
She looked up at him, appealing 
with her eyes, and he smiled,  

646
01:06:39,360 --> 01:06:41,840
tapped the side of his nose and was gone.

647
01:06:44,800 --> 01:06:48,320
Carlo had not arrived with the 
car to pick up Captain Corelli,  

648
01:06:48,320 --> 01:06:51,200
because it had broken down some 
kilometres from the village.  

649
01:06:52,080 --> 01:06:58,240
After kicking the car a number of times, Carlo had 
set off on foot towards the village. Velisarios  

650
01:06:58,240 --> 01:07:03,360
passed him and the two men looked at one 
another with something like recognition,  

651
01:07:03,360 --> 01:07:09,520
because both men had become accustomed to the sad 
suspicion that they were unique in a peculiar way.  

652
01:07:10,640 --> 01:07:16,400
They were both amazed at the other's size and 
for a moment forgot that they were enemies.  

653
01:07:17,360 --> 01:07:22,880
'Hey!' said Velisarios, raising his hands 
in a gesture of pleasure. Carlo offered  

654
01:07:22,880 --> 01:07:29,360
him one of his disgusting cigarettes, Velisarios 
accepted, and they made sour faces to each other  

655
01:07:29,360 --> 01:07:34,880
as they smoked. They then went their separate 
ways, more content than before they had met.

656
01:07:36,000 --> 01:07:41,840
As Carlo walked up the hill towards the house, 
his mind turned towards Captain Corelli.  

657
01:07:42,400 --> 01:07:46,800
For the first time since the death of 
Francesco in the mountains of Albania,  

658
01:07:46,800 --> 01:07:52,320
the soldier was experiencing a kind of 
happiness; in the captain he had once  

659
01:07:52,320 --> 01:07:59,200
again found a man whom he could love and serve. 
In his eyes, Corelli was endlessly optimistic,  

660
01:07:59,760 --> 01:08:05,840
a clear fountain, a kind of saint who remained a 
man of honour because he knew no other way to be.  

661
01:08:07,040 --> 01:08:11,920
Carlo knew that some people thought that 
Corelli was a little mad, but for him, the  

662
01:08:11,920 --> 01:08:17,440
captain was a man who loved life so much that he 
did not care what kind of an impression he made.

663
01:08:18,960 --> 01:08:23,520
One of the pleasures of Carlo's life, at 
that time, was an opera group called La  

664
01:08:23,520 --> 01:08:28,240
Scala that the captain had organized from 
among those of his men who could sing.  

665
01:08:29,120 --> 01:08:34,160
Carlo, who had a fine singing voice, had been 
invited to join when the captain had heard  

666
01:08:34,160 --> 01:08:40,240
him singing as he polished his boots. There was 
another more unusual member of the opera group,  

667
01:08:40,240 --> 01:08:46,160
a young German soldier called Gunter Weber, 
part of a troop of three thousand German  

668
01:08:46,160 --> 01:08:50,240
soldiers who had accompanied the Italian 
army on their invasion of the island.  

669
01:08:51,040 --> 01:08:55,520
Although relations between the Germans and 
Italians appeared friendly, the Germans thought  

670
01:08:55,520 --> 01:09:01,680
of the Italians as inferior, and the Italians were 
puzzled by German discipline and lack of humour.

671
01:09:02,480 --> 01:09:05,680
But Captain Corelli had made 
friends with Gunter Weber,  

672
01:09:05,680 --> 01:09:11,360
a boy who spoke some Italian and whom the captain 
liked because his face was open and friendly,  

673
01:09:11,360 --> 01:09:16,000
and because when he got drunk he 
laughed and lost his German seriousness.  

674
01:09:17,120 --> 01:09:22,640
Weber became a member of the opera club despite 
the fact that he could not sing a note. Neither  

675
01:09:22,640 --> 01:09:28,720
Corelli nor Carlo knew that one day the German 
would betray his friends with a storm of bullets  

676
01:09:28,720 --> 01:09:33,840
that would open red and bleeding wounds in the 
bodies of the companions he had grown to love.
 
 
 

677
01:09:38,160 --> 01:09:38,960
CHAPTER SIX

678
01:09:40,240 --> 01:09:41,280
The Freedom Fighter

679
01:09:43,040 --> 01:09:48,960
After Captain Corelli had left, Pelagia did 
some household tasks, then went outside to  

680
01:09:48,960 --> 01:09:54,640
brush her goat, thinking about the captain 
as she did so. Mandras caught her dreaming.

681
01:09:55,360 --> 01:10:00,880
He had climbed out of bed, cursing and completely 
cured, on the day of the invasion, as if the  

682
01:10:00,880 --> 01:10:06,160
arrival of the Italians was something so important 
that illness was a luxury to be left behind.  

683
01:10:07,360 --> 01:10:11,280
He had gone down to the sea and 
swum as if he had never been away,  

684
01:10:11,840 --> 01:10:18,880
and had returned with a smile on his face 
and a fish for Pelagia. But Pelagia only felt  

685
01:10:18,880 --> 01:10:23,040
guilty now, whenever she saw 
him, and deeply uncomfortable.

686
01:10:24,080 --> 01:10:28,720
She jumped when he tapped her on the shoulder 
and despite her effort to force a bright smile,  

687
01:10:29,280 --> 01:10:35,280
he did not fail to see the look of alarm in her 
eyes. He ignored it but would remember it later.  

688
01:10:36,640 --> 01:10:40,480
'I'm going to join the freedom fighters,' 
he said. 'I'm leaving tomorrow.'

689
01:10:41,280 --> 01:10:48,480
'Oh,' said Pelagia. There was a long silence, 
then she said, 'I won't be able to write.'

690
01:10:49,520 --> 01:10:49,920
'I know.'

691
01:10:51,600 --> 01:10:55,680
Pelagia shook her head slowly and 
sighed. 'Promise me one thing.  

692
01:10:56,800 --> 01:11:02,160
Whenever you are planning to do something 
terrible, think of me and don't do it.'

693
01:11:03,600 --> 01:11:09,440
'I'm a Greek,' he said gently. 'Not a Fascist. 
And I will think of you every minute.'

694
01:11:11,120 --> 01:11:14,720
She heard the sincerity in his voice 
and felt herself wanting to cry.  

695
01:11:15,520 --> 01:11:20,080
They embraced, like brother and sister, 
not people who were engaged to be married.  

696
01:11:21,280 --> 01:11:26,240
'God go with you,' said Pelagia, 
and he smiled sadly. 'And with you.'

697
01:11:27,600 --> 01:11:29,920
'I shall always remember 
you swinging in the tree.'

698
01:11:30,880 --> 01:11:35,280
They laughed, then he looked at 
her lovingly for one last moment,  

699
01:11:35,280 --> 01:11:41,840
took a few steps, paused, turned and 
said softly, 'I shall always love you.'

700
01:11:43,640 --> 01:11:44,640
***

701
01:11:44,640 --> 01:11:48,960
Mandras joined a group of three men in the 
hills of the Peloponnisos in southern Greece.  

702
01:11:49,760 --> 01:11:54,960
They had neither plan nor purpose. All they 
knew was that they were driven by something  

703
01:11:54,960 --> 01:12:00,080
from the depths of the soul, something that 
commanded them to rid their land of strangers  

704
01:12:00,080 --> 01:12:06,800
or die in the attempt. They set fire to lorries, 
and one of their number stabbed an enemy soldier  

705
01:12:06,800 --> 01:12:12,960
and afterwards sat shaking with fear and disgust 
while the others comforted and praised him.  

706
01:12:14,000 --> 01:12:18,560
They lived on the edge of a forest in a cave, 
living off supplies brought by the priest  

707
01:12:18,560 --> 01:12:23,520
of a neighbouring village. There were several 
other groups of freedom fighters in the area,  

708
01:12:23,520 --> 01:12:26,560
the most organized being 
a Communist group known as  

709
01:12:26,560 --> 01:12:32,160
ELAS (although it did not declare itself as 
communist, preferring to disguise the fact).

710
01:12:33,120 --> 01:12:38,400
Mandras joined ELAS at first because 
he had no choice. He and his companions  

711
01:12:38,400 --> 01:12:41,120
were lying in a small leafy 
shelter that they had built,  

712
01:12:41,760 --> 01:12:45,440
when they were suddenly surrounded 
by ten men with thick beards,  

713
01:12:45,440 --> 01:12:52,560
pointing guns at them. Their leader, who wore 
a dirty red cap, said, 'Come out,' and the men  

714
01:12:52,560 --> 01:12:58,320
slowly stood up and came out, fearing for their 
lives, their hands upon the backs of their heads.

715
01:12:59,520 --> 01:13:02,160
'Who are you with?' demanded the man with the cap.

716
01:13:03,280 --> 01:13:05,840
'With no one,' replied Mandras, confused.

717
01:13:06,800 --> 01:13:10,000
'The deal is that either 
you go back to your villages  

718
01:13:10,000 --> 01:13:15,920
and leave us your weapons,' said the leader 
commandingly, 'or you fight us and we kill you,  

719
01:13:15,920 --> 01:13:21,520
or you join us under my command. This is my 
territory and no one else's. Which is it?'

720
01:13:22,960 --> 01:13:26,080
'We came to fight,' explained 
Mandras. 'Who are you?'

721
01:13:27,040 --> 01:13:34,560
'I am Hector, not my real name, and we are the 
local branch of ELAS.' Hector's men grinned in  

722
01:13:34,560 --> 01:13:39,120
a very friendly fashion, and Mandras looked 
from one of his companions to the others.  

723
01:13:40,640 --> 01:13:48,000
'We stay?' he asked, and they nodded. They had 
been too long in the hills to give up the fight  

724
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:51,680
and it was good to have found a leader 
who might know what ought to be done.

725
01:13:52,480 --> 01:13:56,960
'Good,' said Hector. 'Come with us, 
and let's see what you are made of.'

726
01:13:58,640 --> 01:14:04,080
He led Mandras and his companions three kilometres 
to a tiny house guarded by one of Hector's men.  

727
01:14:04,720 --> 01:14:10,880
'Bring him out,' Hector said, and the man kicked 
and pushed a thin old man out into the sunlight,  

728
01:14:10,880 --> 01:14:16,240
where he stood trembling and blinking. Hector 
handed Mandras a length of knotted rope  

729
01:14:16,240 --> 01:14:19,760
and, pointing to the old man, said, 'Beat him.'

730
01:14:20,960 --> 01:14:23,040
Mandras stared at Hector in disbelief  

731
01:14:23,600 --> 01:14:28,480
and the latter stared fiercely back at him. 
'If you want to be with us, you've got to  

732
01:14:28,480 --> 01:14:34,240
learn to teach these people a lesson. This 
man has been found guilty. Now beat him.'

733
01:14:35,840 --> 01:14:40,800
Mandras struck the man once with the 
rope, lightly, because of the man's age,  

734
01:14:40,800 --> 01:14:45,840
and Hector impatiently exclaimed, 
'Harder, harder. What are you? A woman?'  

735
01:14:47,040 --> 01:14:53,280
Mandras struck the old man once more, a 
little harder. 'Again,' commanded Hector.

736
01:14:54,240 --> 01:15:01,600
It was easier each time he hit him. In fact 
it became a pleasure. It was as if all the  

737
01:15:01,600 --> 01:15:08,000
anger from the earliest years of his childhood 
rose in him and was given expression. The old  

738
01:15:08,000 --> 01:15:15,520
man threw himself to the ground, screaming, and 
Mandras suddenly knew he could be a god. Hector  

739
01:15:15,520 --> 01:15:21,200
stepped forward, took the rope from his hand, 
and placed a gun in his grasp. 'Now kill him.'

740
01:15:22,480 --> 01:15:29,760
Mandras knelt down and placed the gun against 
the old man's head, but he could not do it. He  

741
01:15:29,760 --> 01:15:34,960
closed his eyes tight and told himself that 
he had to be a man in front of other men.  

742
01:15:35,760 --> 01:15:41,280
Anyway, he was only doing what Hector had 
ordered him to do. The man was going to  

743
01:15:41,280 --> 01:15:47,360
die anyway. Mandras tightened the muscles 
of his face and shot the man in the head.

744
01:15:49,200 --> 01:15:52,960
Afterwards he looked not at the 
bloody mess of bone and brain,  

745
01:15:53,520 --> 01:15:59,760
but in disbelief at the smoking gun. Hector 
patted Mandras on the back and said, 'Well done'.  

746
01:16:00,800 --> 01:16:04,800
Mandras tried to struggle to 
his feet but could not do so,  

747
01:16:05,360 --> 01:16:11,280
and Hector helped him up. 'Revolutionary 
justice,' he said. 'Historical necessity.'

748
01:16:13,200 --> 01:16:17,840
As they left the village, Mandras found 
that he could not look anyone in the face  

749
01:16:17,840 --> 01:16:23,040
and he stared down into the dirt. 
'What did he do?' he asked finally.

750
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:28,960
'He was a dirty old thief. He took a bottle of 
whisky from supplies that were meant for us.  

751
01:16:29,840 --> 01:16:34,080
You have to be tough with these people 
or they start doing what they like.  

752
01:16:34,080 --> 01:16:38,320
They're full of the wrong ideas and it's 
just something we have to get out of them.'

753
01:16:39,320 --> 01:16:40,320
***

754
01:16:40,320 --> 01:16:46,000
During his time with Hector, Mandras learnt a 
great many things. Hector taught Mandras to read  

755
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:52,480
and write, and taught him all about Communism. 
Mandras learnt that he was not a fisherman  

756
01:16:52,480 --> 01:17:00,000
but a worker, and that he was as good as Dr Iannis 
and deserved the same pay. He learnt to take food  

757
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:06,400
and animals from hungry villagers without payment, 
since ELAS was working so hard on behalf of the  

758
01:17:06,400 --> 01:17:13,120
Greek people. When villagers attempted to resist 
them, then Hector and his men punished them,  

759
01:17:13,120 --> 01:17:20,080
not just by shooting them but by tearing out 
eyes and cutting mouths so that people died  

760
01:17:20,080 --> 01:17:27,440
smiling. Hector explained to Mandras that the 
villagers were Fascists and loyal to the king,  

761
01:17:27,440 --> 01:17:30,640
and that a good lesson would 
help them to change their ways.

762
01:17:31,840 --> 01:17:39,360
Mandras also learnt to rape women and to enjoy 
their screams, since it was all in a good cause.  

763
01:17:40,400 --> 01:17:45,920
A new and better Greece would be built, and you 
did what you liked with the inferior bricks that  

764
01:17:45,920 --> 01:17:51,440
were going to be thrown away anyway. It was 
like making an omelette and throwing away  

765
01:17:51,440 --> 01:17:57,840
the eggshells, said Hector, and Mandras 
drank in every word his leader said.
 
 
 

766
01:17:59,680 --> 01:18:00,480
CHAPTER SEVEN

767
01:18:01,360 --> 01:18:02,560
A Problem with Eyes

768
01:18:04,400 --> 01:18:10,080
Pelagia treated the captain as badly 
as she could. If she served him food,  

769
01:18:10,080 --> 01:18:15,920
she would deliberately spill it as she put it 
down, and eventually she noticed that he had  

770
01:18:15,920 --> 01:18:20,800
acquired the habit of not pulling in his chair 
until she had already put the food on the table.  

771
01:18:21,840 --> 01:18:26,640
His failure to protest at her treatment 
of him and his constant politeness  

772
01:18:26,640 --> 01:18:33,200
made her even more annoyed. Her anger was so 
deep and so bitter that she needed to shout at  

773
01:18:33,200 --> 01:18:39,360
him or even strike him in order to release 
it. After two months of sleepless nights,  

774
01:18:39,360 --> 01:18:45,040
months during which she had done her best to 
annoy him, the captain remained calm and friendly.

775
01:18:46,720 --> 01:18:53,440
One day he left his gun on the table. After 
some thought, Pelagia decided to put the gun  

776
01:18:53,440 --> 01:18:57,840
in a bowl of water for a few minutes in 
the hope that this would do some damage.  

777
01:18:58,960 --> 01:19:03,760
The captain came in and caught her just as 
she was lifting the gun out of the water.  

778
01:19:04,720 --> 01:19:09,440
She heard a voice behind her and, in 
her fear, dropped it back in the bowl.

779
01:19:10,640 --> 01:19:13,840
'Oh God,' she exclaimed, 'you frightened me!'

780
01:19:15,120 --> 01:19:21,360
The captain looked down at the gun, raised his 
eyebrows and said coolly, 'I see you're trying  

781
01:19:21,360 --> 01:19:28,240
to make trouble for me.' This was not what she 
had expected, but nevertheless her heart beat  

782
01:19:28,240 --> 01:19:36,560
faster with fear and anxiety. 'I was washing it,' 
she said weakly at last. 'It was terribly oily.'

783
01:19:37,840 --> 01:19:41,600
'How charming to know so little 
about guns,' said the captain.  

784
01:19:42,320 --> 01:19:46,160
Pelagia went red, strangely 
angered by his suggestion,  

785
01:19:46,160 --> 01:19:51,520
which she knew he did not mean, that she was 
a sweet and silly girl who did stupid things.

786
01:19:53,840 --> 01:19:56,480
'You are not a good liar,' the captain added.

787
01:19:57,440 --> 01:20:01,680
'What do you expect?' she demanded, 
immediately wondering what she had meant.

788
01:20:02,720 --> 01:20:07,600
The captain seemed to know, however. 
'It must be very difficult for you all  

789
01:20:07,600 --> 01:20:12,720
to have to put up with us.' He removed 
the gun from the bowl, sighed and said,  

790
01:20:13,600 --> 01:20:17,840
'I suppose you have done me a 
favour. It does need cleaning.'

791
01:20:18,400 --> 01:20:21,440
'Aren't you angry, then? Why aren't you angry?'

792
01:20:22,640 --> 01:20:28,000
'What's anger got to do with music? Do you really 
believe I've got nothing important to think about?  

793
01:20:29,040 --> 01:20:33,040
Let's just think about important 
things and leave one another in peace.  

794
01:20:33,840 --> 01:20:37,120
I'll leave you alone and you can leave me alone.'

795
01:20:38,560 --> 01:20:45,760
This idea struck Pelagia as new and unacceptable. 
She did not want to leave him alone, she wanted  

796
01:20:45,760 --> 01:20:52,320
to shout at him and hit him. Suddenly overcome 
with emotion, she struck him with all her force,  

797
01:20:52,320 --> 01:20:56,320
right across the left cheek. 
He tried to step back in time,  

798
01:20:56,320 --> 01:21:02,880
but was too late. He steadied himself and touched 
a hand to his face, as if comforting himself,  

799
01:21:03,680 --> 01:21:11,760
then held out the gun. 'Put it back in the water,' 
he said, 'I might find it less painful.' This  

800
01:21:11,760 --> 01:21:17,920
remark made Pelagia even angrier. She rushed 
out into the yard and kicked an iron pot,  

801
01:21:17,920 --> 01:21:24,480
injuring her toe, then threw the pot over the 
wall. The captain, watching her from the window,  

802
01:21:24,480 --> 01:21:32,800
shook his head in amazement. These Greek girls, 
such passion and fire, he thought admiringly, and  

803
01:21:32,800 --> 01:21:40,240
then wondered why no one had ever written an opera 
set in modern Greece. A tune entered his mind and  

804
01:21:40,240 --> 01:21:45,680
he began to sing it softly to himself, thinking 
that perhaps he would call it 'Pelagia's March'.

805
01:21:47,280 --> 01:21:54,240
As the months went by, Pelagia noticed that she 
was losing her anger, and this puzzled and upset  

806
01:21:54,240 --> 01:22:00,480
her. The fact was that the captain had become 
as much a part of the house as the goat or her  

807
01:22:00,480 --> 01:22:05,840
own father, and she was quite used to seeing 
him playing with little Lemoni in the yard,  

808
01:22:05,840 --> 01:22:12,720
or seated at the table, deep in concentration, 
composing music for the mandolin. Early in the  

809
01:22:12,720 --> 01:22:17,680
morning she looked forward with pleasure to the 
moment when he would enter the kitchen and say,  

810
01:22:18,240 --> 01:22:21,760
'Kalimcra Kyria Pelagia. Is Carlo here yet?'  

811
01:22:22,560 --> 01:22:26,720
and in the evening she would actually 
begin to worry if he were a little late.

812
01:22:28,240 --> 01:22:33,680
A new source of anger developed, the problem 
being that this time the anger was directed  

813
01:22:33,680 --> 01:22:40,400
against herself. It seemed that she just could not 
help looking at him, and he was always catching  

814
01:22:40,400 --> 01:22:46,320
her. There was something about him, sitting 
at the table as he went through his paperwork,  

815
01:22:46,320 --> 01:22:52,320
that made her look up at him regularly. 
But every time she looked up, he did too,  

816
01:22:52,320 --> 01:22:58,000
and she would be caught in his steady gaze as 
surely as if he had grasped her by the wrists.

817
01:22:59,120 --> 01:23:04,800
For a few seconds they would look at one another 
and then she would grow red and look down.  

818
01:23:05,840 --> 01:23:11,920
Then a few seconds later she would look up, 
and at that moment he would return her glance.  

819
01:23:12,720 --> 01:23:19,840
It was impossible and embarrassing. 'I've got 
to stop doing this,' she would tell herself and,  

820
01:23:19,840 --> 01:23:24,160
certain that he was deep in his tasks, 
would look up and get caught again.

821
01:23:25,440 --> 01:23:30,640
She knew he was playing a game with her, 
that she was being played with so gently  

822
01:23:30,640 --> 01:23:36,720
that it was impossible to protest. After 
all, she had never caught him looking at her,  

823
01:23:36,720 --> 01:23:44,800
so it was all her fault, obviously. Nevertheless, 
it was a game of which he was in absolute command,  

824
01:23:45,440 --> 01:23:52,240
and in that sense she was its victim. She decided 
that she would not be the one to look down;  

825
01:23:52,880 --> 01:23:59,120
she would wait until he broke away. She searched 
for every last bit of courage and looked up.

826
01:24:00,240 --> 01:24:05,760
They looked at one another for what seemed 
like hours and Pelagia wondered foolishly if  

827
01:24:05,760 --> 01:24:12,320
it was considered acceptable to blink. Her 
eyes began to water and she started seeing  

828
01:24:12,320 --> 01:24:18,080
two captains instead of one. He did not 
look away but began to make funny faces,  

829
01:24:18,720 --> 01:24:24,240
showing his teeth like a horse, and moving 
the tip of his nose from side to side,  

830
01:24:24,240 --> 01:24:31,200
so that Pelagia began a smile, then laughed 
aloud and blinked. Corelli jumped to his feet,  

831
01:24:31,200 --> 01:24:38,400
crying, 'I won! I won,' and the doctor looked 
up from his book, exclaiming, 'What? What?'

832
01:24:39,520 --> 01:24:45,760
'You cheated,' protested Pelagia, laughing. The 
doctor looked from the captain to his daughter,  

833
01:24:46,480 --> 01:24:54,480
adjusted his glasses and sighed. 'Whatever next?' 
he demanded, knowing perfectly well what was next,  

834
01:24:55,120 --> 01:24:57,840
and working out in advance how to deal with it.

835
01:24:58,960 --> 01:25:03,040
Some days later they passed each 
other at the door, she going out  

836
01:25:03,040 --> 01:25:10,880
and he returning from work. Unselfconsciously, she 
raised one hand to his left cheek and, in passing,  

837
01:25:10,880 --> 01:25:17,520
kissed him on the other. He was astonished and, 
by the time she reached the entrance to the yard,  

838
01:25:18,160 --> 01:25:25,680
so was she, because it was not until then that she 
realized what she had done. She stopped as if she  

839
01:25:25,680 --> 01:25:31,760
had walked straight into a wall, felt her blood 
rising to the roots of her hair, and realized that  

840
01:25:31,760 --> 01:25:38,200
she did not dare look back at him. He called 
out, as she knew he would, 'Kyria Pelagia,'

841
01:25:38,800 --> 01:25:39,840
'What?' she demanded.

842
01:25:41,120 --> 01:25:42,000
'What's for dinner?'

843
01:25:42,800 --> 01:25:48,880
'Don't laugh at me. I thought you were my father. 
I always kiss him like that when he comes in.'

844
01:25:49,840 --> 01:25:53,840
'Very understandable. We are both old and small.'

845
01:25:54,480 --> 01:25:57,600
'If you are going to laugh at me, 
I shall never speak to you again.'

846
01:25:58,720 --> 01:26:02,080
He came out and threw himself 
upon his knees before her.

847
01:26:03,040 --> 01:26:09,520
'Oh no,' he cried, 'not that. Shoot me, beat 
me, but don't say you'll never speak to me.'  

848
01:26:10,240 --> 01:26:13,280
He grasped her round the 
knees and pretended to weep.

849
01:26:14,080 --> 01:26:17,760
'The whole village is looking,' 
she protested. 'Stop it at once.'

850
01:26:18,560 --> 01:26:25,040
'My heart is broken,' he cried and, taking 
her hand, he began to cover it with kisses.

851
01:26:25,680 --> 01:26:27,520
'Stupid goat, you are insane.'

852
01:26:28,480 --> 01:26:32,560
Corelli laughed and got to his 
feet. 'Come inside,' he said,  

853
01:26:33,200 --> 01:26:35,520
'I've got something very interesting to show you.'

854
01:26:38,080 --> 01:26:42,640
Relieved by this sudden change of subject, 
she followed him through the door,  

855
01:26:42,640 --> 01:26:45,680
but found that he was passing 
her on the way out again.  

856
01:26:46,560 --> 01:26:52,000
He put his hands on each side of her head, kissed 
her dramatically on the forehead, exclaimed,  

857
01:26:52,640 --> 01:26:58,800
'I'm sorry, I thought it was the doctor,' and 
then ran away across the yard and down the street.  

858
01:26:59,680 --> 01:27:05,440
She stared after him in amazement, making 
every effort not to laugh or smile.
 
 
 

859
01:27:09,760 --> 01:27:10,480
CHAPTER EIGHT

860
01:27:11,200 --> 01:27:11,840
Snails

861
01:27:13,440 --> 01:27:18,480
When the doctor glanced out of the window and 
saw Captain Corelli creeping up behind Lemoni  

862
01:27:18,480 --> 01:27:24,080
in order to surprise her, he laid down his 
pen and went out into the afternoon sunlight.

863
01:27:25,920 --> 01:27:30,000
'Excuse me, children,' said the doctor, 
ignoring the captain's embarrassment,  

864
01:27:30,640 --> 01:27:35,840
'Lemoni, do you remember that you told me you 
know a place where there were lots of snails?  

865
01:27:36,480 --> 01:27:39,040
Can you come round this evening 
and show me where they are?'

866
01:27:40,240 --> 01:27:42,000
Lemoni nodded importantly.

867
01:27:43,360 --> 01:27:45,840
'What's all this about?' asked the captain.

868
01:27:46,880 --> 01:27:50,640
Stiffly, the doctor said, 'Thanks to you Italians,  

869
01:27:50,640 --> 01:27:55,120
there's almost no food. We're going 
out this evening to find snails.'

870
01:27:56,320 --> 01:28:01,040
The captain wiped the sweat from his forehead 
and said, 'Permit me to come and help.'

871
01:28:02,320 --> 01:28:09,440
So in the evening, an hour before sunset, Pelagia 
and her father, Lemoni and the captain climbed  

872
01:28:09,440 --> 01:28:15,040
over a low wall and then began crawling through 
impossibly thick undergrowth in their search for  

873
01:28:15,040 --> 01:28:21,920
snails. It became immediately apparent that there 
were quantities of snails everywhere they looked.  

874
01:28:22,720 --> 01:28:28,432
The child and three adults became so involved 
in their task that they did not notice they  

875
01:28:28,432 --> 01:28:33,840
had become separated. The captain found 
himself on his own and paused for a second,  

876
01:28:34,560 --> 01:28:38,480
realizing that he could not remember 
ever having felt so content.

877
01:28:40,160 --> 01:28:44,720
'Oh, oh no,' came Pelagia's voice from nearby.

878
01:28:45,840 --> 01:28:50,400
Fearing that perhaps she had been hurt, the 
captain crawled towards the place where her  

879
01:28:50,400 --> 01:28:55,760
voice had come from and found her unable 
to move, her hair caught in some briars,  

880
01:28:55,760 --> 01:29:00,480
her neck pulled backwards. 
'Don't laugh,' she said crossly.

881
01:29:01,360 --> 01:29:06,240
'I'm not laughing,' he said, laughing. 
'I was afraid you were hurt.'

882
01:29:07,120 --> 01:29:10,880
'If you don't help me, I'll 
murder you. Just stop laughing.'

883
01:29:11,680 --> 01:29:16,800
'Hold still,' he told her, and reaching 
over her shoulders he began to pull the  

884
01:29:16,800 --> 01:29:24,000
hair out piece by piece, as gently as he could. 
'I've done it,' he said, pleased with himself,  

885
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:30,080
and as he drew back and his lips passed her 
cheek, he kissed it tenderly, before the ear.

886
01:29:31,600 --> 01:29:34,640
She touched her fingertips to 
the place of the kiss, and said,  

887
01:29:35,200 --> 01:29:38,640
shaking her head at him, 'You 
shouldn't have done that.'

888
01:29:40,080 --> 01:29:45,840
He knelt back and held her gaze with his 
own. 'I couldn't help it. I'm sorry.'

889
01:29:47,280 --> 01:29:53,360
They looked at one another for a long moment, 
and then Pelagia began to cry. 'What's the  

890
01:29:53,360 --> 01:29:59,680
matter?' asked Corelli, frowning in concern as 
Pelagia's tears rolled down her cheeks and fell  

891
01:29:59,680 --> 01:30:05,840
into the bucket among the snails. 'You're drowning 
them,' he said, pointing. 'What's the matter?'

892
01:30:07,440 --> 01:30:15,280
She gave a sad smile, and started crying again. 
He took her in his arms and patted her back.  

893
01:30:16,240 --> 01:30:22,880
Suddenly she said, 'I can't stand it 
any more, not any of it. I'm sorry.'

894
01:30:24,640 --> 01:30:30,400
'Everything is horrible,' agreed the captain, 
wondering if he too might start to cry.  

895
01:30:31,520 --> 01:30:37,200
He took her head gently in his hands and 
touched at the tears with his lips. She  

896
01:30:37,200 --> 01:30:42,480
gazed at him wonderingly and suddenly they 
found themselves underneath the briars,  

897
01:30:42,480 --> 01:30:52,080
in the sunset, surrounded by escaping snails, 
deep in their first, secret, guilty kiss. Hungry  

898
01:30:52,080 --> 01:30:58,160
and desperate, filled with light, they could 
not move away from each other, and when finally  

899
01:30:58,160 --> 01:31:03,920
they returned home, they brought back fewer 
snails together than Lemoni brought on her own.

900
01:31:05,920 --> 01:31:13,440
They became lovers in the old-fashioned sense. 
Their idea of making love was to kiss in the dark  

901
01:31:13,440 --> 01:31:20,800
under the trees or sit on a rock watching the sea. 
He loved her too much to risk her unhappiness,  

902
01:31:21,440 --> 01:31:28,240
and she had too much sense to take risks. Again 
and again she had seen the tragedy of girls with  

903
01:31:28,240 --> 01:31:33,600
an unwanted child and the poisoned deaths of 
girls who had tried to end their pregnancies.

904
01:31:35,360 --> 01:31:41,840
It was hard for Pelagia to love an invader and 
sometimes she shouted at Corelli, her eyes filled  

905
01:31:41,840 --> 01:31:48,720
with tears of anger: 'How can you bear to be 
here? Orders? Orders from a madman! Don't you  

906
01:31:48,720 --> 01:31:54,720
know you're being used? Why don't you take your 
guns and leave? Don't you know who the enemy is?'

907
01:31:56,320 --> 01:32:02,400
At these times the captain listened silently and 
bowed his head, the bitterness of his shame eating  

908
01:32:02,400 --> 01:32:08,000
like a worm at the muscles of his heart. But they 
could not stop themselves from loving one another.

909
01:32:09,600 --> 01:32:12,880
Gunter Weber managed to obtain 
a motorcycle for the captain,  

910
01:32:12,880 --> 01:32:17,280
who turned up outside the doctor's 
house one day wearing a cap and goggles.

911
01:32:18,480 --> 01:32:20,800
'Do you want to come for a ride?' he asked.

912
01:32:21,520 --> 01:32:22,720
Pelagia crossed her arms.  

913
01:32:23,520 --> 01:32:29,040
'I've never been on one. In fact I've never 
been in a car either and I'm not starting now.'

914
01:32:30,080 --> 01:32:33,280
'I've never been on one either,' 
he said, 'but it's very easy.'

915
01:32:34,160 --> 01:32:36,400
'Somebody might see us,' said Pelagia.

916
01:32:37,200 --> 01:32:42,240
The captain solved this problem by bringing 
Pelagia a disguise consisting of a cap,  

917
01:32:42,240 --> 01:32:45,840
goggles and a long leather coat, and the next day  

918
01:32:45,840 --> 01:32:51,600
they met around the bend of the road and 
rode off on the bike. They fell off twice,  

919
01:32:51,600 --> 01:32:58,080
without injury, and she gripped his waist, 
whitefaced with terror. She climbed off,  

920
01:32:58,080 --> 01:33:04,800
shaking, and realized she could not wait to get 
back on; it was splendid to ride a motorcycle.

921
01:33:06,560 --> 01:33:11,680
They went to places where Pelagia could not have 
been recognized and to places that were deserted,  

922
01:33:12,400 --> 01:33:17,680
and there she would put her arm through his and 
walk beside him, leaning her weight against his  

923
01:33:17,680 --> 01:33:23,600
shoulder, always laughing. With him, she 
would always remember that she laughed.  

924
01:33:24,880 --> 01:33:31,280
One day they discovered a ruined hut so old that 
the floor had sunk into the earth. They called it  

925
01:33:31,280 --> 01:33:37,200
'Casa Nostra', and in this secret house they would 
spread a blanket and lie embracing and talking.

926
01:33:38,160 --> 01:33:41,680
All their lovers' talk began 
with the phrase, 'After the war'.

927
01:33:42,800 --> 01:33:49,360
'After the war, when we are married, let's go to 
America; I've got relatives in Chicago. After the  

928
01:33:49,360 --> 01:33:53,920
war we won't bring up our children with any 
religion, they can make their own minds up  

929
01:33:53,920 --> 01:34:00,240
when they're older. After the war, we'll go all 
over Europe and you can give concerts in hotels  

930
01:34:00,240 --> 01:34:06,880
and that's how we'll live. After the war I'll 
love you, I'll love you forever after the war.'

931
01:34:08,680 --> 01:34:09,680
***

932
01:34:09,680 --> 01:34:13,520
It was during this period of 
happiness for Pelagia and the captain  

933
01:34:13,520 --> 01:34:17,840
that Dr Iannis was woken one night 
by a gentle tapping on his window.  

934
01:34:18,800 --> 01:34:25,760
Puzzled, the doctor looked out and saw a villager 
accompanied by a very tall fair-haired man wearing  

935
01:34:25,760 --> 01:34:31,840
the Greek national costume, something that a 
wealthy man might wear once a year on a feast day.  

936
01:34:33,200 --> 01:34:37,760
'We thought you were the man to help him,' the 
villager told the doctor, before departing.  

937
01:34:38,880 --> 01:34:46,080
The tall stranger smiled and held out his hand, 
speaking in an extraordinarily old-fashioned Greek  

938
01:34:46,080 --> 01:34:51,680
that the doctor found almost impossible 
to understand. The stranger then climbed,  

939
01:34:51,680 --> 01:34:57,680
uninvited, through the doctor's window into the 
house, and took a huge radio out of his bag.  

940
01:34:58,640 --> 01:35:02,000
Pelagia woke and came into her father's room,  

941
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:06,880
saw the stranger and put her hand over 
her mouth, wide-eyed with amazement.

942
01:35:07,440 --> 01:35:09,840
'Who's this?' she demanded of her father.

943
01:35:10,640 --> 01:35:14,240
'How am I supposed to know,' 
replied the doctor. 'He  

944
01:35:14,240 --> 01:35:18,880
says he's called Bunnios and he 
talks Greek like a Spanish cow.'

945
01:35:19,920 --> 01:35:25,600
The stranger bowed politely and shook 
Pelagia's hand, then smiled charmingly  

946
01:35:25,600 --> 01:35:29,360
and said, 'Greek of the old days. Homer.'

947
01:35:30,320 --> 01:35:32,960
'Ancient Greek?' exclaimed Pelagia,  

948
01:35:32,960 --> 01:35:39,040
disbelievingly. The doctor tapped his 
finger to his forehead. 'English?' he asked.

949
01:35:39,760 --> 01:35:43,040
'English,' agreed the man. 
'But, I must beg you...'

950
01:35:43,600 --> 01:35:45,280
'Of course we won't tell anyone.'

951
01:35:46,480 --> 01:35:52,000
The man smiled. It had been an awful 
burden to speak the finest ancient Greek  

952
01:35:52,000 --> 01:35:53,120
and not be understood.

953
01:35:55,440 --> 01:35:59,920
'We are having an Italian officer sleeping 
in a room,' said the doctor, whose English  

954
01:35:59,920 --> 01:36:06,160
was not as good as he liked to believe, 'so we 
are being very quiet, please. Are you a spy?'

955
01:36:07,040 --> 01:36:12,960
The man nodded and asked, 'Do you have any 
clothes I could have? I would be so grateful.'

956
01:36:14,080 --> 01:36:19,520
The Englishman departed for the town of Argostoli 
at dawn, wearing trousers that ended half way  

957
01:36:19,520 --> 01:36:27,440
down his legs, and having received some good 
advice from the doctor: 'Look, OK? You accent  

958
01:36:27,440 --> 01:36:34,640
terrible-terrible. Not to talk, understand? 
You are quiet until you learning. Also,  

959
01:36:34,640 --> 01:36:41,120
you watch out Communists - they thieves. 
Italians OK, Germans not good, see?'

960
01:36:42,640 --> 01:36:48,720
Bunnios, whose real name was Bunny Warren, 
soon found an empty hut in the hills where,  

961
01:36:48,720 --> 01:36:54,080
using his huge radio, he reported in 
great detail to his British masters,  

962
01:36:54,080 --> 01:36:58,560
informing them of troop movements 
in the area. He also set himself  

963
01:36:58,560 --> 01:37:03,360
the task of learning modern Greek, and was 
assisted in this by the willing islanders.

964
01:37:04,520 --> 01:37:05,520
***

965
01:37:05,520 --> 01:37:10,080
The captain's opera group, La Scala, became 
accustomed to meeting in the doctor's house.

966
01:37:11,440 --> 01:37:14,720
'Your soldiers are stealing from 
people's vegetable patches, when  

967
01:37:14,720 --> 01:37:19,840
we're dying of hunger already,' said the doctor 
to Corelli one day, when the group was there.

968
01:37:20,400 --> 01:37:24,480
'If it's true, they will be 
punished,' the captain replied,  

969
01:37:24,480 --> 01:37:29,040
already deeply shamed and embarrassed 
by the fact that some nights previously  

970
01:37:29,040 --> 01:37:34,320
someone, obviously an Italian 
soldier, had stolen Pelagia's goat.

971
01:37:34,320 --> 01:37:39,520
'We Germans do not do this,' said Gunter 
Weber, with a pleased expression on his face.

972
01:37:40,480 --> 01:37:43,120
'Germans can't sing,' replied Corelli,  

973
01:37:43,120 --> 01:37:48,400
'and anyway, I'll get this investigated 
and I'll put a stop to it. It's too bad.'

974
01:37:49,440 --> 01:37:54,800
Weber smiled. 'You are very famous for 
defending the rights of the Greeks.  

975
01:37:54,800 --> 01:37:57,600
I wonder if sometimes you 
understand why you are here.'

976
01:37:58,800 --> 01:38:03,520
'I try to think of it as a holiday. I 
don't have your advantages, Gunter.'

977
01:38:04,160 --> 01:38:04,880
'Advantages?'

978
01:38:05,840 --> 01:38:11,680
'Yes. I don't have the advantage of thinking 
that other races are inferior to mine.'

979
01:38:12,720 --> 01:38:17,360
'It's a question of science,' said Weber. 
'You can't alter a scientific fact.'

980
01:38:18,160 --> 01:38:20,480
Corelli frowned. 'Science?  

981
01:38:21,280 --> 01:38:26,160
I don't care about science. Moral 
principles are important, not science.'

982
01:38:26,960 --> 01:38:32,720
'We disagree,' said Weber in a friendly fashion. 
'Science tells us that the strong survive.  

983
01:38:33,280 --> 01:38:36,960
Strength needs no excuses and 
doesn't have to give reasons.'

984
01:38:37,840 --> 01:38:41,680
'Science is about facts, and 
morality is about values,'  

985
01:38:41,680 --> 01:38:43,840
said Carlo, who had been listening closely.

986
01:38:45,120 --> 01:38:48,880
'It's also a matter of being able to 
live with yourself,' Corelli added.

987
01:38:49,840 --> 01:38:55,200
'You're a good man,' said Gunter, 'I admit 
it. Why don't I get my record player from  

988
01:38:55,200 --> 01:39:01,760
my car and we can all sing with Marlene 
Dietrich.' He went to his car and proudly  

989
01:39:01,760 --> 01:39:06,560
returned with the record player, which he 
put down on the table. He put on the record  

990
01:39:07,120 --> 01:39:13,280
and Dietrich began to sing, her voice full of 
the sadness of knowledge, the longing for love.

991
01:39:14,080 --> 01:39:22,640
'Oh,' exclaimed Weber, 'her voice makes 
me melt,' and Corelli said, 'Antonia likes  

992
01:39:22,640 --> 01:39:28,880
this. She's going to sing.' He began to 
accompany the song, playing so beautifully  

993
01:39:28,880 --> 01:39:34,160
that in the village people stopped what they were 
doing and listened to Corelli fill the night.  

994
01:39:35,360 --> 01:39:39,840
Pelagia left the kitchen, her form 
ghostlike in the light of the candles.  

995
01:39:40,800 --> 01:39:45,760
'Please play that song again,' she 
asked Weber. 'It was so beautiful.'

996
01:39:46,720 --> 01:39:53,520
'Do you like it?' asked Weber, and she nodded. 
'All right,' he continued, 'when I go home after  

997
01:39:53,520 --> 01:39:58,240
the war, I'll leave it with you. It would 
please me very much for you to have it.'

998
01:39:59,360 --> 01:40:05,200
Pelagia was delighted. She looked at the smiling 
boy with his smart uniform and blond hair  

999
01:40:05,200 --> 01:40:11,360
and was filled with pleasure. 'You're so sweet,' 
she said, and kissed him naturally on the cheek,  

1000
01:40:11,920 --> 01:40:17,760
so that the boys of La Scala cheered and 
Weber went red and hid his eyes with his hand.

1001
01:40:19,240 --> 01:40:20,240
***

1002
01:40:20,240 --> 01:40:25,360
The time came when the doctor decided that it was 
necessary to discuss certain matters with Pelagia.  

1003
01:40:26,480 --> 01:40:29,360
'There's something I have to 
talk to you about,' he told her.  

1004
01:40:30,080 --> 01:40:34,320
'It has not escaped my notice that you 
have fallen in love with the captain.'

1005
01:40:35,680 --> 01:40:42,400
She went violently red and looked terribly 
shocked. 'The captain?' she said foolishly.

1006
01:40:43,520 --> 01:40:50,720
He began a long speech. 'It's not that I don't 
like the captain. Of course, he's a little mad,  

1007
01:40:50,720 --> 01:40:56,560
which is quite simply explained by the fact that 
he is Italian. In fact I like him very much,  

1008
01:40:57,360 --> 01:41:02,640
but you must remember that you are 
engaged to Mandras, and technically,  

1009
01:41:02,640 --> 01:41:08,400
the captain is an enemy. Can you imagine the pain 
you will suffer when people discover that you  

1010
01:41:08,400 --> 01:41:15,120
have given up the love of a Greek in favour of an 
invader? People will throw stones at you and spit,  

1011
01:41:15,120 --> 01:41:20,400
you know that, don't you? You would have to move 
away to Italy if you wanted to stay with him,  

1012
01:41:20,400 --> 01:41:26,080
because here you might not be safe. Are you 
prepared to leave this island and this people?

1013
01:41:27,040 --> 01:41:33,200
'And another thing. Love is a temporary madness. 
When it ends you have to work out whether your  

1014
01:41:33,200 --> 01:41:38,480
roots have so joined together that it is 
unimaginable that you should ever separate.  

1015
01:41:39,360 --> 01:41:46,960
Because that is what love is. Love isn't 
breathlessness, it is not excitement,  

1016
01:41:46,960 --> 01:41:52,320
it is not lying awake at night imagining that 
he is kissing every part of your body. No,  

1017
01:41:52,320 --> 01:41:58,720
don't look so embarrassed, I'm telling you 
some truths. That is just being "in love",  

1018
01:41:58,720 --> 01:42:05,360
which any fool can do. Love itself is what is 
left over when being in love has burned away.

1019
01:42:06,960 --> 01:42:11,840
'I say to you that to marry the captain is 
impossible until our country is free again.  

1020
01:42:12,880 --> 01:42:18,400
I would be happy for you to do this, but this 
means that you have a love that will be delayed.  

1021
01:42:19,280 --> 01:42:26,320
Pelagia, you know as well as I do that love 
delayed means that physical passion increases. No,  

1022
01:42:26,960 --> 01:42:32,320
don't look at me like that. Do you think I don't 
know that young girls can be eaten by desire?  

1023
01:42:33,360 --> 01:42:39,200
Imagine if you got pregnant, what would you do? 
I would not assist in the murder of an innocent.  

1024
01:42:40,000 --> 01:42:45,920
Would you have the child, and then find that no 
man would ever marry you? I would not abandon you  

1025
01:42:45,920 --> 01:42:52,160
as long as I live, even under such circumstances. 
But imagine if I should die. What then?'

1026
01:42:53,920 --> 01:43:01,200
Pelagia had never felt so crushed in all her 
life and wept bitterly, but when she looked up,  

1027
01:43:01,200 --> 01:43:03,680
she found her father looking 
at her sympathetically.  

1028
01:43:04,560 --> 01:43:09,840
'You make everything sound so disgusting,' 
she said. 'You don't know how it is.'

1029
01:43:10,400 --> 01:43:13,040
'I went through a lot of this 
with your mother,' he replied.  

1030
01:43:13,760 --> 01:43:17,600
'She was engaged to someone 
else. I do know how it is.'

1031
01:43:18,640 --> 01:43:22,080
'You don't forbid everything 
then?' she asked hopefully.

1032
01:43:23,120 --> 01:43:30,560
'No, I don't forbid everything. I say you 
must be careful and act honourably to Mandras.  

1033
01:43:31,440 --> 01:43:35,520
Don't give in to your desires, that's 
all. The captain is a good man.  

1034
01:43:36,240 --> 01:43:41,040
Pray for our freedom, Pelagia, because 
then everything becomes possible.'

1035
01:43:42,320 --> 01:43:49,600
Pelagia stood up to go and her father said, 'I 
did not intend to upset you. I was young once.'

1036
01:43:51,040 --> 01:43:55,120
'Not everything was different in your 
day, then,' she said as she left the room,  

1037
01:43:55,760 --> 01:44:00,480
and her father smiled, pleased that his 
words had not crushed his daughter's spirit.

1038
01:44:01,960 --> 01:44:02,960
***

1039
01:44:02,960 --> 01:44:07,840
The doctor and the captain were sitting indoors 
at the kitchen table while the latter was removing  

1040
01:44:07,840 --> 01:44:13,840
a broken string from his mandolin. The doctor 
leaned back and sighed, then suddenly asked,  

1041
01:44:14,720 --> 01:44:20,480
'Are you and Pelagia planning to be married? 
As her father, I think I have a right to know.'

1042
01:44:21,600 --> 01:44:26,400
The captain was so surprised by the frankness 
of the question that he was unable to think  

1043
01:44:26,400 --> 01:44:32,560
of a reply. His relationship with Pelagia 
had only been able to proceed on the basis  

1044
01:44:32,560 --> 01:44:38,080
that no one ever brought the issue out into 
the open. He looked at the doctor anxiously.

1045
01:44:39,200 --> 01:44:43,360
'You can't live here,' said the 
doctor. He pointed to the mandolin.  

1046
01:44:44,240 --> 01:44:49,440
'If you want to be a musician, this is the 
last place to be. And I don't think that  

1047
01:44:49,440 --> 01:44:55,280
Pelagia could live in Italy. She is a Greek. 
She would die like a flower without sunlight.'

1048
01:44:56,320 --> 01:45:01,920
'Ah,' said the captain, for the 
lack of any intelligent remark.

1049
01:45:01,920 --> 01:45:07,440
'It's true,' said the doctor. 'I know you 
have not thought about it. Italians always  

1050
01:45:07,440 --> 01:45:16,000
act without thinking. Anyway, Pelagia is 
a Greek, that's my point. So can it work?'

1051
01:45:16,000 --> 01:45:22,080
There was a silence between the two 
men. 'I love her,' said Corelli at last,  

1052
01:45:22,720 --> 01:45:26,720
as if this were the answer to 
the problem, which to him it was.

1053
01:45:27,680 --> 01:45:32,640
'I know that. You'd have to live here, 
that's all,' said the doctor. 'You might  

1054
01:45:32,640 --> 01:45:36,160
have to choose between loving 
her and becoming a musician.'

1055
01:45:37,760 --> 01:45:44,400
The doctor left the room, more for dramatic effect 
than for any other purpose, and then came back in.  

1056
01:45:45,200 --> 01:45:49,600
'And another thing. This is a very ancient land  

1057
01:45:49,600 --> 01:45:55,440
and we've had nothing except murder for two 
thousand years. We've got so many places full  

1058
01:45:55,440 --> 01:46:01,760
of bitter ghosts that anyone who goes near them 
or lives in them becomes heartless or insane.  

1059
01:46:02,880 --> 01:46:06,960
I don't believe in God, captain, 
but I do believe in ghosts.  

1060
01:46:07,760 --> 01:46:13,760
And there will be many more deaths. It's only a 
question of time. So don't make any plans.'
 
 
 

