CHAPTER NINE

1062
01:46:19,360 --> 01:46:22,480
Autumn 1943: Betrayal

1063
01:46:24,400 --> 01:46:30,400
The Allies invaded Sicily, Italy's southern 
island, and so they betrayed their most  

1064
01:46:30,400 --> 01:46:36,960
loyal and courageous friend, Greece, and 
did not come to its aid. The angry Greeks  

1065
01:46:36,960 --> 01:46:42,800
demanded to know why their country, which was 
occupied by the Italians, had been ignored,  

1066
01:46:42,800 --> 01:46:49,760
and received no answers. The Allies had abandoned 
Greece, the little nation that had given Europe  

1067
01:46:49,760 --> 01:46:56,320
its culture and its heart. To make matters 
worse, during this period the Greek Communists  

1068
01:46:56,320 --> 01:47:02,800
were committing unimaginably vicious acts, but 
for a long time the world did not believe it.

1069
01:47:04,640 --> 01:47:08,480
On Cephallonia, the Italian 
soldiers listened to their radios  

1070
01:47:08,480 --> 01:47:13,120
and followed the course of Allied progress 
up Italy, their homeland, while the German  

1071
01:47:13,120 --> 01:47:19,840
soldiers were angered and disgusted by the Italian 
army's lack of resistance to the Allies. Corelli  

1072
01:47:19,840 --> 01:47:26,400
and his brother officers sensed ice in the air, 
and visits between the Germans and the Italians  

1073
01:47:26,400 --> 01:47:35,920
became less frequent. When Weber turned up at 
meetings of La Scala, he seemed quiet and distant.

1074
01:47:35,920 --> 01:47:39,520
'What happens,' Corelli asked 
Pelagia with a troubled look,  

1075
01:47:40,240 --> 01:47:42,560
'when we have to surrender before the Germans do?'

1076
01:47:43,200 --> 01:47:44,160
'We'll get married.'

1077
01:47:44,960 --> 01:47:51,120
He shook his head sadly. 'It's going to be a 
complete mess. There's no chance of the British  

1078
01:47:51,120 --> 01:47:56,880
coming. They're going straight for Rome. No 
one will save us unless we save ourselves.  

1079
01:47:57,760 --> 01:48:01,600
We should attack the Germans on the island 
now, while there aren't many of them,  

1080
01:48:02,160 --> 01:48:07,520
but our generals don't do anything. 
They say we should trust the Germans.'

1081
01:48:08,560 --> 01:48:09,680
'Don't you trust them?'

1082
01:48:10,400 --> 01:48:11,680
'I'm not stupid.'

1083
01:48:12,480 --> 01:48:15,200
'Come inside,' she said, 'my father's out.'

1084
01:48:16,400 --> 01:48:21,360
'There's no point. My mind is just 
a blank that's filled with worry.'

1085
01:48:22,880 --> 01:48:25,280
Corelli came to the doctor's house less often,  

1086
01:48:25,920 --> 01:48:30,880
and day and night he trained his men, working 
them hard in the terrible August heat,  

1087
01:48:31,440 --> 01:48:36,800
so that the sweat ran down their faces and arms, 
and the sun burned the flesh of their shoulders.  

1088
01:48:37,760 --> 01:48:42,400
They did not complain. They knew that 
the captain was right to prepare them.

1089
01:48:44,000 --> 01:48:50,240
He himself stopped playing the mandolin; there was 
so little time for it that when he picked it up  

1090
01:48:50,240 --> 01:48:57,360
it felt foreign in his fingers in comparison with 
a gun. He went home to Pelagia on his motorbike at  

1091
01:48:57,360 --> 01:49:03,680
times when her father was likely to be out, and 
he brought her bread, honey, bottles of wine,  

1092
01:49:03,680 --> 01:49:09,520
a photograph signed on the back with the words 
'After the War...' written on it in his elegant,  

1093
01:49:09,520 --> 01:49:15,680
foreign-looking handwriting, and he brought her 
his tired, grey face, and his saddened eyes.

1094
01:49:17,200 --> 01:49:23,760
'My poor darling,' she would say, her arms about 
his neck, 'don't worry, don't worry, don't worry,'  

1095
01:49:24,640 --> 01:49:29,760
and he would move back a little and say, 
'Koritsimou, let me just look at you.'

1096
01:49:31,280 --> 01:49:37,440
And then came the time when Carlo was listening 
to the radio, trying to find a signal. It was 8  

1097
01:49:37,440 --> 01:49:41,840
September, and the evenings had become 
much cooler than they had been before.  

1098
01:49:43,120 --> 01:49:49,680
Carlo had recently been thinking about Francesco 
and about the horror of Albania, and now more than  

1099
01:49:49,680 --> 01:49:55,520
ever he knew that it had all been a waste, and 
that his time in Cephallonia had been a holiday  

1100
01:49:55,520 --> 01:50:03,840
from a war that was going to destroy his life once 
more, perhaps forever. He found a voice and turned  

1101
01:50:03,840 --> 01:50:10,640
up the volume: '... all aggressive acts by Italian 
Armed Forces against the forces of the British and  

1102
01:50:10,640 --> 01:50:17,760
the Americans will cease at once, everywhere.' The 
Italians had formally surrendered to the Allies.

1103
01:50:19,200 --> 01:50:24,880
Outside, the bells of the island began to 
ring; they rang all over the island in the  

1104
01:50:24,880 --> 01:50:33,680
towns of Argostoli, Lixouri, Soulari, Dorizata. 
On the radio there was a message from Eisenhower,  

1105
01:50:33,680 --> 01:50:38,880
the American president: '... All Italians 
who take steps to rid themselves of the  

1106
01:50:38,880 --> 01:50:44,080
German presence in their country will have 
the assistance and support of the Allies...'

1107
01:50:45,360 --> 01:50:51,840
Carlo ran out and found Corelli just arriving on 
his bike, a great cloud of blue smoke behind him.  

1108
01:50:52,960 --> 01:50:58,960
'Antonio, Antonio, it's all over, and the 
Allies have promised to help us,' he cried.  

1109
01:50:59,760 --> 01:51:06,480
He threw his enormous arms around the man he loved 
and picked him up, dancing in a circle. 'Carlo,  

1110
01:51:06,480 --> 01:51:13,120
Carlo,' the captain cried, 'put me down. Don't 
get so excited. The Allies don't care about us.  

1111
01:51:13,680 --> 01:51:19,840
We're in Greece, remember. Carlo, you don't 
know your own strength. You half killed me.'

1112
01:51:21,440 --> 01:51:25,120
'They'll help us,' said Carlo, 
but Corelli shook his head.  

1113
01:51:26,080 --> 01:51:31,440
'If we don't act now, we're finished. We've got to 
get the Germans on the island to surrender to us.'

1114
01:51:33,680 --> 01:51:38,080
That night the Italian warships in the 
harbours of the island sailed for home,  

1115
01:51:38,640 --> 01:51:45,040
without informing anyone they were going, or 
taking with them a single Italian soldier. In  

1116
01:51:45,040 --> 01:51:51,200
a terrible act of cowardice, the warships withdrew 
their protection from the soldiers on the island,  

1117
01:51:51,200 --> 01:51:57,840
so that the German soldiers laughed and 
Corelli's men smelled betrayal. Corelli waited  

1118
01:51:57,840 --> 01:52:02,640
at the telephone for orders, and when 
none came he fell asleep in his chair.

1119
01:52:04,160 --> 01:52:09,200
Carlo, now realizing that Corelli's 
pessimistic predictions were probably correct,  

1120
01:52:09,760 --> 01:52:14,800
wrote his captain a long letter in which 
he declared his undying love for him  

1121
01:52:14,800 --> 01:52:21,600
and also his unselfish hope that Corelli would 
find true happiness with Pelagia. Strangely  

1122
01:52:21,600 --> 01:52:27,440
convinced that he was going to die soon, Carlo 
added this letter to his other writings and  

1123
01:52:27,440 --> 01:52:31,680
brought them to the doctor's house, with the 
request that his papers should be placed in  

1124
01:52:31,680 --> 01:52:36,640
the hiding-hole under the trapdoor and only 
opened and read in the event of his death.

1125
01:52:38,080 --> 01:52:45,040
Like Corelli, Gunter Weber also slept from time to 
time in his chair, waiting for orders, desperately  

1126
01:52:45,040 --> 01:52:52,560
tired and with all his confidence gone. He 
missed his Italian friends, but worse than that,  

1127
01:52:52,560 --> 01:52:59,680
his country was losing and he no longer felt proud 
and full of strength. He felt inferior and so  

1128
01:52:59,680 --> 01:53:05,760
betrayed by his country's allies, the Italians, 
that if he had been a woman he would have wept.  

1129
01:53:06,800 --> 01:53:12,000
He tried to pray but the words 
turned bitter in his mouth.

1130
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:15,600
Corelli stopped his motorcycle 
on his way back to camp  

1131
01:53:15,600 --> 01:53:21,760
and beneath the shade of a tree, by a ruined wall, 
he sat and thought about going back to Italy,  

1132
01:53:22,320 --> 01:53:30,560
about surviving, about Pelagia. The truth 
was that he had no home and that was why  

1133
01:53:30,560 --> 01:53:36,000
he never talked about it. Mussolini 
had forced his family to move to Libya,  

1134
01:53:36,000 --> 01:53:42,000
and there they had been attacked by rebels and had 
died, while he lay in hospital with a high fever.

1135
01:53:43,760 --> 01:53:47,680
Of all the relatives' houses where 
he had stayed, which one was home?  

1136
01:53:48,480 --> 01:53:54,800
He had no family except his soldiers and his 
mandolin, and his heart was there in Greece.  

1137
01:53:55,920 --> 01:54:02,720
Had he suffered so much pain, so much loneliness, 
had he finally found a place to be, only to have  

1138
01:54:02,720 --> 01:54:09,280
it torn away? His memories of his parents were 
as thin and indefinite as those of a ghost,  

1139
01:54:10,160 --> 01:54:15,280
and for the first time he began to feel as 
if Pelagia already belonged to his past.  

1140
01:54:16,160 --> 01:54:21,360
He thought about dying and wondered how 
long Pelagia would weep, and what a shame  

1141
01:54:21,360 --> 01:54:27,440
it would be to spoil her lovely flesh with 
tears; it broke his heart to imagine it.  

1142
01:54:28,640 --> 01:54:35,840
He wanted to reach out from beyond the grave and 
comfort her, even though he was not yet dead.

1143
01:54:35,840 --> 01:54:41,040
He went to the doctor's house and asked 
them to look after his mandolin, and Pelagia  

1144
01:54:41,040 --> 01:54:44,080
wrapped it in a blanket and put 
it under the hole in the floor.  

1145
01:54:45,120 --> 01:54:49,840
They told him about Carlo's visit, and how 
he had left a thick pile of papers with them.  

1146
01:54:51,280 --> 01:54:56,960
The captain had not known that Carlo had ambitions 
to be a writer and was curious about the content  

1147
01:54:56,960 --> 01:55:02,560
of the big man's papers. He thought that 
Pelagia looked very thin and almost ill,  

1148
01:55:03,200 --> 01:55:08,320
and when she sadly stroked his cheek, he 
almost did not know how to prevent his tears.

1149
01:55:09,800 --> 01:55:10,800
***

1150
01:55:10,800 --> 01:55:15,680
After Italy's surrender to the Allies, 
General Gandin, leader of the Italian troops  

1151
01:55:15,680 --> 01:55:20,720
on Cephallonia, suffered terrible indecision 
about the course of action he should take.  

1152
01:55:21,520 --> 01:55:26,880
He had two choices. Compared to the 
number of Italian soldiers on the island,  

1153
01:55:26,880 --> 01:55:30,400
there were many fewer German 
troops, and he could insist  

1154
01:55:30,400 --> 01:55:35,760
that the German soldiers laid down their arms 
and surrendered to the superior Italian forces.  

1155
01:55:36,720 --> 01:55:42,000
If the Germans rejected this, then the 
Italian troops could theoretically attack  

1156
01:55:42,000 --> 01:55:47,920
and overcome them. But Gandin knew that he 
would receive no support from the Allies,  

1157
01:55:47,920 --> 01:55:54,880
and moreover, that he would have neither air nor 
sea support from his own country. He knew that the  

1158
01:55:54,880 --> 01:56:00,720
Germans still had a large number of bomber planes 
based in mainland Greece, and the thought of  

1159
01:56:00,720 --> 01:56:06,240
those death machines screaming over the island as 
they dropped their bombs filled him with horror.

1160
01:56:07,920 --> 01:56:14,000
These thoughts led the General to the second 
option, which was to surrender to the Germans,  

1161
01:56:14,000 --> 01:56:19,520
on condition that the latter gave written 
guarantees of the safety of the Italian soldiers  

1162
01:56:19,520 --> 01:56:24,800
on the island. This would mean trusting 
the Germans not to break their promises  

1163
01:56:24,800 --> 01:56:32,240
and attack the Italians. It was this second 
route that Gandin was tempted to take. He was,  

1164
01:56:32,240 --> 01:56:37,600
in a strange way, a man of honour, and still 
considered the Germans to be his allies.

1165
01:56:39,440 --> 01:56:45,120
Unlike General Gandin, the Italian troops on 
Cephallonia knew exactly what should be done.  

1166
01:56:46,000 --> 01:56:51,600
They heard from the radio that the Germans, as 
they withdrew in Italy, were killing and looting  

1167
01:56:51,600 --> 01:56:57,120
along the way and they could see no reason why 
the Germans would not do the same in Cephallonia,  

1168
01:56:57,120 --> 01:57:04,480
given the chance. While Gandin delayed, unable to 
make up his mind, and his soldiers became almost  

1169
01:57:04,480 --> 01:57:10,480
crazy with anger and fear, the Germans quietly 
flew more arms and troops to the island.

1170
01:57:11,760 --> 01:57:18,720
Finally General Gandin came to a decision. Despite 
the universal demand of his men that the Germans  

1171
01:57:18,720 --> 01:57:23,760
should be forced to surrender, the General 
agreed with the German leaders on the island  

1172
01:57:23,760 --> 01:57:29,840
that the Italians should be allowed to keep their 
weapons and peacefully leave Cephallonia. There  

1173
01:57:29,840 --> 01:57:36,560
were no ships, however, to take the Italians away, 
a point which did not seem significant to Gandin.  

1174
01:57:37,680 --> 01:57:43,200
Some of the Italian troops, guessing what was 
likely to happen, became deeply depressed,  

1175
01:57:43,840 --> 01:57:49,920
while others, like Corelli, developed an 
iron determination and prepared their men  

1176
01:57:49,920 --> 01:57:54,640
to the last degree for the terrible battle 
that they were certain lay ahead of them.

1177
01:57:55,920 --> 01:58:01,040
When the German bomber planes arrived, 
early in the afternoon, tipping their wings,  

1178
01:58:01,040 --> 01:58:09,680
it was almost a relief to the waiting Italians. 
Now everything was clear; it was at last obvious  

1179
01:58:09,680 --> 01:58:14,560
that the Germans had betrayed them and that 
every Italian soldier would have to fight for  

1180
01:58:14,560 --> 01:58:20,080
his life. Gunter Weber knew that he would 
have to turn his weapons on his friends.  

1181
01:58:21,120 --> 01:58:26,240
Corelli knew that his musician's fingers, 
so well accustomed to the arts of peace,  

1182
01:58:26,800 --> 01:58:34,080
must now tighten around a gun. General Gandin 
knew too late that he had made the wrong decision  

1183
01:58:34,080 --> 01:58:40,800
and that, as a result, his men were going 
to die. Pelagia knew that a war that had  

1184
01:58:40,800 --> 01:58:47,840
always been somewhere else would now settle 
upon her home and turn its stones to dust.

1185
01:58:49,200 --> 01:58:55,040
The German planes attacked Argostoli first 
because that was where most Italian troops  

1186
01:58:55,040 --> 01:59:00,080
were concentrated. Gandin made the 
foolish mistake of bringing his troops  

1187
01:59:00,080 --> 01:59:05,840
into the town in increasing numbers, and this 
made it easier for the Germans to isolate and  

1188
01:59:05,840 --> 01:59:13,760
cut them down. Houses were crushed by the bombs 
and soldiers and islanders died in large numbers.  

1189
01:59:14,800 --> 01:59:20,640
More and more German soldiers were flown in, and 
spread all over the island, killing as they went.  

1190
01:59:21,680 --> 01:59:27,120
Everyone knew that no ships or planes would come 
to aid an island of Cephallonia's insignificance.  

1191
01:59:28,160 --> 01:59:33,920
On a hillside, Bunny Warren sat by his 
radio and tried to persuade his superiors  

1192
01:59:33,920 --> 01:59:38,800
that they should provide the Italians with 
air and sea support, but without success.

1193
01:59:40,280 --> 01:59:41,280
***

1194
01:59:41,280 --> 01:59:47,120
Dr Iannis and his daughter sat side by side 
at their kitchen table, unable to sleep,  

1195
01:59:47,120 --> 01:59:54,320
holding each others' hands. Pelagia was 
weeping. The doctor wanted to relight his pipe,  

1196
01:59:54,320 --> 01:59:57,440
but out of respect for his daughter's feelings  

1197
01:59:57,440 --> 02:00:04,640
he allowed his hands to stay in hers, and he 
repeated, 'Koritsimou, I am sure he is all right.'

1198
02:00:05,600 --> 02:00:09,760
'But we haven't seen him for days,' 
she cried. 'I just know he's dead.'

1199
02:00:10,480 --> 02:00:14,640
'If he was dead someone would have 
told us, someone from La Scala.  

1200
02:00:14,640 --> 02:00:17,440
They were all nice boys, they would let us know.'

1201
02:00:18,480 --> 02:00:25,840
'Were?' she repeated. 'You think they're all 
dead? You think they're dead too, don't you?'

1202
02:00:26,640 --> 02:00:29,200
'Oh God,' the doctor sighed.

1203
02:00:30,880 --> 02:00:37,360
It was on the morning of 22 September that Captain 
Antonio Corelli, knowing that his leaders were  

1204
02:00:37,360 --> 02:00:43,760
planning to surrender to the Germans, having had 
no sleep for three days, climbed on his motorcycle  

1205
02:00:43,760 --> 02:00:49,840
and sped towards Pelagia's house. He threw 
himself into her arms, resting his burning  

1206
02:00:49,840 --> 02:00:56,560
eyes upon her shoulder, and told her, 'We 
are lost. The British have betrayed us.'

1207
02:00:57,760 --> 02:01:02,080
She begged him to stay, to hide in 
the house, in the hole in the floor,  

1208
02:01:02,080 --> 02:01:06,800
with his mandolin and Carlo's papers, 
but he took her face in his hands,  

1209
02:01:07,360 --> 02:01:12,880
kissed her without the tears that he was too 
tired to weep, and then rocked her in his arms,  

1210
02:01:12,880 --> 02:01:16,640
squeezing her so tightly that she 
thought that her bones would crack.  

1211
02:01:18,000 --> 02:01:24,320
He kissed her again and said, 'Koritsimou, 
this is the last time I shall ever see you.  

1212
02:01:25,280 --> 02:01:29,920
There has been no honour in this 
war, but I have to be with my boys.'  

1213
02:01:31,440 --> 02:01:36,160
With his head hanging down, 
he told her, 'Koritsimou,  

1214
02:01:36,160 --> 02:01:44,080
I am going to die. Remember me to your father. And 
I thank God I have lived long enough to love you.'

1215
02:01:45,840 --> 02:01:51,200
She watched him go as he drove away on his 
motorcycle, the dust cloud surrounding his  

1216
02:01:51,200 --> 02:01:57,920
head, then she went inside and sat at the 
kitchen table, terror gripping her heart.
 
 
 

1217
02:02:02,240 --> 02:02:03,040
CHAPTER TEN

1218
02:02:03,760 --> 02:02:04,880
The Order to Kill

1219
02:02:06,880 --> 02:02:12,880
Gunter Weber stood before his superior officer 
and, his face hard with determination, said,  

1220
02:02:14,000 --> 02:02:20,000
'Sir, I must request that you give this task 
to someone else. I cannot carry it out.'

1221
02:02:21,280 --> 02:02:25,600
His superior raised an eyebrow but 
somehow failed to feel any anger.  

1222
02:02:26,560 --> 02:02:31,840
The truth was that in this position he 
hoped that he would have done the same.

1223
02:02:32,880 --> 02:02:34,480
'Why not?' he asked.

1224
02:02:35,360 --> 02:02:39,520
'Sir, it is against international 
law to murder prisoners of war.  

1225
02:02:40,240 --> 02:02:44,000
It is also wrong. I must request to be excused.'

1226
02:02:44,960 --> 02:02:46,960
'They have betrayed us, their allies.'

1227
02:02:47,920 --> 02:02:53,440
'I realize that, but I am not a criminal, 
sir, and I do not wish to become one.'

1228
02:02:54,720 --> 02:03:03,280
The officer sighed. 'War is a dirty business, you 
know that. We all have to do terrible things. For  

1229
02:03:03,280 --> 02:03:11,200
example, I like you and I admire you for taking 
this position, but I must remind you that the  

1230
02:03:11,200 --> 02:03:17,680
punishment for refusing to obey an order is 
death. I don't state this as a threat but as  

1231
02:03:17,680 --> 02:03:25,520
a fact of life. You know this as well as I do.' He 
walked to the window and then turned. 'They're all  

1232
02:03:25,520 --> 02:03:31,840
going to be shot anyway. Why add your death to 
theirs? It would be a waste of a fine officer.'

1233
02:03:33,520 --> 02:03:38,640
Gunter Weber swallowed hard and his 
lips trembled so that he found it hard  

1234
02:03:38,640 --> 02:03:46,400
to speak. At last he said, 'I request that my 
protest is recorded and put in my file, sir.'

1235
02:03:47,440 --> 02:03:51,280
'Your request is granted,' said 
the officer and left the room.

1236
02:03:53,200 --> 02:03:55,840
Weber leaned against the wall and lit a cigarette,  

1237
02:03:56,560 --> 02:03:59,760
but his hands shook so much 
that he immediately dropped it.

1238
02:04:01,520 --> 02:04:07,600
'Let's sing, boys,' said Antonio Corelli, looking 
round the inside of the truck where his men sat,  

1239
02:04:08,160 --> 02:04:14,080
watched by expressionless German soldiers. 
One of the Italians was already tearful,  

1240
02:04:14,080 --> 02:04:17,120
others were praying, their 
heads bowed down to their knees.  

1241
02:04:18,240 --> 02:04:24,240
Corelli felt strangely happy as if he were 
drunk with tiredness and the absolute certainty  

1242
02:04:24,240 --> 02:04:32,720
of death. Why not smile in the face of death? 
'Let's sing, boys,' he repeated, 'Carlo, sing.'

1243
02:04:34,560 --> 02:04:40,640
Carlo gazed at him with eyes full of endless 
sorrow, and began very softly to sing a song  

1244
02:04:40,640 --> 02:04:47,840
from an opera they all loved, Madame Butterfly, 
and soon others joined in, when they felt able to.  

1245
02:04:49,360 --> 02:04:54,080
The tune comforted them, and it was 
easier to sing than to think on death;  

1246
02:04:54,960 --> 02:04:56,800
it gave the heart something to do.

1247
02:04:58,800 --> 02:05:05,520
When the truck arrived, Gunter Weber's knees 
began to shake. Almost before it had arrived,  

1248
02:05:05,520 --> 02:05:09,360
it seemed that he had known that life had 
called him to the killing of his friends.  

1249
02:05:10,400 --> 02:05:16,560
He had not expected them to arrive singing the 
tune that he and La Scala had sung together  

1250
02:05:16,560 --> 02:05:21,840
late at night at the doctor's house, nor had he 
expected them to jump so lightly from the truck.  

1251
02:05:23,120 --> 02:05:29,680
He ordered a German soldier to put his friends 
against the wall, lit another cigarette and turned  

1252
02:05:29,680 --> 02:05:38,000
away, but finally he turned again and approached 
the Italians. More than half of them were praying,  

1253
02:05:38,000 --> 02:05:44,160
kneeling in the soil, and others wept like 
children at a death. Antonio Corelli and  

1254
02:05:44,160 --> 02:05:49,760
Carlo Guercio were embracing. Weber reached for 
his packet of cigarettes and approached them.

1255
02:05:51,120 --> 02:05:58,800
'Cigarette?' he asked them, and Corelli took one, 
Carlo refusing. Corelli looked at Weber and said,  

1256
02:06:00,160 --> 02:06:03,120
'Your hands are trembling and your legs.'

1257
02:06:04,560 --> 02:06:08,560
'Antonio, I am very sorry, I tried...'

1258
02:06:08,560 --> 02:06:15,840
Corelli sucked on his cigarette and said, 'I 
am sure you did, Gunter, I know how it goes.'

1259
02:06:16,400 --> 02:06:19,280
Weber's face trembled with the 
effort of hiding his tears,  

1260
02:06:19,840 --> 02:06:22,640
and at last he said suddenly, 'Forgive me.'

1261
02:06:24,320 --> 02:06:29,840
Carlo made a sound of disgust in his throat 
and said, 'You will never be forgiven.'  

1262
02:06:31,200 --> 02:06:34,960
But Corelli put his hand up to 
silence his friend and said quietly,  

1263
02:06:35,680 --> 02:06:40,720
'Gunter, I forgive you. If I do not, who will?'

1264
02:06:42,640 --> 02:06:49,520
Weber held out his hand. 'Goodbye, Gunter,' 
said Corelli, taking it. Allowing his hand  

1265
02:06:49,520 --> 02:06:54,960
to remain in his former friend's, he shook 
it briefly one final time and released it.  

1266
02:06:55,840 --> 02:06:59,040
He linked an arm through 
Carlo's, and smiled up at him.  

1267
02:06:59,760 --> 02:07:06,320
'Come,' he said, 'we two have been companions 
in life. Let's go together to heaven.'

1268
02:07:08,560 --> 02:07:16,240
It was a beautiful day to die. A few soft clouds 
hid the top of Mount Aenos and nearby a goatbell  

1269
02:07:16,240 --> 02:07:22,560
rang. Corelli realized that his own legs were 
shaking and that he could do nothing to prevent  

1270
02:07:22,560 --> 02:07:29,200
it. He thought about Pelagia, with her dark 
eyes, her passionate nature, her black hair.  

1271
02:07:30,240 --> 02:07:35,360
He saw her clearly in his mind's eye: making 
a blanket that grew smaller every day;  

1272
02:07:36,000 --> 02:07:42,480
arm in arm with her father, returning from the 
sea; kissing Gunter Weber on the cheek at the  

1273
02:07:42,480 --> 02:07:50,560
offer of the record player. Pelagia, whose form 
had been so sweetly rounded, now so pale and thin.

1274
02:07:52,160 --> 02:07:58,720
A Croatian soldier approached Weber, a man who, in 
Weber's opinion, had a dangerously violent nature.  

1275
02:07:59,520 --> 02:08:04,480
The Croatian said, 'Sir, more 
will be arriving. We can't delay.'

1276
02:08:05,760 --> 02:08:10,160
'Very well,' said Weber. He 
closed his eyes and prayed,  

1277
02:08:10,720 --> 02:08:13,920
a prayer without words to a God who did not care.

1278
02:08:15,600 --> 02:08:20,880
There was nothing formal about the killings, and 
the victims were not lined up against the wall  

1279
02:08:21,440 --> 02:08:28,080
or made to face forwards. Many of them were 
left on their knees, praying or weeping or  

1280
02:08:28,080 --> 02:08:36,480
begging for mercy. Some stood smoking as if at a 
party, and Carlo stood next to Corelli, glad to  

1281
02:08:36,480 --> 02:08:43,440
die at last and determined to die a soldier's 
death. Corelli put one hand in his pocket to  

1282
02:08:43,440 --> 02:08:49,840
steady the shaking of his leg, and deeply breathed 
the Cephallonian air that held Pelagia's breath.

1283
02:08:51,280 --> 02:08:55,360
The German boys heard the command 
to fire and fired in disbelief.  

1284
02:08:56,560 --> 02:09:02,000
Those of them whose eyes were open aimed 
wide or high, or aimed to avoid a death.  

1285
02:09:02,640 --> 02:09:08,160
The Croatian soldier shot to kill, 
firing rapidly and taking careful aim.

1286
02:09:09,280 --> 02:09:15,760
Weber's head spun. His former friends were 
leaping and dancing in the rain of bullets,  

1287
02:09:15,760 --> 02:09:22,880
were crying out, stumbling to their knees, arms 
waving, their mouths filled with blood. But  

1288
02:09:22,880 --> 02:09:31,120
what no one had seen, even Weber, was that at the 
order to fire, Carlo had stepped quickly sideways  

1289
02:09:31,120 --> 02:09:37,520
in front of Corelli, and had gripped the latter's 
wrists so tightly that he was unable to move.  

1290
02:09:38,480 --> 02:09:42,160
Corelli stared wonderingly 
into the middle of Carlo's back  

1291
02:09:42,160 --> 02:09:47,760
as great holes burst though from inside the 
latter's body, releasing fountains of blood.

1292
02:09:48,960 --> 02:09:56,960
Carlo stood unbroken as one bullet after another 
entered his chest like white-hot knives. He stood  

1293
02:09:56,960 --> 02:10:04,800
perfectly still and counted to thirty, looked up 
at the sky and then threw himself over backwards.  

1294
02:10:06,080 --> 02:10:12,720
Corelli lay beneath him, unable to move, 
so astonished by this extraordinary,  

1295
02:10:12,720 --> 02:10:16,800
saintly act of love that he did not 
hear the Croatian soldier's voice.

1296
02:10:17,920 --> 02:10:25,360
'Italians, it's all over. If any of you are 
living, stand up now and you will go free.'

1297
02:10:27,360 --> 02:10:31,680
He did not see the two or three 
stand up and see them fall again  

1298
02:10:31,680 --> 02:10:36,960
as the Croatian shot them down. Then 
he heard the single shots as Weber,  

1299
02:10:37,520 --> 02:10:42,880
drunk with horror, wandered among the dead, 
putting those still living out of their pain.  

1300
02:10:44,400 --> 02:10:50,800
Next to his head he saw Weber's boot and he 
saw Weber bend down and look directly into his  

1301
02:10:50,800 --> 02:10:57,520
eyes where he lay trapped beneath Carlo's great 
weight. He saw the shaking gun approach his face,  

1302
02:10:58,480 --> 02:11:05,920
he saw the ocean of sorrow in Webers eyes, 
and then he saw the gun withdrawn, unfired.  

1303
02:11:07,040 --> 02:11:12,560
He tried to breathe more freely, and realized 
he was having difficulty, not only because of  

1304
02:11:12,560 --> 02:11:18,480
Carlo's weight but because the bullets that had 
passed through his friend had also struck himself.

1305
02:11:19,800 --> 02:11:20,800
***

1306
02:11:20,800 --> 02:11:27,120
Corelli lay beneath his friend for hours, their 
blood mixing in the soil, in their uniforms,  

1307
02:11:27,120 --> 02:11:34,720
in their flesh. It was not until evening that 
Velisarios came across the heap of tragic bodies,  

1308
02:11:34,720 --> 02:11:40,560
and recognized the man as big as himself who had 
once reached a hand across the barrier of war  

1309
02:11:41,120 --> 02:11:48,800
and offered him a cigarette. He looked down into 
the vacant and staring eyes, reached down and  

1310
02:11:48,800 --> 02:11:55,280
tried to close them. He failed, and was struck by 
the horror of leaving such a brother to the wind  

1311
02:11:55,280 --> 02:12:04,400
and birds. He knelt down and with a huge effort he 
lifted Carlo from the ground, and, as he did so,  

1312
02:12:04,400 --> 02:12:10,560
he saw the mad captain who was staying at the 
doctor's, the one whose 'secret' love for Pelagia  

1313
02:12:10,560 --> 02:12:17,840
was known and discussed by everyone on the island. 
The man's eyes were not vacant and they blinked.  

1314
02:12:19,120 --> 02:12:26,000
The lips moved. 'Doctor,' 
said the dying man. 'Pelagia.'

1315
02:12:28,160 --> 02:12:34,240
The strong man put Carlo against the wall. 
Then he carefully picked the captain up,  

1316
02:12:34,240 --> 02:12:39,200
felt how light he was, and set off 
across the stony fields to save his life.

1317
02:12:40,960 --> 02:12:46,080
Nobody knows the exact number of the Italian 
dead that lay upon the earth of Cephallonia,  

1318
02:12:46,720 --> 02:12:54,800
but at least four thousand were murdered, possibly 
nine thousand. The evidence was lost in flame,  

1319
02:12:54,800 --> 02:13:00,080
because the Germans, displaying knowledge 
of their guilt, burnt the bodies, cutting  

1320
02:13:00,080 --> 02:13:06,960
down trees that were a thousand years old to 
make the fires. They changed flesh into smoke,  

1321
02:13:07,760 --> 02:13:13,440
they put one dead boy after another across 
their shoulders and tipped them into the flames,  

1322
02:13:14,160 --> 02:13:18,800
working until their legs weakened and 
the flames became too hot to approach.

1323
02:13:20,720 --> 02:13:24,480
One of the bodies that they burned 
was the body of General Gandin,  

1324
02:13:25,040 --> 02:13:32,480
who trusted his enemies and tried to save his men. 
Another who died at this time was Father Arsenios,  

1325
02:13:32,480 --> 02:13:37,920
the priest from Pelagia's village. He wandered 
among the bodies and the flames until he was  

1326
02:13:37,920 --> 02:13:43,840
so mad with grief that he began to beat the heads 
and shoulders of the German soldiers with a stick.  

1327
02:13:45,200 --> 02:13:52,160
At first the soldiers, who had murdered thousands, 
did not know what to do, but then an officer came  

1328
02:13:52,160 --> 02:13:58,800
up behind Arsenios and fired a single shot into 
the back of his neck, exploding his brains.

1329
02:14:00,480 --> 02:14:07,040
Men and women and the few Italian soldiers who 
had escaped approached the fires as closely as the  

1330
02:14:07,040 --> 02:14:13,440
heat permitted and began to pull away the bodies 
at the edge of the fires. All of them thought the  

1331
02:14:13,440 --> 02:14:20,240
same things: 'Is this what it will be like under 
the Germans? How many of these boys could there  

1332
02:14:20,240 --> 02:14:27,600
have been? How many of these boys did I know? Can 
I imagine how it is to die of bleeding, slowly?'

1333
02:14:29,120 --> 02:14:34,560
At dawn a thick, black cloud hung 
over the land and blocked out the sun,  

1334
02:14:35,280 --> 02:14:39,840
and the people returned to their 
houses and locked their doors.
 
 
 

1335
02:14:43,440 --> 02:14:44,320
CHAPTER ELEVEN

1336
02:14:45,040 --> 02:14:45,920
An Operation

1337
02:14:47,840 --> 02:14:53,840
When the door was suddenly kicked open just as 
it was getting dark, Pelagia's first thought  

1338
02:14:53,840 --> 02:14:58,080
was that it was the Germans, since she 
knew that all the Italians were dead.  

1339
02:14:59,120 --> 02:15:05,600
Like everybody else she had heard the sounds 
of battle and seen truck after truck pass by,  

1340
02:15:05,600 --> 02:15:11,920
bearing either cheering German soldiers 
or the dead bodies of Italians. At night  

1341
02:15:11,920 --> 02:15:17,280
she had gone out with her father, whose cheeks 
were trembling with tears of anger and pity,  

1342
02:15:17,840 --> 02:15:21,920
and looked for lives to save among 
those bodies abandoned in the fires.

1343
02:15:23,360 --> 02:15:28,880
It had left her speechless, not with 
fear or sorrow, but with emptiness.

1344
02:15:30,560 --> 02:15:35,280
When the door flew open she was 
frightened, but she had nevertheless,  

1345
02:15:35,280 --> 02:15:39,520
somehow been expecting it. Her 
gun was ready in her pocket.  

1346
02:15:40,240 --> 02:15:47,760
She stood up, her hand tightening around the 
gun, her face colourless, and saw Velisarios,  

1347
02:15:47,760 --> 02:15:53,280
breathing hard. He advanced to the table 
and gently placed his burden on it.

1348
02:15:54,560 --> 02:15:56,480
'Who is it?' asked Pelagia.

1349
02:15:57,440 --> 02:16:01,520
'He's alive,' said Velisarios. 
'It's the mad captain.'

1350
02:16:02,960 --> 02:16:08,880
She bent down to look with eyes full of both 
horror and hope, but she did not recognize him;  

1351
02:16:09,440 --> 02:16:15,360
there were too many holes, too much blood. 
She wanted to touch him but withdrew her hand.  

1352
02:16:16,480 --> 02:16:18,800
Where does one touch a man like this?  

1353
02:16:19,760 --> 02:16:27,600
The body opened its eyes and the 
mouth smiled. 'Kalimera, koritsimou,'  

1354
02:16:27,600 --> 02:16:32,161
it said, and she recognized the voice.

1355
02:16:32,160 --> 02:16:34,479
'It's the evening,' she said foolishly.  

1356
02:16:35,840 --> 02:16:40,160
'Kalispera, then,' he 
whispered and closed his eyes.

1357
02:16:42,399 --> 02:16:46,799
Pelagia looked up at Velisarios, her 
eyes wide and desperate, and said,  

1358
02:16:47,439 --> 02:16:53,439
'Velisarios, you have never done a greater thing. 
I'm going to get my father. Stay with him.'  

1359
02:16:54,560 --> 02:16:58,320
She found her father at the 
kapheneion and dragged him out,  

1360
02:16:58,319 --> 02:17:02,880
ignoring the angry stares of the other 
men, and Kokolios, who roared at her.

1361
02:17:04,000 --> 02:17:09,040
The doctor looked at the body and knew 
he had never seen anything worse. There  

1362
02:17:09,040 --> 02:17:16,560
was enough blood to fill the veins of a horse. 
'It would be kinder to kill him,' he said, but  

1363
02:17:16,560 --> 02:17:23,680
before Velisarios could say, 'I thought so too,' 
Pelagia began beating her father with both hands.  

1364
02:17:24,479 --> 02:17:31,200
And so water was put on to boil and the rags 
of the captain's uniform were gently cut away.

1365
02:17:32,880 --> 02:17:35,680
Dr Iannis complained as he cleaned away the blood.  

1366
02:17:36,640 --> 02:17:42,320
'What am I supposed to do? I have no 
equipment to perform an operation.'

1367
02:17:42,319 --> 02:17:45,599
'Shut up, shut up, shut up,' Pelagia shouted,  

1368
02:17:45,600 --> 02:17:51,040
her heart racing with both fear and 
determination. 'Just shut up and do it.'

1369
02:17:52,640 --> 02:17:57,440
Because the doctor was unaware that most of 
the blood and flesh had belonged to the broad  

1370
02:17:57,439 --> 02:18:04,080
back of Carlo Guercio, it seemed unbelievable to 
him that Antonio Corelli was as little wounded  

1371
02:18:04,080 --> 02:18:10,319
as he was. Once he was cleaned, it was clear 
that the victim had six bullets in his chest,  

1372
02:18:11,120 --> 02:18:17,680
one in the stomach, and one through the outer 
flesh in his right arm. But the doctor knew  

1373
02:18:17,680 --> 02:18:25,120
too much to be optimistic and it still seemed 
hopeless. Frightened of the task that lay ahead  

1374
02:18:25,120 --> 02:18:31,519
of him, he opened a bottle of raki, drank 
deeply and passed the bottle to Velisarios,  

1375
02:18:31,520 --> 02:18:37,920
who did the same. Then, with the comforting 
taste of alcohol in his mouth, he reached for  

1376
02:18:37,920 --> 02:18:43,920
an instrument and moved it gently around in 
each wound until he felt it reach a bullet.

1377
02:18:45,040 --> 02:18:51,359
He stood up amazed, realizing that the holes 
were not even deep and that the bullets should  

1378
02:18:51,359 --> 02:18:57,920
have passed right through the victim's body 
but had not done so. 'Daughter,' he said,  

1379
02:18:58,880 --> 02:19:06,480
'I swear by all the saints that this man's 
flesh is made of steel. I think he'll live.'

1380
02:19:07,760 --> 02:19:16,960
'Antonio,' he called, and Corelli opened his eyes. 
'Antonio, I'm going to operate. I haven't got much  

1381
02:19:16,960 --> 02:19:24,000
morphia. Can you drink?' Corelli nodded, and 
Pelagia poured a cup of raki down his throat  

1382
02:19:24,000 --> 02:19:30,800
while the doctor injected morphia into his arm. 
Pelagia looked at that desperately damaged body,  

1383
02:19:30,800 --> 02:19:36,160
helpless as a worm, and knew that it 
was not exactly a body that one loved,  

1384
02:19:36,160 --> 02:19:42,639
but that one loved the man who shone out through 
the eyes and used his mouth to smile and speak.  

1385
02:19:44,240 --> 02:19:47,840
The doctor saw her dreaming and 
said, 'Don't just sit there.  

1386
02:19:48,399 --> 02:19:53,120
We need more boiling water. And wash 
your hands, especially under the nails.'

1387
02:19:54,560 --> 02:19:59,840
Pelagia discovered in that hour how difficult 
the task was that she had set her father.  

1388
02:20:00,640 --> 02:20:06,080
Her hands trembled, and at first she could 
hardly force herself to touch the captain.  

1389
02:20:06,960 --> 02:20:11,760
She looked up and saw her father cutting 
wide holes around the bullet wounds  

1390
02:20:11,760 --> 02:20:18,720
and had to resist her desire to be sick. The 
doctor started on the bullet in the stomach,  

1391
02:20:18,720 --> 02:20:23,360
since he needed to do something that was 
relatively easy in order to increase his  

1392
02:20:23,359 --> 02:20:30,960
confidence. He found it not far beneath the 
surface of the skin and picked it out, amazed by  

1393
02:20:30,960 --> 02:20:39,120
its flattened shape. 'It's unbelievable,' he said, 
showing it to Pelagia. 'How do you explain this?'

1394
02:20:40,880 --> 02:20:47,359
'He was behind that big man, the one as 
big as me,' said Velisarios. 'The big man  

1395
02:20:47,359 --> 02:20:54,399
was holding him from behind, like this.' He 
stood up and put his hands behind his back  

1396
02:20:54,399 --> 02:21:01,200
to show how one could grip another's wrists. 'I 
think he was trying to save the man,' he said.

1397
02:21:03,040 --> 02:21:06,960
'Carlo,' said Pelagia, 
suddenly bursting into tears.  

1398
02:21:07,920 --> 02:21:12,800
Carlo was the first of the boys of La Scala 
whom they now knew with certainty was dead.

1399
02:21:14,000 --> 02:21:18,399
'No man who dies like that has died for 
nothing,' said the doctor, fighting back  

1400
02:21:18,399 --> 02:21:23,839
his own need for tears. Pelagia wiped her 
eyes on the sleeve of her dress and said,  

1401
02:21:24,960 --> 02:21:28,080
'Antonio always said that Carlo 
was the bravest in the Army.'

1402
02:21:29,520 --> 02:21:32,320
'Velisarios, is the man's body still there?  

1403
02:21:32,880 --> 02:21:36,640
We would like to bury it and not 
see it burned,' said the doctor.

1404
02:21:37,680 --> 02:21:44,880
'It's after dark, I'll go and look,' said the 
strongman. 'On the way, I might kill a German, who  

1405
02:21:44,880 --> 02:21:51,600
knows?' He departed, happy to be out of that house 
where the sights were enough to make one ill.

1406
02:21:53,359 --> 02:21:58,399
When the doctor had finished cleaning out the 
wound, he gave Pelagia the task of sewing it up,  

1407
02:21:58,960 --> 02:22:04,480
and she did so with accuracy and care, despite 
her feeling of the unreality of it all.  

1408
02:22:05,439 --> 02:22:10,240
Velisarios buried Carlo Guercio's remains 
that night in the yard of the doctor's house.  

1409
02:22:11,280 --> 02:22:16,719
Just before dawn, when the operation on the 
captain was finished at last, and father and  

1410
02:22:16,720 --> 02:22:22,880
daughter were both utterly exhausted, they came 
out to say their goodbye to that heroic soldier.

1411
02:22:23,920 --> 02:22:26,960
Pelagia combed the hair and kissed the forehead,  

1412
02:22:27,600 --> 02:22:31,201
and Velisarios placed a 
cigarette in the dead man's lips.  

1413
02:22:32,479 --> 02:22:40,319
'I owed him one,' he said. The doctor made a 
speech while Pelagia wept beside him. 'Sleep  

1414
02:22:40,319 --> 02:22:46,799
long and well,' he ended. 'As long as we remember 
you, you will be remembered fair and young.'

1415
02:22:48,080 --> 02:22:52,080
Leaning upon each other, the doctor 
and his daughter returned inside.  

1416
02:22:52,960 --> 02:22:59,200
Carefully, they carried Corelli to Pelagia's 
bed, and outside the first birds sang.

1417
02:23:00,920 --> 02:23:01,920
***

1418
02:23:01,920 --> 02:23:07,760
It was only a short time before the Germans began 
to take an interest in loot. Not only did the  

1419
02:23:07,760 --> 02:23:14,400
doctor have to hide his valuables, he also had to 
hide an Italian officer who lay, unable to move,  

1420
02:23:14,399 --> 02:23:20,240
in his daughter's bed. Pelagia made a bed for 
him at the bottom of the hole in the kitchen,  

1421
02:23:20,880 --> 02:23:24,480
and once again Velisarios 
was called in to carry him.  

1422
02:23:25,200 --> 02:23:31,840
There Corelli was reunited with his mandolin 
and Carlo's papers were temporarily removed.  

1423
02:23:32,479 --> 02:23:36,399
The lid of the hiding-place was left open 
unless troops were in the neighbourhood.

1424
02:23:37,600 --> 02:23:44,880
For the first day after the operation the captain 
slept, but when he first woke, the pain was so bad  

1425
02:23:44,880 --> 02:23:49,359
that he could not move at all, and he felt 
as if he had been run over by a lorry.

1426
02:23:50,479 --> 02:23:53,919
'I can't breathe,' he told the doctor.

1427
02:23:54,800 --> 02:24:01,600
'If you couldn't breathe you couldn't speak.' The 
captain said nothing and the doctor continued,  

1428
02:24:02,720 --> 02:24:05,120
'It appears that Carlo saved your life.'

1429
02:24:06,319 --> 02:24:09,679
'It doesn't "appear". I know he did.  

1430
02:24:10,399 --> 02:24:15,759
Of all of us, he died the best. 
And he's left me to remember it.'

1431
02:24:17,040 --> 02:24:22,880
'You shouldn't weep, Captain. We are going to 
get you well, and then get you off the island.'

1432
02:24:24,240 --> 02:24:27,920
'When I am better you must 
move me from the house, Doctor.  

1433
02:24:28,720 --> 02:24:34,160
I don't want you in danger. If I 
am caught, I should die alone.'

1434
02:24:35,520 --> 02:24:41,840
'We can move you to your secret house, where you 
used to go with Pelagia. Don't look so surprised.  

1435
02:24:42,800 --> 02:24:47,120
Everybody knew. And you may 
not get better. Remember that.'

1436
02:24:48,399 --> 02:24:51,519
'My God, Doctor, please tell me some lies.'

1437
02:24:52,720 --> 02:24:58,400
'The truth will make us free. We 
overcome fear by looking it in the eyes.'

1438
02:25:00,399 --> 02:25:06,639
The captain fell into a fever two days later and 
Pelagia remained in the hiding-place with him,  

1439
02:25:06,640 --> 02:25:13,120
wiping his forehead to reduce his temperature. 
The fever came to a crisis on the fourth day,  

1440
02:25:13,760 --> 02:25:18,400
and Corelli was sweating so much 
and talking so nonsensically  

1441
02:25:18,399 --> 02:25:25,599
that both the doctor and Pelagia feared for 
his life. But two days later the fever left,  

1442
02:25:25,600 --> 02:25:31,440
and the patient opened his eyes with wonder, 
as if realizing that he existed for the first  

1443
02:25:31,439 --> 02:25:37,759
time. He felt weaker than it ought to be 
possible to feel, but by the same evening  

1444
02:25:37,760 --> 02:25:44,800
he was able to stand with the doctor's help and 
let himself be washed. Pelagia fetched a mirror  

1445
02:25:44,800 --> 02:25:51,840
and showed him his new-grown beard, and that 
night he was fed his first solid meal. Snails.

1446
02:25:52,520 --> 02:25:53,520
***

1447
02:25:53,520 --> 02:25:58,960
In later life, Pelagia remembered the 
time of Corelli's recovery and his escape  

1448
02:25:58,960 --> 02:26:06,319
not as a period of exciting adventure, nor even as 
a time of fear and hope, but as the slow beginning  

1449
02:26:06,319 --> 02:26:14,799
of her sorrows. The war had reduced her anyway. 
Her skin, stretched tightly over her bones,  

1450
02:26:14,800 --> 02:26:21,520
was transparent from lack of food, and when she 
ate she chewed carefully in case she lost a tooth.  

1451
02:26:22,720 --> 02:26:28,640
Her rich black hair had thinned and lost 
its shine, and showed the first grey hairs  

1452
02:26:28,640 --> 02:26:34,960
that should not have appeared for at least 
another decade. It was hard to obtain food,  

1453
02:26:34,960 --> 02:26:41,120
and the doctor was reduced to trapping snakes 
and other such creatures. Things were not  

1454
02:26:41,120 --> 02:26:48,240
hopeless, however; there was always the 
sea, the source of Cephallonia's being.

1455
02:26:48,240 --> 02:26:53,439
As soon as Corelli could walk, he went in 
the company of the doctor and Velisarios to  

1456
02:26:53,439 --> 02:27:00,080
Casa Nostra at night, while Pelagia remained at 
home in the hiding-place in which the mandolin,  

1457
02:27:00,080 --> 02:27:06,960
the doctor's History and Carlo's papers had been 
replaced. As long as the German rapists were on  

1458
02:27:06,960 --> 02:27:14,240
the island, she hardly left the house. Corelli 
had given her his ring, too big for any of her  

1459
02:27:14,240 --> 02:27:20,800
fingers, and she turned it round and round in 
the lamplight. The captain came frequently,  

1460
02:27:20,800 --> 02:27:27,600
after dark, complaining that the hut was cold, his 
new beard scratching her cheeks as they lay fully  

1461
02:27:27,600 --> 02:27:33,760
clothed upon her bed, wrapped in each other's 
embrace, talking of the future and the past.

1462
02:27:35,680 --> 02:27:37,840
'I will always hate the Germans,' she said.

1463
02:27:39,200 --> 02:27:40,479
'Gunter saved my life.'

1464
02:27:41,600 --> 02:27:43,920
'He murdered all your friends.'

1465
02:27:43,920 --> 02:27:45,040
'He had no choice.  

1466
02:27:45,840 --> 02:27:50,480
It wouldn't surprise me if he shot himself 
afterwards. He was trying not to cry.'

1467
02:27:51,359 --> 02:27:52,880
'There is always a choice.'

1468
02:27:53,760 --> 02:28:00,320
'He wasn't brave like Carlo. Only one in a million 
is made like that, you mustn't blame poor Gunter.'

1469
02:28:01,600 --> 02:28:05,040
Pelagia desperately wanted to 
keep her captain on the island,  

1470
02:28:05,040 --> 02:28:11,519
but knew that she would kill him if she did. There 
were people who were prepared to betray for bread,  

1471
02:28:11,520 --> 02:28:15,281
and it could only be a matter of time 
before the Germans became aware of his  

1472
02:28:15,280 --> 02:28:21,840
presence in their lives. She asked Kokolios 
and Stamatis to enquire for news of Bunnios,  

1473
02:28:21,840 --> 02:28:25,840
the English spy, and to tell 
him to call on her if he could.

1474
02:28:27,040 --> 02:28:31,840
For some time now Bunny Warren had been 
encouraging the owners of boats to help the  

1475
02:28:31,840 --> 02:28:37,600
few surviving Italian soldiers to escape from 
the island, and it was easy for him to arrange  

1476
02:28:37,600 --> 02:28:44,080
the captain's departure. He called at Pelagia's 
home one night, tapping softly on her window,  

1477
02:28:44,720 --> 02:28:50,000
and when she had removed herself from Corelli's 
embrace, she looked out and saw the man whose  

1478
02:28:50,000 --> 02:28:56,960
help she had both sought and feared. He came in 
through the door and very formally shook her hand.

1479
02:28:58,560 --> 02:29:04,161
'Who is this?' asked Corelli, who for a moment 
had been fearing a visit from the Germans.

1480
02:29:05,439 --> 02:29:12,000
'Bunnios,' said Pelagia, without answering his 
question, 'this is an Italian soldier and we have  

1481
02:29:12,000 --> 02:29:18,319
to get him out.' By chance a boat was leaving 
for Sicily the following morning and it would  

1482
02:29:18,319 --> 02:29:24,160
be easy to put the captain on board. They simply 
had to go to a certain bay at one o'clock in the  

1483
02:29:24,160 --> 02:29:29,439
morning with a lamp, and flash out to sea in 
answer to the signals flashed from the boat.

1484
02:29:30,880 --> 02:29:34,080
Corelli did not go back to 
Casa Nostra before dawn,  

1485
02:29:34,080 --> 02:29:39,359
but stayed with Pelagia in the house. The 
three of them sat in that familiar kitchen,  

1486
02:29:39,359 --> 02:29:45,679
saddened and fearful, talking quietly and 
shaking their heads over all the memories.

1487
02:29:46,560 --> 02:29:49,840
'I owe my life to you, Doctor,' the captain said.

1488
02:29:50,720 --> 02:29:54,080
'I am sorry about the scars. 
It was the best I could do.'

1489
02:29:55,359 --> 02:30:01,519
'And I am sorry, Doctor, about the rape of the 
island. I don't suppose we will ever be forgiven.'

1490
02:30:02,479 --> 02:30:05,919
'As you know, Captain, I 
must have forgiven you, or  

1491
02:30:06,479 --> 02:30:09,280
I would not have given you 
permission to marry my daughter.'

1492
02:30:10,399 --> 02:30:17,599
Pelagia and Corelli looked at each other and the 
captain said, 'We have decided that if we have  

1493
02:30:17,600 --> 02:30:25,201
a son, we will name him Iannis.' The doctor 
was visibly delighted, even though this was  

1494
02:30:25,200 --> 02:30:32,160
exactly what he would have expected under the 
circumstances. He looked up, his eyes watering,  

1495
02:30:32,160 --> 02:30:40,319
and said simply, 'Antonio, if I have ever had a 
son it was you. You have a place at this table.'

1496
02:30:41,840 --> 02:30:46,480
Corelli stood up and the two men 
embraced, clapping each other on the back,  

1497
02:30:46,479 --> 02:30:48,559
and then the doctor embraced his daughter.  

1498
02:30:49,760 --> 02:30:56,080
'I'll leave you two children together,' he said. 
'There is a little girl dying and I should visit.'

1499
02:30:58,080 --> 02:31:02,240
The doctor left the house and the 
two lovers sat opposite each other,  

1500
02:31:02,240 --> 02:31:08,319
unable to speak. Finally the tears began to 
follow each other slowly down Pelagia's cheeks,  

1501
02:31:08,880 --> 02:31:14,720
and Corelli knelt beside her, put his arms 
around her and laid his head against her chest.  

1502
02:31:16,160 --> 02:31:20,559
He was shocked again at how thin 
she was and closed his eyes tightly,  

1503
02:31:21,120 --> 02:31:28,240
imagining that it was another world. 'I am so 
afraid,' she said. 'I think you won't come back,  

1504
02:31:28,240 --> 02:31:34,960
and the war goes on and on forever, and there's no 
safety and no hope and I'll be left with nothing.'

1505
02:31:36,880 --> 02:31:42,080
'I shall not forget you and I 
will come back,' replied Corelli.

1506
02:31:42,080 --> 02:31:42,559
'Promise?'

1507
02:31:43,120 --> 02:31:47,359
'I promise. I have left you my ring and Antonia.'

1508
02:31:48,479 --> 02:31:50,080
'We never read Carlo's papers.'

1509
02:31:51,200 --> 02:31:54,240
'Too painful. We'll read them when I return.'

1510
02:31:54,840 --> 02:31:58,080
She stroked his hair in silence and said finally,  

1511
02:31:59,120 --> 02:32:05,280
'Antonio, I wish that we had... 
lain together. As a man and woman.'

1512
02:32:06,880 --> 02:32:09,840
'Everything at the right time, koritsimou.'

1513
02:32:10,720 --> 02:32:12,080
'There may not be a time.'

1514
02:32:12,800 --> 02:32:15,200
'There will be. You have my promise.'

1515
02:32:17,040 --> 02:32:23,040
At eleven o'clock Bunny Warren scratched at 
the window. He carried a knife in his belt  

1516
02:32:23,040 --> 02:32:27,760
and sounded extremely efficient as he 
gave detailed instructions to the doctor,  

1517
02:32:27,760 --> 02:32:29,920
who translated them for Corelli's benefit.

1518
02:32:31,200 --> 02:32:36,399
It was a cold December night, there 
was no moon, and since most Germans  

1519
02:32:36,399 --> 02:32:41,040
preferred to be indoors on such a night, the 
journey to the beach was relatively safe.  

1520
02:32:42,240 --> 02:32:50,319
Nevertheless, Pelagia's heart beat fast and a dark 
hole seemed to be opening in her heart. Corelli  

1521
02:32:50,319 --> 02:32:55,840
felt so sad he almost wished that they would 
meet some German soldiers so that he could die,  

1522
02:32:56,399 --> 02:33:03,120
fighting and killing, and end it all. He knew that 
to leave the island would be to lose his roots.

1523
02:33:04,479 --> 02:33:10,559
For warmth, the four of them stood close together 
on the tiny patch of sand, waiting for the flash  

1524
02:33:10,560 --> 02:33:16,161
of a lamp that would come to them from the 
sea. Corelli walked to the waterline and,  

1525
02:33:16,160 --> 02:33:20,240
seeing the black waves, wondered how 
he would ever survive the journey.  

1526
02:33:21,200 --> 02:33:25,920
He felt his love for the island turning 
in his chest like the twist of a knife,  

1527
02:33:26,560 --> 02:33:31,281
because he had his own village now and 
