1572
02:38:04,880 --> 02:38:11,600
The Germans left and the celebrations began, 
but no sooner had the bells begun ringing than  

1573
02:38:11,600 --> 02:38:18,640
the members of the Communist organization ELAS, 
now calling themselves EAM, came out from hiding  

1574
02:38:18,640 --> 02:38:25,040
and attempted to take control of the country. 
They formed Workers' Councils and elected  

1575
02:38:25,040 --> 02:38:31,280
themselves to every post of authority. In 
Cephallonia the Communists began to send  

1576
02:38:31,280 --> 02:38:37,679
awkward characters to prison camps. On the 
mainland they poisoned, with dead animals,  

1577
02:38:37,680 --> 02:38:44,720
the water of villages that opposed them. Into 
mass graves they threw the dead bodies of Greeks  

1578
02:38:44,720 --> 02:38:49,680
who had had their eyes torn out and their 
mouths cut into the shape of a smile.  

1579
02:38:51,040 --> 02:38:57,600
They kidnapped 30,000 little children and sent 
them across the border into Communist Yugoslavia  

1580
02:38:57,600 --> 02:39:03,680
to be taught how to be true Communists. 
ELAS soldiers captured by the British were  

1581
02:39:03,680 --> 02:39:09,840
so frightened of their leaders that they begged 
to be allowed to remain in British prison camps.

1582
02:39:10,399 --> 02:39:16,240
Pelagia and the doctor were two out of millions 
of people whose lives were forever destroyed  

1583
02:39:16,240 --> 02:39:22,399
by these butchers. The doctor was dragged away 
in the night by three men who had decided that  

1584
02:39:22,399 --> 02:39:29,759
since he was a doctor he must be a Fascist. 
They threw Pelagia into a corner and beat  

1585
02:39:29,760 --> 02:39:35,600
her unconscious with a chair. When Kokolios 
came out from his house to defend the doctor,  

1586
02:39:35,600 --> 02:39:42,400
he too was carried away, even though he was 
a Communist. He was accompanied by Stamatis,  

1587
02:39:42,399 --> 02:39:47,759
a supporter of the royal family, and the three 
men were taken to the harbour for transportation.

1588
02:39:49,359 --> 02:39:51,839
Pelagia did not know what 
had happened to her father,  

1589
02:39:52,479 --> 02:39:58,559
and none of the authorities would tell her. 
Alone in the house, penniless and helpless,  

1590
02:39:59,120 --> 02:40:05,040
for the first time in her life she thought 
of ending everything by killing herself. The  

1591
02:40:05,040 --> 02:40:13,040
island seemed to be cursed by an endless series of 
oppressors. When would Antonio return? The war was  

1592
02:40:13,040 --> 02:40:19,920
continuing in Europe, and probably he was dead. 
She heard that the Communists had been killing the  

1593
02:40:19,920 --> 02:40:25,760
Italian soldiers who had come to fight alongside 
them against the Greeks. Had the time come,  

1594
02:40:25,760 --> 02:40:31,600
finally, to hate the Greeks? Of the nations 
who had broken into her house to beat her  

1595
02:40:31,600 --> 02:40:35,840
and steal her possessions, only the 
Italians were innocent, it seemed.

1596
02:40:37,279 --> 02:40:44,479
Fortunately she had a friend. Drosoula had long 
known that Pelagia had lost her love for Mandras,  

1597
02:40:44,479 --> 02:40:51,439
and that by his long silence he had given up his 
rights. She knew also that Pelagia was waiting  

1598
02:40:51,439 --> 02:40:59,839
for an Italian, but she felt no bitterness and 
never uttered a single word of blame. When Pelagia  

1599
02:40:59,840 --> 02:41:06,319
stumbled bleeding through her door after the 
Communists had taken Dr Iannis, Drosoula, who had  

1600
02:41:06,319 --> 02:41:12,880
also suffered much, stroked her hair and uttered 
loving words, as if Pelagia were her own daughter.  

1601
02:41:14,399 --> 02:41:19,920
Within a week she had closed up her little house 
on the harbour and moved into the doctor's house  

1602
02:41:19,920 --> 02:41:26,960
on the hill. She found his Italian gun in a 
drawer and kept it at her side in case of attack.

1603
02:41:28,080 --> 02:41:34,720
Like Pelagia, Drosoula had been reduced by 
the war. The layers of fat had melted from  

1604
02:41:34,720 --> 02:41:42,640
her waist and thighs, and her great ugly moon 
of a face had sunk inwards. However, her tall,  

1605
02:41:42,640 --> 02:41:49,840
thin form and grey hairs demanded respect, 
and her unbroken spirit gave Pelagia strength.

1606
02:41:50,960 --> 02:41:57,200
For comfort they slept together in the doctor's 
bed, and by day they made plans to find supplies  

1607
02:41:57,200 --> 02:42:03,840
of food and listened to each others complaints and 
stories. They dug for roots in the undergrowth,  

1608
02:42:03,840 --> 02:42:07,600
and Drosoula took her young friend 
down to the harbour to learn to fish.

1609
02:42:09,520 --> 02:42:16,960
But Drosoula was out when Mandras returned, full 
of selfimportance and new ideas, expecting the  

1610
02:42:16,960 --> 02:42:22,880
admiring attention of the young woman he had 
not seen for years, and determined to take  

1611
02:42:22,880 --> 02:42:29,040
revenge. He came in through the door without 
knocking and leaned his gun against the wall.  

1612
02:42:30,319 --> 02:42:34,719
When she heard the noise in the kitchen, 
Pelagia, who was in her room, called out,  

1613
02:42:35,359 --> 02:42:42,080
'Drosoula?' A man came in who she did not 
recognize, except that he looked very like  

1614
02:42:42,080 --> 02:42:48,240
Drosoula had done before the war; there 
was the same swollen stomach and thighs,  

1615
02:42:48,240 --> 02:42:54,080
the same round, coarse face and thickened 
lips. Puzzled, Pelagia stood up.

1616
02:42:55,200 --> 02:43:02,000
Mandras also was confused. There was something 
about this desperately thin, frightened girl  

1617
02:43:02,000 --> 02:43:08,720
that reminded him of Pelagia, but this woman 
had silver threads in her thin black hair, her  

1618
02:43:08,720 --> 02:43:14,880
blouse and skirt hung straight to the ground, her 
cheeks were hollow. He looked quickly around the  

1619
02:43:14,880 --> 02:43:21,160
room to see whether Pelagia was there, assuming 
that this must be a cousin or an aunt. 'Mandras,  

1620
02:43:23,120 --> 02:43:27,279
is it you?' said the woman, 
and he recognized the voice.

1621
02:43:28,479 --> 02:43:34,639
He stood, amazed and confused, with 
much of his hatred knocked out of him,  

1622
02:43:34,640 --> 02:43:39,680
while she looked at those coarse and 
altered features and felt deep disgust.  

1623
02:43:41,040 --> 02:43:45,519
'I thought you must be dead,' she said finally.

1624
02:43:46,960 --> 02:43:56,160
He closed the door and leaned against it. 'You 
mean you were hoping I was dead. As you see,  

1625
02:43:56,160 --> 02:44:04,080
I am not. I am very much alive and well. 
Don't I get a kiss from my fiancee?'

1626
02:44:04,080 --> 02:44:08,399
She advanced fearfully and 
placed a kiss on his right cheek.

1627
02:44:09,760 --> 02:44:12,960
'I am glad you are alive,' she said.

1628
02:44:13,840 --> 02:44:16,560
He caught both her wrists and held them tightly.  

1629
02:44:17,520 --> 02:44:22,720
'I don't think you are. How is your 
father, by the way? Is he not here?'

1630
02:44:24,000 --> 02:44:32,080
'Let me go,' she said softly, and he did so. 
'The Communists took him away' she told him.

1631
02:44:33,279 --> 02:44:36,319
'Well, he must have done something to deserve it.'

1632
02:44:37,520 --> 02:44:43,600
'He did nothing. He healed the sick. And they 
beat me with a chair and took everything.'

1633
02:44:44,560 --> 02:44:50,480
'There must be reasons. The party is never 
wrong. Whoever is not with us is against us.'

1634
02:44:52,000 --> 02:44:56,160
She noticed that he wore the red star 
of ELAS sewn into the front of his cap.  

1635
02:44:57,520 --> 02:44:59,840
'You're one of them,' she said.

1636
02:45:00,640 --> 02:45:04,161
He leaned against the door, 
placing all his weight against it,  

1637
02:45:04,160 --> 02:45:06,960
increasing her sense of imprisonment and her fear.  

1638
02:45:08,160 --> 02:45:16,240
'Not just one of them, an important one of them,' 
he stated, sounding pleased with himself, then  

1639
02:45:16,240 --> 02:45:23,040
added challengingly, 'Soon we will have a nice 
big house to live in. When shall we get married?'

1640
02:45:24,479 --> 02:45:27,839
She trembled and, seeing 
this, his anger increased.  

1641
02:45:29,120 --> 02:45:35,519
'We will not be married,' she said. 'We were 
very young, it was not what we thought it was.'

1642
02:45:36,560 --> 02:45:43,040
'Not what we thought? And there was I, fighting 
for Greece, thinking of you all day and dreaming  

1643
02:45:43,040 --> 02:45:48,640
of you at night. And now I come back at last 
and find a faded cow who has forgotten me.'

1644
02:45:49,760 --> 02:45:51,760
'What's the matter with you?' she asked.

1645
02:45:52,399 --> 02:45:57,120
'The matter with me?' He took from 
his pocket a thick bundle of papers.  

1646
02:45:57,920 --> 02:46:04,399
'This is what is the matter with me.' He threw 
them towards her feet and she picked them up  

1647
02:46:04,399 --> 02:46:10,479
slowly. She held the bundle in her hands 
and realized that it consisted of her  

1648
02:46:10,479 --> 02:46:17,200
letters to him in Albania. 'My letters?' 
she said, turning them over in her hands.

1649
02:46:18,880 --> 02:46:24,880
Mandras gave a sudden roar of disgust and, 
seizing the letters, he found the last one,  

1650
02:46:24,880 --> 02:46:32,480
held it up to the light and read, 'You never 
write to me, and at first I was sad and worried.  

1651
02:46:33,279 --> 02:46:37,840
Now I realize that you cannot care and this 
has caused me to lose my love for you also.  

1652
02:46:38,640 --> 02:46:44,400
I want you to know that I have decided to 
release you from your promises. I am sorry,'

1653
02:46:45,840 --> 02:46:52,720
He gave a smile that was both humourless 
and threatening. 'Yes, I'm able to read now,  

1654
02:46:53,359 --> 02:46:56,719
and this is what I found in the letters 
I had been carrying next to my heart.  

1655
02:46:57,760 --> 02:47:02,960
And now I know the truth. Do you know the 
first thing I heard when I arrived back here?  

1656
02:47:03,520 --> 02:47:11,360
I heard, "Mandras, did you hear about your old 
fiancee? She's going to marry an Italian." So  

1657
02:47:12,000 --> 02:47:17,120
