His name was Spiridon and he 
played his bozouki with such skill  

2050
03:27:52,560 --> 03:27:56,720
that he could persuade even the Germans to 
put their arms around each other's shoulders  

2051
03:27:56,720 --> 03:28:04,240
and dance in a circle while stamping on the floor. 
Iannis loved Spiridon, with his broad shoulders  

2052
03:28:04,239 --> 03:28:10,479
and his wide mouth that seemed to contain a 
hundred flashing teeth. Pelagia also loved  

2053
03:28:10,479 --> 03:28:16,399
him because he reminded her of her long-lost 
captain, and occasionally her heart wished  

2054
03:28:16,399 --> 03:28:22,160
desperately for a time-machine to take her back 
to the days of the only real love of her life.

2055
03:28:23,600 --> 03:28:29,280
Iannis did not fail to notice that Spiridon 
was popular with women, who at the end of every  

2056
03:28:29,279 --> 03:28:34,399
performance would seize the red roses from 
the vases in the middle of their tables, and  

2057
03:28:34,399 --> 03:28:41,839
throw them at him. So one day Iannis demanded that 
Spiridon should teach him how to play the bozouki.

2058
03:28:43,040 --> 03:28:47,760
'Your arms aren't long enough yet,' 
said Spiro. 'It would make more sense  

2059
03:28:47,760 --> 03:28:53,280
to start with a mandolin. It's the same 
thing really, but small enough for you.'

2060
03:28:54,080 --> 03:28:55,359
'Will you teach me to play it?'

2061
03:28:56,160 --> 03:29:02,960
'Of course, but we'll have to find a mandolin. 
Otherwise we might have to do just the theory.'

2062
03:29:04,479 --> 03:29:09,279
Iannis begged his mother and father to get 
him one, and they promised to buy one when  

2063
03:29:09,279 --> 03:29:17,840
they next went to Athens, but forgot. Eventually 
Pelagia told him, 'In fact we have one already,  

2064
03:29:17,840 --> 03:29:23,520
but it's buried under the old house. I am 
sure Antonio wouldn't mind you digging it up.'

2065
03:29:24,319 --> 03:29:25,279
'Who's Antonio?'

2066
03:29:26,000 --> 03:29:31,600
'My Italian fiance who was killed in 
the war. It belonged to him. There  

2067
03:29:31,600 --> 03:29:36,240
was a big trapdoor in the middle of the 
floor and it was in a hole underneath.'

2068
03:29:37,680 --> 03:29:44,080
So Iannis dragged Spiridon up the hill and showed 
him a ghostly ruin overgrown with long grass,  

2069
03:29:44,720 --> 03:29:47,840
its broken stones just visible above the growth.  

2070
03:29:48,560 --> 03:29:53,201
All around it lay the silent and 
deserted remains of lonely little houses.

2071
03:29:54,720 --> 03:29:57,120
'It's the saddest place,' said Iannis.  

2072
03:29:57,760 --> 03:30:04,960
'I come here to explore sometimes.' He pointed. 
'My grandfather died in there. I'm named after  

2073
03:30:04,960 --> 03:30:11,200
him. Grandma says he was the best doctor in Greece 
and that he could cure people by touching them.'

2074
03:30:12,319 --> 03:30:16,160
The two of them went through what had 
once been the door and scratched their  

2075
03:30:16,160 --> 03:30:21,760
heads when they saw the rubbish that lay all 
around. Spiro blew out his cheeks and sighed.  

2076
03:30:22,960 --> 03:30:27,680
'We've got two days work here,' he said. 
'We'll just have to get on with it.'

2077
03:30:28,960 --> 03:30:33,840
By the next evening there was a clear 
space in the middle of the old floor  

2078
03:30:33,840 --> 03:30:37,920
and the trapdoor lay revealed in the 
area that had once been the kitchen.  

2079
03:30:38,880 --> 03:30:44,000
Spiro tried to get his fingers under the 
iron ring of the door but, hard as he tried,  

2080
03:30:44,000 --> 03:30:50,239
he could not move it. He and the child were 
gazing at the ring and scratching their heads  

2081
03:30:50,239 --> 03:30:56,479
when they became aware of a very big old man in a 
black suit, standing a little bent in the doorway.  

2082
03:30:57,760 --> 03:31:04,160
'What are you doing?' he asked. 'Oh, it's you, 
young Iannis. I thought you were looters.'

2083
03:31:05,200 --> 03:31:08,479
'We're trying to open this,' 
said the boy. 'It's stuck,  

2084
03:31:08,479 --> 03:31:10,479
and it's got something inside that we want.'

2085
03:31:11,439 --> 03:31:17,839
The old man came inside and examined the trapdoor 
with his watery eyes before slowly bending down  

2086
03:31:18,399 --> 03:31:22,080
and putting the tips of the fingers 
of one hand under the iron ring.  

2087
03:31:23,120 --> 03:31:29,120
He leaned sideways, putting all his weight and 
strength into lifting the ring and, with a sudden  

2088
03:31:29,120 --> 03:31:36,960
loud crack, the door flew upwards in a cloud 
of dust. Velisarios rubbed his hands together,  

2089
03:31:37,520 --> 03:31:43,201
blew on the tips of his fingers and seemed 
suddenly to become a tired old man again.  

2090
03:31:44,479 --> 03:31:50,399
'Goodbye, my friends,' he said, and made his 
way slowly down the path to the new village.

2091
03:31:52,000 --> 03:31:54,479
'Unbelievable,' said Spiro.

2092
03:31:55,840 --> 03:32:02,239
Inside the hiding-place, in perfect condition, 
they found an antique German record player,  

2093
03:32:02,880 --> 03:32:06,800
a handmade blanket, a bundle 
of papers written in Italian  

2094
03:32:07,359 --> 03:32:12,160
and another package of papers with the 
title, 'A Personal History of Cephallonia'.  

2095
03:32:13,279 --> 03:32:19,679
There was also a cloth bundle containing the 
most beautiful mandolin that Spiro had ever seen.

2096
03:32:21,120 --> 03:32:25,120
When Iannis showed Pelagia the 
mandolin, she started crying  

2097
03:32:25,840 --> 03:32:33,920
and, to Iannis's amazement, she did not stop for a 
whole week. Iannis comforted her as best he could,  

2098
03:32:33,920 --> 03:32:40,000
climbing on to her knees, which he was really 
a little too old for, and wiping her tears,  

2099
03:32:40,000 --> 03:32:45,520
wondering how it was possible to love an old 
woman with stiff knees and thin grey hair so much.  

2100
03:32:46,720 --> 03:32:51,920
While Iannis comforted Pelagia, Spiro 
carefully cleaned and polished the mandolin.  

2101
03:32:52,560 --> 03:32:58,320
He tightened and tuned each string and 
told Iannis, with great seriousness,  

2102
03:32:58,319 --> 03:33:03,840
that the mandolin was the most precious thing he 
would ever own, so that Iannis learned to regard  

2103
03:33:03,840 --> 03:33:09,360
the instrument with a respect that he had never 
felt in church, when dragged there by Pelagia.

2104
03:33:10,120 --> 03:33:11,120
***

2105
03:33:11,120 --> 03:33:18,319
In October 1993 Iannis was fourteen, and he had 
had a whole summer in which to play in public  

2106
03:33:18,319 --> 03:33:24,960
with Spiridon and have red roses thrown at him. 
In order not to annoy his grandmother with his  

2107
03:33:24,960 --> 03:33:30,960
constant practising - in fact not to make her cry 
again - he had gone up to the ruins of the old  

2108
03:33:30,960 --> 03:33:37,040
house to play in private, and was concentrating 
very hard on a particularly difficult piece of  

2109
03:33:37,040 --> 03:33:44,319
music. He was biting his lip with the effort, 
and did not notice an old man who approached him  

2110
03:33:44,319 --> 03:33:49,920
and watched him with critical but 
delighted interest. Iannis nearly  

2111
03:33:49,920 --> 03:33:56,880
jumped out of his seat when a voice said, in 
a very strange accent, 'Excuse me, young man.'

2112
03:33:57,520 --> 03:34:01,121
'Ah!' Iannis exclaimed. 'You frightened me.'

2113
03:34:02,160 --> 03:34:07,599
'I couldn't help noticing,' said the man, 
'that you are doing something wrong.'

2114
03:34:08,720 --> 03:34:15,280
'I know, I'm having trouble with this piece,' 
replied Iannis, noticing how unusually bright-eyed  

2115
03:34:15,279 --> 03:34:20,960
the old man was, and how there was about 
him an atmosphere of energy and laughter.

2116
03:34:22,000 --> 03:34:28,960
'Let me show you how to place your fingers.' The 
old man came over to Iannis and started to pull  

2117
03:34:28,960 --> 03:34:34,319
the boy's fingers into place, explaining 
as he did so why the fingers were better  

2118
03:34:34,319 --> 03:34:40,639
in this position. Then he stood upright and 
added, 'You can always tell a really good  

2119
03:34:40,640 --> 03:34:45,201
musician because a good musician doesn't 
seem to be moving his fingers at all.'

2120
03:34:46,080 --> 03:34:48,319
'You seem to know a lot about it,' said Iannis.

2121
03:34:48,880 --> 03:34:53,120
'Well, I ought to. I've been a 
professional mandolin player for  

2122
03:34:53,120 --> 03:34:57,120
nearly all my life. I can tell 
that you're going to be good.'

2123
03:34:58,399 --> 03:35:01,759
'Play me something?' asked the 
boy, offering him the mandolin.  

2124
03:35:02,640 --> 03:35:08,880
The old man took the mandolin, settled it into 
this body and began to play in such a way that  

2125
03:35:08,880 --> 03:35:16,960
Iannis's mouth fell open with amazement. Suddenly 
the old man stopped, turned the mandolin over,  

2126
03:35:17,600 --> 03:35:25,201
examined it with an expression of disbelief 
and exclaimed, 'Mother of God, it's Antonia.'

2127
03:35:26,720 --> 03:35:29,600
'How did you know it's called Antonia?'  

2128
03:35:30,319 --> 03:35:35,359
asked Iannis, both surprised and 
suspicious. 'Have you seen it before?'

2129
03:35:36,640 --> 03:35:39,360
'Where did you find it? Who gave it to you?'

2130
03:35:40,399 --> 03:35:44,319
'I dug it out of that hole,' said 
Iannis, pointing to the open trapdoor.  

2131
03:35:45,200 --> 03:35:46,639
'Grandma told me it was there.'

2132
03:35:47,920 --> 03:35:53,680
'And would your grandmother be Kyria 
Pelagia, daughter of Dr Iannis?'

2133
03:35:54,479 --> 03:35:57,120
'That's me. I'm called Iannis, after him.'

2134
03:35:58,319 --> 03:36:04,000
The old man sat next to the boy on the wall, 
still holding the mandolin, and wiped his  

2135
03:36:04,000 --> 03:36:07,760
forehead with a handkerchief, 
seeming suddenly very anxious.  

2136
03:36:09,200 --> 03:36:20,160
'Tell me, young man, is your grandmother 
alive? Is she happy?' he asked finally.

2137
03:36:20,160 --> 03:36:25,279
'She cries sometimes, ever since we dug Antonia 
and all the other things out of the hole.'

2138
03:36:26,640 --> 03:36:29,600
'And what about your grandfather? Is he well?'

2139
03:36:30,560 --> 03:36:34,880
The boy seemed confused. 
'What grandfather?' he asked.

2140
03:36:36,000 --> 03:36:40,479
'Not your father's father. I 
mean Kyria Pelagia's husband,'  

2141
03:36:40,479 --> 03:36:42,639
said the old man, wiping his forehead again.

2142
03:36:43,680 --> 03:36:46,480
'There isn't one. I didn't even know she had one.'

2143
03:36:47,680 --> 03:36:53,201
'Are you saying that Kyria Pelagia hasn't got 
a husband? You haven't got a grandfather?'

2144
03:36:54,160 --> 03:36:55,439
'I suppose I must have,  

2145
03:36:56,160 --> 03:37:01,760
but I've never heard of him. I've only got 
my father's father, and he's half-dead.'

2146
03:37:02,720 --> 03:37:10,880
The old man stood up, looked around him and said, 
'This was a beautiful place. I had the best years  

2147
03:37:10,880 --> 03:37:16,800
of my life here. And do you know what? I 
was going to marry your grandmother once.  

2148
03:37:18,080 --> 03:37:20,000
I think it's time I saw her again.'

2149
03:37:21,600 --> 03:37:25,360
The two of them were walking down the 
hill when Iannis stopped suddenly.  

2150
03:37:26,239 --> 03:37:32,160
'If you're the one who played the mandolin and was 
going to marry Grandma... does that mean you're  

2151
03:37:32,160 --> 03:37:44,160
the ghost?' The autumnal sun shone briefly through 
the cloud, and the old man paused for thought.
 
 
 

2152
03:37:44,160 --> 03:37:45,760
CHAPTER SEVENTEEN

2153
03:37:45,760 --> 03:37:46,320
The Return

2154
03:37:48,560 --> 03:37:55,280
Antonio Corelli, although in his seventies, 
rediscovered a certain youthful energy in his old  

2155
03:37:55,279 --> 03:38:01,599
limbs as he danced about, trying to avoid being 
hit by the frying pans that Pelagia was busily  

2156
03:38:01,600 --> 03:38:10,800
throwing at him. 'You pig!' she screamed. 'All my 
life waiting, all my life thinking you were dead.  

2157
03:38:10,800 --> 03:38:16,000
And you alive and me a fool. How can 
you break such promises? Betrayer!'

2158
03:38:17,359 --> 03:38:23,279
Corelli backed against the wall, trying to hold 
off the broomstick that Pelagia was waving at him.  

2159
03:38:23,279 --> 03:38:26,639
'I told you,' he cried. 'I 
thought you were married.'

2160
03:38:27,760 --> 03:38:32,239
'Married!' she exclaimed bitterly. 
'No such luck! Thanks to you,  

2161
03:38:32,239 --> 03:38:38,080
you rat.' She made a move as if she was going to 
hit him across the head with the broom handle.

2162
03:38:38,760 --> 03:38:43,280
'I came back for you. 1946. I came  

2163
03:38:43,279 --> 03:38:47,519
round the bend and there you were with 
the little baby, looking so happy.'

2164
03:38:48,160 --> 03:38:54,559
'Was I married? Who told you that? So I adopt 
a baby that someone leaves on my doorstep...  

2165
03:38:54,560 --> 03:38:58,960
Couldn't you have said, "Excuse 
me, but is this your baby?"'

2166
03:38:58,960 --> 03:39:04,399
'Please stop hitting me. I came back 
every year, you know I did. You saw me,  

2167
03:39:04,399 --> 03:39:11,839
I always saw you with the child. I was so 
bitter I couldn't speak. But I had to see you.'

2168
03:39:12,880 --> 03:39:16,640
'Bitter? I don't believe my ears. You? Bitter?'

2169
03:39:17,600 --> 03:39:24,800
'For ten years,' said Corelli, 'for ten years 
I was so bitter that I even wanted to kill you.  

2170
03:39:25,760 --> 03:39:33,120
And then I thought, well, OK, I was away for three 
years, perhaps she thought I wasn't coming back,  

2171
03:39:33,680 --> 03:39:37,680
perhaps she thought I was dead, 
perhaps she thought I'd forgotten,  

2172
03:39:37,680 --> 03:39:44,720
perhaps she met someone else and fell in love. 
As long as she's happy. But I still came back,  

2173
03:39:44,720 --> 03:39:49,840
every year, just to see you were 
all right. Is that betrayal?'

2174
03:39:50,720 --> 03:39:56,880
'And did you ever see a husband? And did you 
think what it did to me when I ran to you  

2175
03:39:56,880 --> 03:39:59,680
and you disappeared? Did 
you think about my heart?'

2176
03:40:00,800 --> 03:40:07,440
'OK, so I jumped the wall and hid. I had 
to. I thought you were married, I told you.  

2177
03:40:08,000 --> 03:40:12,319
Pelagia, please, this is a terrible 
embarrassment for the customers.  

2178
03:40:12,319 --> 03:40:14,960
Can't we go for a walk and 
talk about it on the beach?'

2179
03:40:16,399 --> 03:40:20,160
She looked round at all the 
faces, some of them grinning,  

2180
03:40:20,160 --> 03:40:22,160
some of them pretending to look the other way.  

2181
03:40:23,199 --> 03:40:28,720
Everywhere there were overturned chairs and tables 
that Pelagia had thrown to the floor in her anger.  

2182
03:40:29,760 --> 03:40:37,680
'You should have died,' she shouted, 'and left me 
with my dreams. You never loved me.' She marched  

2183
03:40:37,680 --> 03:40:44,160
out of the door, leaving Corelli bowing repeatedly 
to the customers and saying, 'Please excuse us.'

2184
03:40:45,760 --> 03:40:51,520
Two hours later they were sitting on a familiar 
rock, gazing out over the sea at the yellow lights  

2185
03:40:51,520 --> 03:40:58,240
of the harbour reflected in the blackened waters. 
'I see you got my postcards, then,' he said.

2186
03:40:59,279 --> 03:41:01,599
'In Greek. Why did you learn Greek?'

2187
03:41:02,560 --> 03:41:08,880
'I was ashamed of being an invader. I was so 
ashamed that I didn't want to be Italian any  

2188
03:41:08,880 --> 03:41:14,480
more. I've been living in Athens for about 
twenty-five years. I'm a Greek citizen.'

2189
03:41:15,439 --> 03:41:16,879
'Did you become a composer?'

2190
03:41:17,760 --> 03:41:24,080
'Yes, I've played my music all over the world. 
I wrote my first big piece of music for you.  

2191
03:41:24,640 --> 03:41:30,800
It's called "Pelagia's March".' He 
noticed that she was trying not to cry,  

2192
03:41:30,800 --> 03:41:37,440
and thought how emotional she had become in her 
old age. She had even knocked out his false teeth,  

2193
03:41:37,439 --> 03:41:41,839
so that they had fallen in the sand 
and had to be washed in the sea.

2194
03:41:43,760 --> 03:41:47,920
'I feel like an unfinished poem,' 
said Pelagia, with a heavy sigh.  

2195
03:41:49,199 --> 03:41:52,720
Corelli felt a sting of shame and avoided a reply.

2196
03:41:53,920 --> 03:41:58,319
'Everything's changed. Everything 
here used to be so pretty  

2197
03:41:58,319 --> 03:42:01,279
and now the houses look 
like boxes made of cement.'

2198
03:42:02,399 --> 03:42:07,359
'And we have electricity and telephones 
and running water and proper toilets  

2199
03:42:07,359 --> 03:42:11,040
and earthquake-resistant houses. Is that so bad?'

2200
03:42:12,399 --> 03:42:17,199
There was a silence, during which the 
thoughts of both of them returned to the past.  

2201
03:42:18,800 --> 03:42:21,760
'I see you still have my ring,' he said.

2202
03:42:22,960 --> 03:42:27,439
'Only because I couldn't get it off,' 
she answered. 'I had it altered to fit  

2203
03:42:27,439 --> 03:42:36,080
and now I regret it.' She hesitated. 'So 
did you get married? I suppose you did.'

2204
03:42:36,800 --> 03:42:44,720
'Me? No. As I said, I was very bitter for 
years and years. I was horrible to everyone,  

2205
03:42:44,720 --> 03:42:51,120
especially women, and then I became successful 
and I was all over the world, flying from one  

2206
03:42:51,120 --> 03:42:56,399
place to another. And, anyway, who wants to be 
with someone who is dreaming of someone else?'

2207
03:42:57,760 --> 03:43:03,120
'Antonio Corelli, I can see that you can 
still tell lies with your silver tongue.  

2208
03:43:03,920 --> 03:43:10,640
And how can you bear to look at me now? I'm an 
old woman. I feel ashamed to be so old and ugly.  

2209
03:43:11,439 --> 03:43:16,879
You look the same, just old and thin, 
but I look like someone else, I know it.  

2210
03:43:17,840 --> 03:43:22,000
I want you to remember me 
properly. Now I'm just a lump.'

2211
03:43:23,120 --> 03:43:30,160
'You forget that I came to spy on you. If you 
see things happen gradually, there's no shock.  

2212
03:43:30,160 --> 03:43:34,559
You're just the same.' He 
squeezed her hand gently and said,  

2213
03:43:35,279 --> 03:43:42,160
'Don't worry, it's still Pelagia. Pelagia 
with a bad temper, but still Pelagia.'

2214
03:43:43,920 --> 03:43:47,840
'Did you ever think that I might have 
been raped and that was why I had a baby?'

2215
03:43:48,800 --> 03:43:50,400
'Yes, I did.'

2216
03:43:51,359 --> 03:43:51,599
'And...?'

2217
03:43:53,040 --> 03:43:55,040
'I admit it made a difference.  

2218
03:43:56,080 --> 03:44:01,840
We had some ideas about dishonour then, 
didn't we? Thank God we're not so stupid now.'

2219
03:44:02,720 --> 03:44:05,840
'The man who tried to rape me... I shot him.'

2220
03:44:06,720 --> 03:44:09,840
He looked at her in disbelief. 'You shot him?'

2221
03:44:10,800 --> 03:44:15,279
'I was never dishonoured. He was 
the fiance I had before you.'

2222
03:44:16,399 --> 03:44:18,719
'You never said anything about a fiance.'

2223
03:44:19,600 --> 03:44:20,000
'Jealous?'

2224
03:44:20,640 --> 03:44:25,760
'Of course I'm jealous.' The emotion was 
beginning to stir him a little too much  

2225
03:44:26,319 --> 03:44:31,840
and he tried to control his feelings. Pelagia 
decided it was time to change the subject.  

2226
03:44:33,040 --> 03:44:37,439
'I want to show you something. You 
never read Carlo's papers, did you?  

2227
03:44:38,160 --> 03:44:44,399
Come back to the taverna and eat, and I'll give 
you his writing. We do an excellent snails dish.'

2228
03:44:45,040 --> 03:44:49,439
'Snails!' he exclaimed. 'I 
remember all about snails.'

2229
03:44:51,040 --> 03:44:56,399
Corelli sat at the table with its plastic cloth 
and read through the stiff old sheets that had  

2230
03:44:56,399 --> 03:45:03,519
curled up at the corners. As he read, he frowned, 
and once or twice he blinked as if in disbelief.  

2231
03:45:04,560 --> 03:45:10,480
When he had finished reading, Pelagia came 
and sat opposite him. 'Well?' she asked.

2232
03:45:11,439 --> 03:45:12,960
He tapped the pile of papers.  

2233
03:45:14,800 --> 03:45:21,120
'I wish you hadn't shown me these. I'm more 
old-fashioned than I thought. I had no idea.'

2234
03:45:22,399 --> 03:45:24,639
'He loved you. Are you disgusted?'

2235
03:45:25,520 --> 03:45:28,720
'Sad... It's a shock. I can't help it.'

2236
03:45:30,080 --> 03:45:36,000
'He wasn't just another hero, was he? 
He was more complicated. Poor Carlo.'

2237
03:45:37,600 --> 03:45:44,000
They began to talk more freely. 'Are 
you very famous then?' Pelagia asked.

2238
03:45:44,960 --> 03:45:47,840
'Only in the sense that other 
musicians have heard of me.  

2239
03:45:48,560 --> 03:45:51,600
I've retired now... In fact, I was thinking...  

2240
03:45:52,560 --> 03:45:58,800
I want to rebuild the old house. I want to 
live in a nice place. A place with memories.'

2241
03:46:00,160 --> 03:46:02,399
'Without water and electricity?'

2242
03:46:02,399 --> 03:46:05,599
'I'll put them in. Would you sell me the site?'

2243
03:46:06,239 --> 03:46:09,599
'You're insane. I don't even know if we own it.'

2244
03:46:10,720 --> 03:46:16,000
'Then you don't mind. I'd pay you to 
come and clean it,' he said wickedly.

2245
03:46:16,800 --> 03:46:22,000
She took him seriously. 'What? Do 
I need money? With this taverna?  

2246
03:46:22,000 --> 03:46:25,840
Go home to Athens. Anyway, Lemoni would do it.'

2247
03:46:26,560 --> 03:46:28,480
'Little Lemoni? She's still here?'

2248
03:46:29,040 --> 03:46:31,439
'She's as big as a ship and a grandmother.'

2249
03:46:32,560 --> 03:46:35,840
He fell silent again, 
remembering the past, then said,  

2250
03:46:37,279 --> 03:46:40,719
'So do I have your permission 
to rebuild the house?'

2251
03:46:41,600 --> 03:46:44,240
'No,' she said, still holding on to her anger.

2252
03:46:45,120 --> 03:46:51,599
'Oh.' He looked at her doubtfully. He would 
return to the topic at a later date, he decided.  

2253
03:46:52,880 --> 03:46:57,199
'I'm going to come and see you 
tomorrow,' he said, 'with a surprise.'

2254
03:46:58,160 --> 03:47:03,920
'I don't want any surprises. Go to hell 
with your surprises. You owe me a life.'

2255
03:47:03,920 --> 03:47:06,480
'Ah. I'll bring you a life then.'

2256
03:47:07,199 --> 03:47:08,479
'Stupid old man.'

2257
03:47:10,319 --> 03:47:16,960
He turned up the next day with screaming brakes 
in a cloud of blue smoke. Pelagia shook her head  

2258
03:47:16,960 --> 03:47:22,960
disapprovingly as he climbed carefully off the 
motorbike, which was bright red and looked as if  

2259
03:47:22,960 --> 03:47:29,600
it had been designed for racing. 'Do you know 
where we're going?' the captain said. 'We're  

2260
03:47:29,600 --> 03:47:35,520
going to see if Casa Nostra is still there...' 
he tapped the machine '... on a motorbike.'

2261
03:47:36,640 --> 03:47:39,360
'Do you really think the 
hut survived the earthquake?  

2262
03:47:39,920 --> 03:47:43,840
And do you really think I'm going 
on a thing like that? At my age?'

2263
03:47:44,640 --> 03:47:47,680
'I hired it specially. It goes very well.'

2264
03:47:48,560 --> 03:47:51,121
'No,' she said. 'My knees are too stiff.'

2265
03:47:52,160 --> 03:47:54,479
'Don't you want to see Casa Nostra?'

2266
03:47:55,439 --> 03:47:56,879
'Not with a madman.'

2267
03:47:57,920 --> 03:48:02,160
'I've got it for two days. We can 
sit on a rock and watch the sea.'  

2268
03:48:03,920 --> 03:48:09,680
It took a long time to persuade her. As they 
swung dangerously from side to side along  

2269
03:48:09,680 --> 03:48:15,360
the stony roads, she held on tightly to his 
waist, her face buried between his shoulders.  

2270
03:48:16,239 --> 03:48:22,319
Corelli noticed that she held on to him even more 
desperately than in the old days, and from time  

2271
03:48:22,319 --> 03:48:27,840
to time he deliberately swung to one side of 
the road so that she would hold him tighter.  

2272
03:48:29,439 --> 03:48:32,319
'May the saints save me,' thought Pelagia,  

2273
03:48:33,120 --> 03:48:41,840
and in search of safety slid her arms right round 
his waist and linked her fingers together.
 
 
 
 

2274
03:48:41,840 --> 03:48:42,481
- THE END -

